132004 (9 doubles, 1 mixed)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n\n===Ladies since 1884===\n! Record\n! Era\n! style=\"width:15em;\" | Player(s)\n! Count\n! Winning years\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Winner of most Ladies' Singles titles\n| Before 1968:\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Helen Wills Moody|Helen Wills]]\n| 8\n| 1927, 1928, 1929, 1930, 1932, 1933, 1935, 1938\n|-\n| Open Era:\n| {{flagicon|CZE}}/{{flagicon|USA}} [[Martina Navratilova]]\n| 9\n| 1978, 1979, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1985, 1986, 1987, 1990\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Winner of most consecutive Ladies' Singles titles\n| Before 1968:\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Suzanne Lenglen]]\n| 5\n| 1919, 1920, 1921, 1922, 1923\n|-\n| Open Era:\n| {{flagicon|CZE}}/{{flagicon|USA}} [[Martina Navratilova]]\n| 6\n| 1982, 1983, 1984, 1985, 1986, 1987\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Winner of most Ladies' Doubles titles\n| Before 1968:\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Elizabeth Ryan]]\n| 12\n| 1914 (with [[Agatha Morton]]), 1919, 1920, 1921, 1922, 1923, 1925 (with [[Suzanne Lenglen]]), 1926 (with [[Mary Browne]]), 1927, 1930 (with [[Helen Wills Moody|Helen Wills]]), 1933, 1934 (with [[Simonne Mathieu]])\n|-\n| Open Era:\n| {{flagicon|CZE}}/{{flagicon|USA}} [[Martina Navratilova]]\n| 7\n| 1976 (with [[Chris Evert]]), 1979 (with [[Billie Jean King]]), 1981, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986 (with [[Pam Shriver]])\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Winner of most consecutive Ladies' Doubles titles\n| Before 1968:\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Suzanne Lenglen]] <br /> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Elizabeth Ryan]]\n| 5\n| 1919, 1920, 1921, 1922, 1923\n|-\n| Open Era:\n|{{flagicon|CZE}}/{{flagicon|USA}} [[Martina Navratilova]] <br /> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Pam Shriver]]\n{{flagicon|URS}}/{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Natasha Zvereva]]\n| 4\n| 1981, 1982, 1983, 1984\n1991 (with [[Larisa Neiland]]), 1992, 1993, 1994 (with [[Gigi Fern\u00e1ndez]])\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Winner of most Mixed Doubles titles \u2013 ladies\n| Before 1968:\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Elizabeth Ryan]]\n| 7\n| 1919, 1921, 1923 (with [[Randolph Lycett]]), 1927 (with [[Francis Hunter|Frank Hunter]]), 1928 (with [[Patrick Spence]]), 1930 (with [[Jack Crawford (tennis)|Jack Crawford]]), 1932 (with [[Enrique Maier]])\n|-\n| Open Era:\n| {{flagicon|CZE}}/{{flagicon|USA}} [[Martina Navratilova]]\n| 4\n| 1985 (with [[Paul McNamee]]), 1993 (with [[Mark Woodforde]]), 1995 (with [[Jonathan Stark (tennis)|Jonathan Stark]]), 2003 (with [[Leander Paes]])\n|-\n|rowspan=3|Winner of most Championships (total: singles, doubles, mixed) \u2013 ladies\n| Before 1968:\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Elizabeth Ryan]]\n| 19\n| 1914\u201334 (12 doubles, 7 mixed)\n|-\n| Open Era:\n| {{flagicon|CZE}}/{{flagicon|USA}} [[Martina Navratilova]]\n| 20\n| 1976\u20132003 (9 singles, 7 doubles, 4 mixed)\n|-\n| Combined:\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Billie Jean King]]\n| 20\n| 1961\u201379 (6 singles, 10 doubles, 4 mixed)\n|}\n\n=== Miscellaneous ===\n[[File:Plaque on Wimbledon Court No. 18 to commemorate the longest match in tennis history between John Isner and Nicolas Mahut on 22-24 June 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Record plaque about the longest match ever played at Wimbledon]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Miscellaneous\n! Record\n! Player(s)\n! Count\n! Winning years\n|-\n|Match wins (men) singles\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Roger Federer]]\n|101\n|2001\u20132019 (open era)\n|-\n|Match wins (women) singles\n|{{flagicon|TCH}}/{{flagicon|USA}} [[Martina Navratilova]]\n|120\n|1973\u20132004 (open era)\n|-\n|Career match winning performance (men) singles\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Bj\u00f6rn Borg]]\n| 92.72% (51\u20134)\n|1973\u20131981 (open era)\n|-\n|Career match winning performance (women) singles\n| {{flagicon|FRG}} [[Steffi Graf]]\n| 90.36% (75\u20138)\n| 1984\u20131999 (open era)\n|-\n|Won title without losing a set (men) singles\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Hadow]] <br /> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Don Budge]] <br /> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Trabert]] <br /> {{flagicon|USA}} [[Chuck McKinley]] <br /> {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Bj\u00f6rn Borg]] <br /> {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Roger Federer]]\n| 18\u20130 <br /><br /> 21\u20130 <br /><br /><br /