emeteries, which have been partially excavated. \nSome gems found are in the archaeological Museum of Ioannina [6] .\n\n===Houses of Kassope===\nOne of the private houses (\"House\"), located northeast of Origin composed of a central courtyard to courtyard, the androna, the house with the kitchen, the baths and auxiliary areas. It was destroyed in 167 BC and repaired later drafts.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of cities in ancient Epirus]]\n\n==External links==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20160611190950/http://www.gtp.gr/TDirectoryDetails.asp?ID=14713\n\n{{coord|39|08|43|N|20|40|32|E|display=title|region:GR-PV_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 4th century BC]]\n[[Category:Cities in ancient Epirus]]\n[[Category:Populated places in ancient Epirus]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Greece]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Epirus (region)]]\n[[Category:Cities in ancient Greece]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cassope"}
{"title_page": "History of Celtic F.C. (1994\u2013present)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n\n[[File:Celtic park 5.jpg|thumb|right|170px]]\n[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic Football Club]] has always competed in the highest level of [[football in Scotland]], currently the [[Scottish Premiership]]. The club was constituted in 1887, and played its first game in 1888. Celtic play their home games at [[Celtic Park]] having moved there in 1892 from their original ground nearby.\n\nBy 1994, Celtic had endured several years of decline and were encountering difficulties on and off the park.  Expatriate businessman [[Fergus McCann]] wrested control of the club from the family dynasties that had run Celtic since its founding.  The club was reconstituted as a PLC and floated on the stock market, raising \u00a314&nbsp;million.  The finance provided funding for the rebuilding of Celtic Park into a 60,000 all-seated stadium, the largest football stadium in Scotland.\n\nThe team improved over the years that followed and in 1998 won the league title, their first championship success in ten years. The arrival of [[Martin O'Neill]] as manager in 2000 saw the club become one of two dominant forces in Scotland, winning three league titles in five years and reaching the [[2003 UEFA Cup Final|UEFA Cup Final in 2003]]. In [[2005\u201306 in Scottish football|2005\u201306]], Celtic's home games attracted an average attendance of 58,149, placing Celtic at the time behind only [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in terms of highest average attendance for any football club in the United Kingdom.\n\nCeltic are currently managed by [[Neil Lennon]], who was appointed on a permanent basis after his Scottish Cup victory over Hearts in May 2019, having earlier in the season taken over on a caretaker basis following [[Brendan Rodgers]]' departure from the club.\n\n==The Fergus McCann era (1994\u20131999)==\nThe [[Bank of Scotland]] informed Celtic on 3 March 1994 that it was calling in [[Receivership|receivers]] as a result of the club exceeding a \u00a35&nbsp;million [[overdraft]].<ref name=\"ssc1\">{{cite web|last=MacDonald|first=Hugh|title=The Saving of Celtic, Part One: David Low|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/the-saving-of-celtic-part-one-david-low.23570438|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=1 March 2014|date=1 March 2014}}</ref> Expatriate businessman [[Fergus McCann]], however, wrested control of the club from the family dynasties which had controlled Celtic since its founding,<ref name=\"ssc1\" /> purchasing the club for a reported \u00a39&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=s9_2|title=Celtic FC Team Profile|publisher=Scottish Premier League|accessdate=23 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314003846/http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=s9_2|archive-date=14 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>  According to media reports, McCann took over the club minutes before it was to be declared [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]].<ref name=\"ssc1\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/6469284/Celtic-chairman-John-Reid-pledges-to-keep-the-clubs-finances-under-control.html |title=Celtic chairman John Reid pledges to keep the club's finances under control |work=The Telegraph |date=30 October 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2011 |first=Roddy |last=Forsyth}}</ref><ref name=\"Celticseer\">{{cite news |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/spl/Fergus-the-Celtic-seer.2507591.jp |title=Fergus the Celtic seer |work=The Scotsman |date=29 February 2004 |accessdate =23 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/new-celtic-team-takes-over-three-directors-ousted-as-17-8m-rescue-package-pledged-the-new-team-takes-over-with-a-promise-1.717089 |title= New Celtic team takes over. Three directors ousted as #17.8m rescue package pledged. The new team takes over with a promise |work=Herald Scotland |date=5 March 1994 |accessdate =23 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt this time, the club was an estimated \u00a37&nbsp;million in debt and attendances at Parkhead frequently dipped below 20,000.<ref name=\"dm0103\">{{cite news|last=McGarry|first=John|title=McCann:20 Years On; Covert operations in a great rebellion|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=1 March 2014|pages=106\u2013107}}</ref> The old board had insisted on a limit of only 7,000 season tickets, on the basis that \"season tickets are more trouble than they're worth\".<ref name=\"scot1\">{{cite web|last=Gibbons|first=Glenn|title=No point in McCann/Rangers parallel|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/glenn-gibbons-no-point-in-mccann-rangers-parallel-1-3307232|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=15 February 2014|date=15 February 2014}}</ref> Shortly prior to the takeover, the club was only valued at around \u00a320,000 due the [[Common stock#Ordinary shares|ordinary shares]] being artificially valued at \u00a31 each and the regulations of the [[Private company limited by shares|private limited]] company which decreed that shares could only be traded with the permission of the directors, who had first refusal on any that became available.<ref name=\"scot1\" />  Most significantly, the shares were not allowed to \"float\" to their true value, as a result of which directors were able to purchase them for around \u00a33 each. Bulk holders such as [[Michael Kelly (Lord Provost)|Michael Kelly]], Chris White and David Smith insisted on being paid around \u00a3300 per share, leaving McCann resentful over the disappearance of funds that could have been used in the resuscitation of the business.<ref name=\"ssc1\" /><ref name=\"scot1\" />\n\nIn order to alleviate the club's debt, McCann reconstituted the then [[Limited company|privately owned]] Celtic Football & Athletic Company Limited into a [[public limited company]] \u2013 Celtic PLC. To finance this restructuring, McCann set up a share issue which generated \u00a314&nbsp;million, one of the most successful [[Initial public offering|stock market flotations]] in British financial history.<ref name=\"ssc1\" /><ref name=\"Celticseer\" /><ref name=\"McCannAttack\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/4772870/McCann-on-the-attack-over-Celtic-criticism.html |title=McCann on the attack over Celtic criticism |work=The Telegraph |date=3 October 2000 |accessdate=23 September 2011 |first=Andrew |last=Lomax}}</ref>\n\n===Tommy Burns spell===\n[[File:Airdriecelticcupfinal.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Celtic playing against Airdrie in the 1995 Scottish Cup Final; this was their first trophy since 1989]]\nOn the playing side, manager [[Lou Macari]] was sacked by McCann and replaced in the summer of 1994 by former Celtic player [[Tommy Burns (footballer)|Tommy Burns]], with [[Billy Stark]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reynolds|first=Jim|title=As Celtic doors reopen, another looks set to close. Burns' continuing reshuffle now leaves Grimes in limbo|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/as-celtic-doors-reopen-another-looks-set-to-close-burns-continuing-reshuffle-now-leaves-grimes-in-limbo-1.492898|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=23 July 1994}}</ref> Former player and manager [[Davie Hay]] also returned to the club, as chief scout.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paul|first=Ian|title=Hay will be chief scout at Celtic|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/hay-will-be-chief-scout-at-celtic-1.493228|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=21 July 1994}}</ref> Celtic played their home games at [[Hampden Park]] in the first season under the new regime due to the redevelopment of Celtic Park.<ref>{{cite web|title=NOW YOU KNOW: No Hampden home comforts for Hoops|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/other-football/now-you-know-no-hampden-home-comforts-for-hoops-125825n.21212636|work=Evening Times|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=30 May 2013}}</ref> Celtic were poor in the league that season, but managed to win their first trophy in six years when they defeated [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrie]] 1\u20130 in the [[1995 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup Final]] on 27 May 1995.<ref name=\"cup95\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/celtics-compensation-1621393.html?CMP=ILC-refresh |work=The Independent |first=Simon |last=O'Hagan |title=Celtic's compensation |date=28 May 1995}}</ref> The winning goal was scored by Dutch striker [[Pierre van Hooijdonk]], who had been signed several months earlier from [[NAC Breda]] for \u00a31.2&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"cup95\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Celebration again as Dutch recall striker Hooydonk|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celebration-again-as-dutch-recall-striker-hooydonk-1.699671|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=13 January 1995}}</ref>\n\nThe following season saw Celtic return to their home ground at Celtic Park. Former East German international striker [[Andreas Thom]] was signed over the summer for a then club record fee of \u00a32.2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/celtic-break-club-record-to-sign-thom-1593811.html |title=Celtic break club record to sign Thom |work=The Independent |date=29 July 1995 |accessdate=5 August 2013 |first=Guy |last=Hodgson}}</ref> During the pre-season, defender [[Tony Mowbray]] persuaded his teammates to engage in a pre-match [[huddle]] prior to a friendly against German side [[Kickers Emden]] in an effort to boost the players' camaraderie and togetherness.<ref name=\"mhuddle\">{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=David|title=Tony Mowbray: The big bruising Celtic defender with an eye for the beautiful game|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/tony-mowbray-the-big-bruising-celtic-1027725|work=Daily Record|accessdate=10 July 2014|date=17 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tony Mowbray - Welcome To Celtic Football Club|url=http://www.ballymenashamrockcsc.com/?q=node/48|publisher=Ballymena Shamrock Celtic Supporters Club|accessdate=10 July 2014|date=18 June 2009}}</ref>  Although Mowbray would leave the club several weeks later, the pre-match huddle remains a constant ritual that is performed by Celtic players to this day prior to every game.<ref name=\"mhuddle\" />  Tommy Burns' second season saw him successfully restore a more attacking style of play to the side.  The new strike pairing of Van Hooijdonk and Thom forged an accomplished partnership up front.  The midfield duo of [[Paul McStay]] and [[John Collins (footballer, born 1968)|John Collins]] were integral to Celtic's attractive football and [[Jackie McNamara]] and [[Simon Donnelly]] won praise for their link-up play on the right. Celtic only lost one league match during the 1995\u201396 season, but for all the plaudits they received, they remained unable to prevent [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] from winning an eighth-straight league title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic's Nearly Men|url=http://www.scotzine.com/oor-football-years/celtics-nearly-men/|work=Scotzine|accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, the club was under pressure to invest heavily in playing talent \u2013 particularly from the fans \u2013 to thwart Rangers' attempts to equal and surpass the nine-in-a-row record Celtic held.<ref name=\"ssc1\" /> McCann was often criticised by the fans and media for his perceived frugality,<ref name=\"ssc1\" /> but further signings were made in 1996, with Portuguese striker [[Jorge Cadete]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Traynor|first=James|title=Message is clear that there's a new kid on the block|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/message-is-clear-that-there-s-a-new-kid-on-the-block-1.459085|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=2 April 1996}}</ref> and Italian winger [[Paolo Di Canio]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Di Canio joins Celtic in #3m deal|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/di-canio-joins-celtic-in-3m-deal-1.452648|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=1 June 1996}}</ref> arriving at Celtic Park.\n\nThe 1996\u201397 season saw Tommy Burns under intense media scrutiny and pressure from the supporters as Rangers closed in on their ninth successive league title. Despite Van Hooijdonk, Cadete and Di Canio having outstanding seasons as individual players, Celtic struggled to match the form of the previous season. John Collins had left for [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in the summer<ref name = \"bosman\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/FRANCS%3B+FOR%3B+NOTHING%3B+Celtic+in+French+farce+over+Collins+fee+CHEEKY!-a061314116|title=Francs For Nothing|first=Jim|last=Rodger|work=Daily Mirror|date=25 July 1996|accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref> and Paul McStay was toiling with injury. As a result, individual performances were unable to make up for the lack of overall team coherence and Celtic finished the season trophy-less, with Rangers winning their [[History of Rangers F.C.#Nine in a row|ninth successive league title]] and equalling Celtic's record set under Jock Stein.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers wins 9th successive Scottish title|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=rangers-wins-9th-successive-scottish-title-1997-05-09|work=Daily News|accessdate=2 March 2014|date=9 May 1997}}</ref>\n\nMcCann found himself embroiled in contractual disputes with the trio of Van Hooijdonk, Cadete and Di Canio, labelling them the \"Three Amigos\".<ref>{{cite news|title=McCann: I had to run 'Three Amigos' out of town|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/McCANN%3A+I+HAD+TO+RUN+THREE+AMIGOS+OUT+OF+TOWN.-a060751699|accessdate=16 December 2013|newspaper=Sunday Mail|date=1 November 1998}}</ref> McCann refused to cave in to what he considered the excessive demands of these foreign mercurial talents and, to the frustration of fans, the three each left the club under a cloud, albeit for large transfer fees.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fletcher|first=Rob|title=Whatever happened to Pierre van Hooijdonk|url=http://www.footballfancast.com/football-blogs/whatever-happened-to-pierre-van-hooijdonk|work=FootballFanCast|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=14 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jorge Cadete: the former Celtic striker who lost everything|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jan/29/jorge-cadete-portugal-celtic-state-benefits|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=29 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Di Canio\u2019s Celtic years: good, bad and ugly|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/di-canio-s-celtic-years-good-bad-and-ugly-1-3106641|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nWith just three weeks left of the 1996\u201397 season, Burns was sacked, with the club's remaining coaching staff also leaving at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Paul|first1=Ian|last2=Sinclair|first2=Paul|title=Burns is finally out The 'amicable' parting is not appreciated by more than 2000 angry fans outside Parkhead as even the manager has a police escort to leave|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/burns-is-finally-out-the-amicable-parting-is-not-appreciated-by-more-than-2000-angry-fans-outside-parkhead-as-even-the-manager-has-a-police-escort-to-leave-1.400268|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=2 March 2014|date=3 May 1997}}</ref> Various names were touted in the media as being likely to take over, however McCann made a surprising choice in Dutch coach [[Wim Jansen]]. Furthermore, it was announced that the traditional [[Manager (association football)|manager]]'s position at Celtic had been abolished, with the responsibilities to be split between the new roles of a [[Coach (sport)#Football|head coach]] (Jansen) who would deal with coaching, tactics and team selection, and a [[Director of football|general manager]] to deal with contracts and general administration duties.<ref name=\"misc9700\">{{cite book|last1=White|first1=John|title=The Celtic Football Miscellany|date=2006|publisher=Carlton Books|isbn=978-1844421626|page=122|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Celtic-Football-Miscellany-John-White/dp/1844421627/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1493155491&sr=1-1&keywords=9781844421626|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> The office of the general manager was somewhat controversially taken up by solicitor and former TV football commentator [[Jock Brown]].<ref name=\"JockB\">{{cite web|last=Oliver|first=Gary|title=Celtic cross|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/30-Clubs/6033-celtic-cross|work=When Saturday Comes|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>  [[Davie Hay]] was promoted from his scouting role to Assistant General Manager, whilst former Celtic player [[Murdo MacLeod]] was appointed as assistant coach to Jansen.\n\n===League title under Jansen===\nThe summer of 1997 saw substantial changes to Celtic's playing personnel.  Scottish internationalists [[Darren Jackson]] and [[Craig Burley]] were Jansen's first signings, closely followed by Dutch winger [[Regi Blinker]], Danish centre-half [[Marc Rieper]] and, more significantly, Swedish attacker [[Henrik Larsson]] from [[Feyenoord]] in a \u00a3650,000 deal.  [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]] reserve goalkeeper [[Jonathan Gould]] also arrived at Celtic Park in a low-key transfer deal. Club captain [[Paul McStay]], however, retired from playing that summer due to injury, after a playing career of 15 years and 678 appearances for the club.<ref>{{cite web|first=Graham |last=Spiers |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/still-the-modest-maestro-paul-mcstay-a-member-of-the-last-celtic-side-to-taste-victory-over-rangers-at-ibrox-in-1994-talks-to-graham-spiers-1.189683 |title=Still the modest maestro Paul McStay, a member of the last Celtic side to taste victory over Rangers at Ibrox, in 1994, talks to Graham Spiers |work=Herald Scotland |date=28 April 2001 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nRangers started the 1997\u201398 season as strong favourites for the league title and had themselves invested heavily over the summer in new players.  Celtic made a poor start to the season, losing their first two league matches, but soon began to find their feet.  Marc Rieper and [[Alan Stubbs]] quickly formed an impressive understanding in central defence,<ref>{{cite web|title=Player Profile - Alan Stubbs|url=http://www.toffeeweb.com/players/profiles/Stubbs.asp|publisher=Toffee Web|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> while Craig Burley proved to be a revelation in midfield with his energetic play and important goals. Jonathan Gould became the team's first choice goalkeeper and had an excellent season. Henrik Larsson had made an uninspiring start at Celtic, gifting [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]'s [[Chic Charnley]] the winning goal through a careless pass on his debut and then scoring an own-goal in a [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] tie (Celtic still triumphed 6\u20133 on the night and won on aggregate). The Swede, however, soon established himself as a pivotal player in the side,<ref>{{cite web|title=Larsson favourite to be player of year|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/larsson-favourite-to-be-player-of-year-1.352388|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=27 February 1998}}</ref> at this time playing just off the main strikers.\n\nAn injury time equaliser from Alan Stubbs in November 1997 against Rangers saw Celtic remain behind the Ibrox club in the league, but stay within reaching distance. The next Old Firm encounter at New Year saw Celtic win 2\u20130 with goals from Craig Burley and recent signing from [[Borussia Dortmund]], [[Paul Lambert]].  Over the following months, Celtic and Rangers each had spells at the top of the table,<ref>{{cite web|last=Gallacher|first=Ken|title=Now the title race tension swings back on to Celtic|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/now-the-title-race-tension-swings-back-on-to-celtic-1.347269|work=Hearld Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=13 April 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Broadley|first=Ian|title=Aberdeen ease relegation fears to leave Celtic three points clear of Rangers Defiant Smith not ready to surrender league title|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/aberdeen-ease-relegation-fears-to-leave-celtic-three-points-clear-of-rangers-defiant-smith-not-ready-to-surrender-league-title-1.346641|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=20 April 1998}}</ref> and as the season reached its climax, both sides dropped unexpected points as nerves took hold.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spiers|first=Graham|title=Celtic stunned by nerve gas Hibs deliver assured display to preserve a sliver of hope|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1998-04-25%3A+Celtic+0-0+Hibernian,+Premier+Division|accessdate=16 December 2013|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|date=26 April 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Killie Halt Rangers 10 In A Row Bid!|url=http://www.killiefc.com/Classic%20Matches/020598-Rangers%20(SPL).htm|publisher=KillieFC.com|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>  Celtic eventually clinched the league title win a 2\u20130 win over [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] on the last day of the season, their first championship title in ten years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/90174.stm |title=Celtic get by with a little help from their Scandinavians |work=BBC Sport |date=9 May 1998 |accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nDespite the triumph, the title-winning celebrations soon soured when Wim Jansen made good his long held threat to resign,<ref>{{cite web|last=Paul|first=Ian|title=Jansen controversy is played down by Celtic|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/jansen-controversy-is-played-down-by-celtic-1.349198|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=25 March 1998}}</ref> after difficulties working with Jock Brown and Fergus McCann.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Phil|title=Jansen had 'no future' at Celtic|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-jansen-had-no-future-at-celtic-1159706.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=12 May 1998}}</ref> Jansen resigned just two days after the club sealed the title, with Brown widely portrayed as the villain of the piece.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jansen 'wanted to quit Celtic after two weeks'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/91468.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=12 May 1998}}</ref> Davie Hay had been controversially sacked by Brown earlier in the season<ref>{{cite news|title=Jock forced me out; Davie Hay exclusive|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/JOCK+FORCED+ME+OUT%3B+Davie+Hay+exclusive.-a060757458|accessdate=17 December 2013|newspaper=Sunday Mail|date=11 January 1998}}</ref> and Jansen's assistant, Murdo MacLeod, was sacked a week after Jansen's resignation.<ref name=\"JockB\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Robertson|first=Rob|title=It's MacLeod's turn to be a Parkhead casualty|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/it-s-macleod-s-turn-to-be-a-parkhead-casualty-1.340940|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=5 June 1998}}</ref>\n\n===Venglo\u0161 spell===\nA number of high-profile names were proferred as the replacement for Jansen, but the man eventually appointed by Celtic was Slovakian [[Jozef Venglo\u0161]]. Many fans, swayed doubtless by the local media, were disappointed and angry at the decision, citing  Venglo\u0161' poor record whilst in charge of English club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] some years before.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Madeley|first1=Gavin|title=Celtic pick new coach out of the blue |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celtic-pick-new-coach-out-of-the-blue-1.335554|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=18 July 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Broadfoot|first1=Darryl|title=Celtic deny that Slovakian's appointment is a panic move after Houllier snub Venglos takes hot seat |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celtic-deny-that-slovakian-s-appointment-is-a-panic-move-after-houllier-snub-venglos-takes-hot-seat-1.335641|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=18 July 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Shields|first1=Tom|title=Fans ask: Doctor Who?|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/fans-ask-doctor-who-1.335651|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=18 July 1998}}</ref> Following early exits in the [[UEFA Champions League]], UEFA Cup and [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]], and a poor start to their league campaign,<ref name=\"JBq\">{{cite news|title=Brown quits Parkhead|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/scottish_premier/209621.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=7 November 1998}}</ref> Celtic and Venglo\u0161 were subject to intense media scrutiny. The lack of players signed during the close season was one area in which the club were strongly criticised for.<ref name=\"JockB\" />  Amidst the almost constant negative publicity surrounding the club, Jock Brown resigned in November 1998.<ref name=\"JBq\" />\n\nPlayers did, however, begin to arrive in the late autumn: Norwegian defender [[Vidar Riseth]], Swedish defensive midfielder [[Johan Mj\u00e4llby]], Slovakian play-maker [[\u013dubom\u00edr Morav\u010d\u00edk]] and Australian striker [[Mark Viduka]] all joined. Following this, Celtic's fortunes began to turn when they won 5\u20131 against Rangers, Larsson and Morav\u010d\u00edk both scoring twice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tonic for Doctor Jo|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1998-11-21%3A+Celtic+5-1+Rangers,+PremierLeague|accessdate=29 January 2014|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|date=22 November 1998}}</ref>\n\nVenglo\u0161 now had Celtic playing good football and his deployment of Larsson as an out-and-out striker was proving to be a huge success, with the Swede eventually going  on to score 38 goals that season. The signing of Lubomir Morav\u010d\u00edk had initially been ridiculed by the Scottish media, but the Slovakian's skills soon won the doubters over.<ref>{{cite book|last=Purden|first=Richard|title=Faithful Through and Through|year=2013|publisher=Hachette Scotland}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Charles|first=Sean|title=Stars of the Past: Lubomir Moracvik|url=http://www.footandball.net/stars-of-the-past-lubomir-moracvik/|work=Foot and Ball|accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref>  Celtic rallied in the league but were still unable to prevent Rangers from winning the championship. Defeat in the [[1999 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup final]], also against Rangers, only confirmed the club's lack of progress on the field.<ref>{{cite news |last=Spiers|first=Graham|title=It's treble Advocaat|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1999-05-29%3A+Celtic+0-1+Rangers%2C+Scottish+Cup+Final|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|accessdate=30 January 2015|date=30 May 1999}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Celtic Park New.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The redeveloped Celtic Park - a 60,832 capacity stadium]]\nShortly after the end of the season, Venglo\u0161 resigned on health grounds but remained as an advisor and European scout for the club for a brief period.<ref>{{cite web|title=Venglos to leave Celtic?|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/venglos-to-leave-celtic-26152292.html|work=The Independent (Ireland)|accessdate=30 January 2015|date=5 April 1999}}</ref><ref name=\"drjoz\">{{cite book|publisher=lulu.com|last=Ross|first=David|title=Gaffers|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3FBuAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA602&lpg=PA602&dq=venglos+leave+celtic&source=bl&ots=EbARPDf4tb&sig=xk7AdfHIm0VAzFwjy_3rlPKuKr0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mtbLVKWXLcT6UOOtgfAD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=venglos%20leave%20celtic&f=false|accessdate=30 January 2015|page=602|isbn=978-1470927103}}</ref>  Although his tenure as head coach was strained, Venglo\u0161 is generally fondly regarded by fans, in particular for the signing of Morav\u010d\u00edk.<ref name=\"drjoz\" />\n\nIn March 1999, [[Scottish Football Association]] (SFA) Chief Executive [[Jim Farry]] was fired as a result of him deliberately delaying the registration of Jorge Cadete in 1996. The delay resulted in Cadete missing several matches for Celtic he could have played in, in particular a Scottish Cup semi-final tie against Rangers which Celtic lost 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|title=SFA boss suspended|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/288283.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 December 2013|date=1 March 1999}}</ref>  Fergus McCann had complained about the matter initially to the SFA and then to an independent commission, who subsequently found Farry guilty of gross misconduct.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ian|last=Paul |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/fergus-finishes-farry-mccann-leaves-sfa-no-option-1.303362 |title=Fergus finishes Farry McCann leaves SFA no option |work=Herald Scotland |date=2 March 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Farry was sacked days after the commission's findings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/292088.stm |title=Farry sacked by SFA |work=BBC Sport |date=8 March 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn taking over Celtic in 1994, Fergus McCann stated that he would be only be at the club for five years.  In September 1999, he officially announced that his majority stake in Celtic was for sale.<ref name=\"McCannSellshare\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/452152.stm |title=McCann sells Celtic shares |work=BBC Scotland |date=20 September 1999 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> By this time, the redevelopment of Celtic Park into a 60,000 all-seated capacity stadium was complete, at a cost of \u00a340&nbsp;million.,<ref name=\"Celticseer\" /><ref name=\"McCannSellshare\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/scottish_premier/341197.stm |title=Kerr's Ceaucescu jibe at McCann |work=BBC Sport |date=11 May 1999 |accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> and the club had 53,000 season ticket holders.<ref name=\"scot1\" />  The club was now a successful business and the team vastly improved from when he took over in 1994.  McCann sold his shares for \u00a340&nbsp;million, making a profit of \u00a331&nbsp;million on his initial investment.<ref name=\"McCannSellshare\" />  After McCann's exit, Irish billionaire [[Dermot Desmond]] was left as the largest shareholder, with a 20% stake in the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/markets-lift-on-back-of-takeover-bids-397912.html |title=Markets lift on back of takeover bids |work=The Independent (Ireland)|date=25 September 1999 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> Allan MacDonald was appointed chief executive/managing director.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sinclair|first=Paul|title=Football: Fergus: my time at Celtic is over|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+Fergus%3A+my+time+at+Celtic+is+over.-a060419686|accessdate=1 February 2016|work=Daily Record|date=2 April 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Martin O'Neill (1999\u20132005)==\n\n===Barnes & Dalglish===\nThe [[1999\u20132000 Celtic F.C. season|1999\u20132000 season]] is widely considered one of the biggest disasters in the club's history. [[Kenny Dalglish]] returned to the club to fill the General Manager's post (which had been vacant since the departure of Jock Brown), while the head coach position was filled by former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[England national football team|England]] player [[John Barnes (footballer)|John Barnes]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Phil|last=Gordon |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-celtic-send-for-dalglish-and-barnes-1099459.html |title=Football: Celtic send for Dalglish and Barnes - Sport |work=The Independent |date=11 June 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarnes had never managed a professional club, and the fans' worst fears were realised when Celtic's title challenge drastically faltered shortly after the winter break. Following a series of poor results \u2013 including elimination from the UEFA Cup and a broken leg away against [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] for Henrik Larsson<ref>{{cite news|first=Simon|last=Buckland|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/fears-for-larssons-future-after-broken-leg-nightmare-26136099.html |title=Fears for Larsson's future after broken leg nightmare |work=The Independent (Ireland)|date=22 October 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/505289.stm |title=Celts fail to tame Lyon challenge |work=BBC Sport|date=4 November 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> \u2013 Rangers increased their lead at the top of the [[Scottish Premier League]] table and demands for Barnes to be sacked began.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moore |first=Glenn |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/dalglish-rallies-behind-celtic-coach-barnes-742841.html |title=Dalglish rallies behind Celtic coach Barnes - Scottish - Football |work=The Independent |date=4 December 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20051013/celtic-v-hearts_2241541_725930 |title=Celtic v Hearts - Memorable Matches - Celtic 2 Hearts 3 |publisher=Heartsfc.co.uk |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112192702/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20051013/celtic-v-hearts_2241541_725930 |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"fanp\">{{cite web|first1=Chris|last1=Starrs|first2=William|last2=Tinning |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/fans-in-protest-as-caley-humble-celtic-1.249919 |title=Fans in protest as Caley humble Celtic |work=Herald Scotland |date=9 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 2000, Celtic hosted a rearranged Scottish Cup tie at home to [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]. Caley Thistle were an in-form side, fourth-placed in Division 1, although only in the Scottish Football League since 1994. Nevertheless, the match was still widely expected to be an easy victory for Celtic. However, Caley Thistle won the match 3\u20131 in one of the biggest Scottish Cup upsets ever,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/636000.stm |title=Caley's minnows slay Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=8 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> which sparked a protest involving over a hundred Celtic fans outside the stadium.<ref name=\"fanp\" /> The memorable headline in ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper the following day read: \"[[Supercalifragilisticexpialidocious#Other references|Super Caley Go Ballistic, Celtic Are Atrocious]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://supercaleygoballistic.com/2012/01/09/hello-world/ |title=Who Was the Super Caley Sub? |publisher=supercaleygoballistic |date=9 January 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529150051/http://supercaleygoballistic.com/2012/01/09/hello-world/ |archivedate=29 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Having refused to speak to the press after the match, Barnes held a press conference the next day, and implied that a dispute between him and Mark Viduka at half-time had badly unsettled the team and been responsible for the defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/636105.stm |title=Celtic chief plans 'full review' |work=BBC News |date=9 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Barnes was sacked the following morning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/637415.stm |title=Barnes forced out |work=BBC News |date=10 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nKenny Dalglish took over as head coach until the end of the season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/638554.stm |title=Dalglish aims to steady Celtic ship |work=BBC News |date=11 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and brought Tommy Burns back to assist him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/other-sports/tommy-burns-was-one-of-celtics-greatest-977594 |title=Tommy Burns was one of Celtic's greatest, says Scotland legend Kenny Dalglish |work=Daily Record |date=17 May 2008 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> While Dalglish generally retained the respect of the supporters, Celtic's league form deteriorated further and the club finished 21 points behind Rangers at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/1999-2000/table |title=Scottish Premier League 1999-2000 Table |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112190945/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/1999-2000/table |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A League Cup final victory over [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] was the only consolation in one of the most embarrassing periods of the club's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+DALGLISH+LIFTED+BY+CUP+WIN%3B+Celtic+2+Aberdeen+0.-a060293157 |title=Dalglish lifted by Cup win; Celtic 2 Aberdeen 0 |work=The Mirror |date=20 March 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===The arrival of O'Neill===\nFollowing the sacking of John Barnes, [[Guus Hiddink]] emerged as Celtic chief executive Alan MacDonald's initial choice to take over as manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/733476.stm |title=Celtic struggle to tempt Hiddink |work=BBC News |date=2 May 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  However, Hiddink's apparent lack of interest in the Celtic post<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+HIDDINK+DEAL+IN+DANGER%3B+Delays+cast+doubt+over+Guus+move.-a062047071 |title=HIDDINK DEAL IN DANGER; Delays cast doubt over Guus move |work=Daily Record |date=12 May 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> and the intervention of majority shareholder [[Dermot Desmond]] saw [[Leicester City]] manager [[Martin O'Neill]] come to the fore as the club's primary target.<ref>{{cite web|last=McHugh|first=Joe|title=Coyle, Moyes and Mowbray touted as Hoops power broker eyes up Strachan's successor|url=http://www.herald.ie/sport/soccer/coyle-moyes-and-mowbray-touted-as-hoops-power-broker-eyes-up-strachans-successor-27912944.html|work=The Herald (Ireland)|accessdate=22 October 2013|date=26 May 2009}}</ref>  \n \n[[File:O'Neill, Martin.jpg|180px|thumb|left|Martin O'Neill]]\n[[Martin O'Neill]] \u2013 from [[Kilrea]], [[Northern Ireland]], a former European Cup winner in his playing days with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] \u2013 arrived at the club in the wake of the Barnes/Dalglish fiasco in June 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/769394.stm |title=Celtic win O'Neill tussle |work=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> O'Neill took full charge of all team matters, effectively re-establishing the traditional role of \"manager\" at Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kerr|first=Thomas|title=Dalglish set to leave post at Celtic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jun/07/newsstory.sport|work=The Guardian|accessdate=19 December 2013|date=7 June 2000}}</ref> With the \"general manager\" role now redundant, Dalglish was sacked by Celtic at the end of June.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Dalglish hits out over messy Celtic divorce|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/4754679/Dalglish-hits-out-over-messy-Celtic-divorce.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 December 2013|date=30 June 2000}}</ref>\n\nOver the summer, O'Neill bought [[Chris Sutton]] from [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for a club record \u00a36&nbsp;million, while Mark Viduka moved south to join [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/829023.stm |title=O'Neill secures Sutton |work=BBC Sport |date=11 July 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Belgian international centre-half [[Joos Valgaeren]] also arrived in the summer in a bid by O'Neill to shore up a porous Celtic defence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/848828.stm |title=Joos boost for Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=28 July 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nO'Neill's signings quickly settled in at Celtic; Sutton scored the winning goal on the first of the day of the season in a 2\u20131 win over [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/858625.stm |title=Celtic new boys off to winning start |work=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> while Valgaeren linked up well with Alan Stubbs and Tom Boyd in the centre of defence.  Further players arrived over the course of 2000\u201301; left-sided midfielder [[Alan Thompson (footballer, born 1973)|Alan Thompson]] was signed from Aston Villa,<ref>{{cite news|first=Jon |last=Brodkin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/sep/02/newsstory.sport6 |title=O'Neill gets his man as Thompson signs for Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=2 September 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> the pacy [[Didier Agathe]] arrived from Hibernian,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://celticjournal.org/2031/exclusive-didier-agathe-interview/ |title=Exclusive: Didier Agathe Interview |work=Celtic Journal |date=15 June 2013 |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726195358/http://celticjournal.org/2031/exclusive-didier-agathe-interview/ |archivedate=26 July 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> centre-half [[Ramon Vega]] headed north on loan from [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/1073543.stm |title=Celtic hit Dons for six |work=BBC Sport |date=17 December 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> goalkeeper [[Robert Douglas (footballer)|Rab Douglas]] was signed up from Dundee and midfielder [[Neil Lennon]] was signed from O'Neill's old club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ley |first=John |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/2994143/Lennon-realises-dream-to-join-his-idols-Celtic.html |title=Lennon realises dream to join his idols Celtic |work=The Telegraph |date=7 December 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  That season saw Celtic go on to win their first domestic treble since 1969, winning the League, Scottish Cup and League Cup. O'Neill became only the second Celtic manager to achieve this, after Jock Stein.<ref name=\"treble32\">{{cite news|last=Hayward |first=Paul |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/3006199/Scottish-Cup-final-Business-as-usual-for-loyal-ONeill.html |title=Scottish Cup final: Business as usual for loyal O'Neill |work=The Telegraph |date=27 May 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The season was also additionally memorable because of some excellent results against rivals Rangers. A famous 6\u20132 victory in the opening [[Old Firm]] encounter of the season at Celtic Park proved to everyone that the balance of power in Scotland had shifted.<ref>{{cite web|first=James|last=Traynor |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/spl-celtic-6-rangers-2-1009206 |title=SPL: Celtic 6 Rangers 2, August 28, 2000 |work=Daily Record |date=10 February 2009 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Two further league victories against Rangers: 1\u20130 (at Celtic Park),<ref>{{cite web|first=Ian|last=Paul |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celtic-close-in-on-league-title-ricksen-red-card-infuriates-advocaat-1.198993 |title=Celtic close in on league title:Ricksen red card infuriates Advocaat |work=Herald Scotland |date=12 February 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and 3\u20130 (at Ibrox)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/3004436/Larsson-brings-up-the-half-century-as-Celtic-win-Old-Firm-clash.html |title=Larsson brings up the half-century as Celtic win Old Firm clash |work=The Telegraph |date=29 April 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> ensured O'Neill's first league title was won by a considerable distance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2000-2001/table |title=Scottish Premier League 2000-2001 Table |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112194151/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2000-2001/table |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nO'Neill's debut season also saw outstanding performances produced by players already at Celtic. Henrik Larsson scored 53 goals in all competitions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/player.php?playerid=2842 |title=Celtic Player Henrik Larsson Details |work=FitbaStats |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and won the [[European Golden Shoe]] with his 35 league goals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Irvine |first=Neil |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/3007495/Larsson-goals-earn-Europes-golden-boot.html |title=Larsson goals earn Europe's golden boot |work=Telegraph |date=18 June 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Larsson was voted both SPFA and Scottish Football Writers Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season review 2000/01|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200001-2008-06-01/|publisher=SPFL|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> Young Bulgarian midfielder [[Stiliyan Petrov]] impressed as well, having been signed the previous season by John Barnes. In 2001, the 21-year-old Bulgarian became the first foreign winner of the [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year|SPFA Young Player of the Year]] award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstalk.ie/Petrov-announces-retirement-from-football |title=Newstalk - Petrov announces retirement from football |work=Newstalk.ie |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Impact in Europe===\nCeltic further strengthened their squad \u2013 in every sense \u2013 for the 2001\u201302 season with the signings of the powerfully-built Guinean defender [[Bobo Bald\u00e9]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=24753 |title=Bobo Balde |work=SoccerBase |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and Welsh striker [[John Hartson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1464876.stm |title=Celtic sign trio on deadline day |work=BBC Sport |date=2 August 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2001, Celtic played [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in [[Amsterdam]] in the first leg of the qualifier tie for the [[2001\u201302 UEFA Champions League|2001\u201302 Champions League]], turning in an outstanding performance.<ref name=\"Tictactic.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tictactic.co.uk/classic-tictactic-champions-league-3rd-qualifying-round-2001-ajax-1-3-celtic/ |title=Classic TicTacTic \u2013 Champions League 3rd Qualifying Round 2001: Ajax 1-3 Celtic |publisher=Tictactic.co.uk |date=11 July 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201215900/http://www.tictactic.co.uk/classic-tictactic-champions-league-3rd-qualifying-round-2001-ajax-1-3-celtic/ |archivedate=1 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"George Grant\">{{cite news|title=My Celtic could easily have had six, says O'Neill |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-65527/My-Celtic-easily-says-ONeill.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=6 August 2013|first=George|last=Grant|date=9 August 2001}}</ref> First-half goals from Dutch winger [[Bobby Petta]] and [[Didier Agathe]] gave Celtic a 2\u20131 lead at half-time. [[Chris Sutton]] added a third in the second half with a powerful header to give Celtic an impressive 3\u20131 win.<ref name=\"Forsyth\">{{cite news|last=Forsyth |first=Roddy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/3010365/Champions-League-Petta-sets-Celtic-on-the-path-to-glittering-prize.html |title=Champions League: Petta sets Celtic on the path to glittering prize |work=The Telegraph |date=8 August 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  A nervy second leg performance at Parkhead saw Celtic lose 0\u20131 on the night but progress to the group stages on aggregate, their first involvement in the Champions League group stages since the redevelopment of the tournament in the 1990s.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/3011251/Champions-League-Celtic-edge-through-but-nerves-show.html |title=Champions League: Celtic edge through but nerves show |work=The Telegraph |date=22 August 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> This was the first of three occasions that O'Neill's Celtic side qualified for the group stage of the Champions League, and on the only occasion they failed, they went on to reach the final of the UEFA Cup.\n\nCeltic made their debut in the group stages of the Champions League on 18 September 2001, losing 2\u20133 to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in [[Turin]].  Celtic had recovered from a 2\u20130 deficit to level the match at 2\u20132, but lost a third goal near the end from a controversial penalty.<ref>{{cite news|first=Barry|last=Glendenning |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/18/minutebyminute.sport1 |title=Juventus 3 - 2 Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=18 September 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/virals/130211/martin-oneills-memorable-rant-celtics-clash-juventus-2001-191434 |title=Magazine: Martin O'Neill's memorable rant from Celtic's clash with Juventus in 2001 |work=TalkSport |accessdate=6 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214020117/http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/virals/130211/martin-oneills-memorable-rant-celtics-clash-juventus-2001-191434 |archive-date=14 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Celtic recovered from that set-back to win their next two home matches against [[FC Porto|Porto]] and [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]],<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Walker |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/26/championsleague.porto |title=Celtic 1 - 0 Porto |work=The Guardian |date=26 September 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Graham|last=Clark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/11/championsleague.sport |title=Celtic 1 - 0 Rosenborg |work=The Guardian |date=11 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> but lost the away matches against the same opposition.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Taylor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/18/championsleague.porto |title=Porto 3 - 0 Celtic|work=The Guardian |date=18 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Walkerv|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/24/championsleague.sport1 |title=Rosenborg 2 - 0 Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=24 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic's final group match was against Juventus at Parkhead on 31 October 2001. It was a memorable European night in [[Glasgow]] as a Chris Sutton brace and an outstanding performance from \u013dubom\u00edr Morav\u010d\u00edk helped Celtic to a famous 4\u20133 win. Despite finishing the group with nine points, however, Celtic failed to qualify for the next round<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/1627972.stm |title=Celtic bow out in style |work=BBC Sport |date=31 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and parachuted into the [[2001\u201302 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]. Celtic were drawn against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in the UEFA Cup, and in the first leg in Spain had goalkeeper Rab Douglas to thank for keeping the score to a manageable 0\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/1666912.stm |title=Valencia vanquish Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=22 November 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The second leg in Glasgow saw Henrik Larsson scoring to give Celtic a 1\u20130 win after 90 minutes to level the tie on aggregate.  As no goals were scored during extra-time, the tie went to penalty-kicks. Celtic lost the penalty shoot-out and were knocked out.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|first=Graham|last=Clark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/dec/07/uefa.sport |title=Uefa Cup: Celtic 1 - 0 Valencia (1-1 agg, Valencia win 5-4 on pens) |work=The Guardian |date=7 December 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nCeltic cruised to their second successive league title in 2001\u201302, their first back-to-back titles in 20 years<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200102-2008-06-01/ |title=Season Review 2001/02 |publisher=SPFL |date=1 June 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> and finished 18 points clear of second-placed Rangers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2001-2002/table |title=Scottish Premier League 2001-2002 Table |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224418/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2001-2002/table |archivedate=1 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Rangers, under new manager [[Alex McLeish]], did however enjoy a modicum of revenge in the cup tournaments, beating Celtic 2\u20131 in the semi-final of the League Cup<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/cis_ins_cup/1800034.stm |title=Konterman kills Celtic's dream |work=BBC Sport |date=5 February 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and twice coming from behind in the Scottish Cup Final in May 2002 to win 3\u20132 through a last-minute goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scottish_cup/1966673.stm |title=Rangers win Old Firm final |work=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nO'Neill's third season at Celtic, 2002\u201303, was probably the most memorable, even although the club did not win any silverware.<ref name=\"killie4\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Walker |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/may/26/match.sport |title=Kilmarnock 0 - 4 Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=25 May 2003|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The domestic cup tournaments again eluded Celtic; in the space of a week in March 2003, Celtic lost 2\u20131 to Rangers in the League Cup final<ref>{{cite news|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2398103/CIS-Cup-Final-Hartson-makes-Rangers-day.html |title=CIS Cup Final: Hartson makes Rangers' day |work=The Telegraph |date=17 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and then were knocked out of the Scottish Cup a week later at the fourth round stage by Inverness Caledonian Thistle.<ref>{{cite news|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2398483/Super-Caley-shock-Celtic-in-cup-again.html |title=Super Caley shock Celtic in cup again |work=The Telegraph |date=27 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The league campaign was a tight contest, and going into the last fixture both Celtic and Rangers were level on points. Both sides recorded high-scoring wins in their respective fixtures \u2013 Celtic won 4\u20130 at [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], but Rangers' 6\u20131 win at Ibrox over [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dumfermline Athletic]] saw them win the league on goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200203-2008-06-01/ |title=Season Review 2002/03 |publisher=SPFL |date=1 June 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>  It was in Europe, however, that Celtic made their mark.\n\nCeltic's [[The Bhoys from Seville|European campaign in 2002\u201303]] began somewhat inauspiciously when they were beaten by [[FC Basel|Basel]] on away goals in a qualifier tie for the Champions League.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2218965.stm |title=Celtic beaten in Basel |work=BBC Sport |date=28 August 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic dropped into the UEFA Cup, and in the first round eased to a 10\u20131 aggregate win over Lithuanian minnows [[FK S\u016bduva Marijampol\u0117|FK S\u016bduva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/FOOTBALL+%3A+CELTS+GO+ON+A+BALTIC+CRUISE%3B+So+easy+as+clever+Bhoys+make...-a092432444 |title=Celtic go on a Baltic cruise; So easy as clever Bhoys make it 10 out of 10 for the clever Bhoys|work=Daily Record |date=4 October 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  The next round, Celtic were paired with [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redandwhitekop.com/forum/index.php?topic=7379.0 |title=UEFA Cup draw. Celtic v Blackburn |publisher=Redandwhitekop.com |date= |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> managed by former Rangers player-manager [[Graeme Souness]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Davies |first=Christopher |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackburn-rovers/3035810/Souness-prepares-for-Scottish-reunion.html |title=Souness prepares for Scottish reunion |work=The Telegraph |date=9 October 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic were poor in the first leg at Parkhead, but a Henrik Larsson goal five minutes from full-time secured a crucial 1\u20130 win on the night and a narrow lead to take down to [[Ewood Park]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/3037111/Larsson-gives-Celtic-the-edge.html</ref>  In the build-up to the return match, Blackburn captain [[Gary Flitcroft]] made public that Souness had commented in the dressing room after the first game that Blackburn were the better side and should have won: \"That was men against boys.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth |first=Roddy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackburn-rovers/3037870/Irish-argue-Celtics-case.html |title=Irish argue Celtic's case |work=The Telegraph |date=14 November 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  In the second leg, Celtic showed much more composure and scored after 14 minutes through Larsson.  Celtic controlled the game after that and Chris Sutton scored another goal for Celtic in the second half, with Celtic winning 2\u20130 on the night and 3\u20130 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Taylor|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/nov/15/uefa.sport |title=Blackburn Rovers 0 - 2 Celtic (Celtic won 3-0 on aggregate)|work=The Guardian |date=2 December 2003|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic's third round UEFA cup opponents were [[Celta de Vigo]]. In a first-leg overshadowed by eccentric refereeing,<ref>{{cite news|last=McCarthy|first=David|title=Clueless Columbo; Nightmare referee is a mystery as raging O'Neill blows his top |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+CLUELESS+COLUMBO%3B+Nightmare+referee+is+a+mystery+as+raging...-a094717506|accessdate=4 October 2013|newspaper=Daily Record|date=29 November 2002}}</ref> Larsson scored the only goal of the game in Glasgow.<ref>{{cite news|first=Graham|last=Clark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/nov/29/uefa.sport |title=Celtic 1 - 0 Celta Vigo |work=The Guardian |date=28 November 2002|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  The return match in Spain was won 2\u20131 by Celta, levelling the aggregate score at 2\u20132, but [[John Hartson]]'s away goal won the tie for Celtic. This was the first time ever that Celtic had knocked out a Spanish club in European competition, and also the first time in 23 years that Celtic had remained in European competition beyond Christmas.<ref>{{cite news|first=Chris|last=Roberts at the Balaidos Stadium |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/dec/13/uefa.sport1 |title=Celta Vigo 2 - 1 Celtic (Celtic win on away goals) |work=The Guardian |date=12 December 2002|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seville celtic fans.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Celtic fans at the UEFA Cup Final in Seville]]\nGerman [[Bundesliga]] team [[VfB Stuttgart]] were Celtic's fourth round opponents in the Spring of 2003. Celtic came from behind to win the first leg 3\u20131 at Parkhead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/uefa_cup/2780267.stm |title=Petrov sinks Stuttgart |work=BBC Sport |date=21 February 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> In the second leg, Celtic went 2\u20130 up early on, but a comeback by Stuttgart saw the Bundesliga side win 3\u20132 on the night; Celtic however won 5\u20134 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2798753.stm |title=Celtic kill off Stuttgart |work=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  The quarter-finals saw another English [[Premier League]] opponent for Celtic: Liverpool. The first leg took place at Celtic Park on 13 March 2003.  The first leg ended 1\u20131 with Larsson scoring for Celtic in the first minute but the away goal gave Liverpool the advantage going in to their home tie at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2836319.stm |title=Liverpool hold Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> During the first leg, Liverpool player [[El Hadji Diouf]] spat at a Celtic supporter, and was later fined \u00a35,000 at Glasgow's [[Sheriff Court]] for the incident.<ref>{{cite news |title=Diouf will not face assault charges |work=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]| url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/english/2006/1116/211372-dioufe/ |accessdate=25 January 2015 |date=14 June 2007}}</ref>  The return match at Anfield took place the following week. Celtic won 2\u20130, with the goals coming from an Alan Thompson free-kick and a long-range strike from [[John Hartson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2864921.stm |title=Celtic brush aside Liverpool |work=BBC Sport |date=20 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nCeltic's first European semi-final since the early 1970s saw them paired against Portuguese side [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]]. Celtic drew 1\u20131 in the first game at Parkhead,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2909819.stm |title=Celtic held by Boavista |work=BBC Sport |date=10 April 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> but a Henrik Larsson goal in the 80th minute of the return match in Portugal won the tie and ensured Celtic's progress to the UEFA Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jon|last=Brodkin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/apr/25/newsstory.sport4 |title=Boavista 0 - 1 Celtic (Agg: 1-2) |work=The Guardian |date=25 April 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2003, around 80,000 Celtic fans travelled to watch the club compete in the [[2003 UEFA Cup Final|final]], held in [[Seville]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/gallery/0,8561,972767,00.html |title=Celtic in Seville: A picture special |work=Observer Sport (The Guardian) |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Stephen|last2=Henderson|first2=Damien|title=Hats off to very good bhoys and ghirls 80,000 Celtic fans in Spain and not a single arrest|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/hats-off-to-very-good-bhoys-and-ghirls-80-000-celtic-fans-in-spain-and-not-a-single-arrest-1.117903|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=23 May 2003}}</ref> Celtic lost the final on 21 May 2003 3\u20132 to Porto after extra time, despite two goals from Henrik Larsson during normal play. Celtic's cause was not helped by the late sending-off of defender Bobo Bald\u00e9 and the referee's over-indulgence of Porto's time-wasting and their players' persistent feigning of injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/european/2003/0522/172812-celtic01/ |title=UEFA may discipline O'Neill over comments |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |date=14 June 2007 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> However, the exemplary conduct of the thousands of travelling Celtic supporters received widespread praise from the people of Seville and the fans were awarded prestigious [[FIFA Fair Play Award|Fair Play Awards]] from both [[FIFA]] and [[UEFA]] \"for their extraordinarily loyal and sporting behaviour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/ballondor/archive/edition=1999902003/news/newsid=90249/index.html |title=Celebrating Celtic pride in the heart of Andalusia |publisher=FIFA.com |date=15 December 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3189853.stm |title=Celtic fans 'Europe's best' |work=BBC News |date=28 August 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Continued success===\n[[File:Oldfirm.jpg|thumb|left|350px|Celtic and Rangers fans at Parkhead in 2004]]\nCeltic regained the SPL title in 2003\u201304 in emphatic manner, winning by a margin of 18 points and scoring over 100 goals.<ref name=\"lg0304\">{{cite web|title=Season review 2003/04|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200304-2008-06-01/|publisher=SPFL|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> The league campaign also saw Celtic win 25 games in a row, setting a new British record.<ref name=\"lg0304\" />  Celtic recorded five wins (four in the league, one in the Scottish Cup) over rivals Rangers; a last minute Chris Sutton goal in May 2004 giving Celtic a 1\u20130 win in the final Old Firm fixture of the season and their first [[Whitewash (sport)|whitewash]] of wins over their rivals for over 30 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 1 Rangers 0|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/3691469.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=8 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nCeltic qualified for the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|Champions League in 2003\u201304]], but again could only finish third in the group stages and dropped into the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic suffer Lyon heartbreak; Lyon 3-2 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/3304353.stm|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=10 December 2003|work=BBC News}}</ref>  After a straightforward aggregate win over [[FK Teplice]],<ref>{{cite web|title=FK Teplice 1-0 Celtic: Safe passage|url=http://espnfc.com/en/report/142294/report.html?soccernet=true|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=4 March 2014|date=3 March 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304221913/http://espnfc.com/en/report/142294/report.html?soccernet=true|archivedate=4 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Celtic were drawn against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the round of 16. A dramatic first leg in Glasgow saw Celtic win 1\u20130 through an Alan Thompson goal, but goalkeeper Rab Douglas and Barcelona's [[Thiago Motta]] were sent off during half-time for fighting in the tunnel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic spoil Bar\u00e7a's winning streak|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2003/matches/round=1721/match=74496/postmatch/report/index.html|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=11 March 2004}}</ref>  The return match in Spain saw Celtic fielding 19-year-old reserve goalkeeper [[David Marshall (footballer)|David Marshall]] in place of Douglas and young defender [[John Kennedy (Scottish footballer)|John Kennedy]] standing in for Bobo Bald\u00e9, who was also suspended.<ref name=\"0416r\">{{cite news|title=Celtic stun Barcelona; Barcelona 0-0 Celtic (agg:0-1)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3560199.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=25 March 2004}}</ref> Celtic found themselves under a sustained barrage of pressure, but the two youngsters turned in outstanding performances.  Marshall pulled off outstanding saves from [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]] and [[Luis Garc\u00eda (footballer, born 1978)|Luis Garc\u00eda]], while Kennedy made a number of great tackles to keep Barcelona at bay.<ref name=\"0416r\" /> Celtic held out for a scoreless draw on the night to win on aggregate and progress to the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"0416r\" />  Celtic's run in Europe was finally ended in the next round by another Spanish side, [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], losing 3\u20131 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Villareal 2-0 Celtic (Villareal win 3-1 on aggregate)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/3621937.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 March 2014|date=14 April 2004}}</ref>\n\nThe Scottish Cup final was reached with ease; Celtic conceding only one goal as they knocked out [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]], [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]], Rangers and [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] en route.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic Fixtures & Results - 2003/04 (Scottish Cup)|url=http://espnfc.com/team/fixtures/_/id/256/season/2003/league/sco.tennents/celtic?cc=5739|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>  The final against Dunfermline took place on 22 May 2004 and was the last match Henrik Larsson played for the club. The Swede ended his Celtic career on a high note, scoring twice as Celtic came from behind to win 3\u20131, completing a league and cup double for the season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barnes|first=John|title=Departing Larsson earns Celtic double|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2379408/Departing-Larsson-earns-Celtic-double.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 March 2014|date=23 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nThe following season ([[2004\u201305 Celtic F.C. season|2004\u201305]]), O'Neill's last at the club, saw Celtic struggle to maintain their dominance of recent years.  Nevertheless, they took an early lead in the league campaign and won their first encounter against Rangers in August 2004, their seventh consecutive win in Old Firm games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 1-0 Rangers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/3601320.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=29 August 2004}}</ref>  \nThe league contest went to the final day of the season with Celtic needing to win away at [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] to guarantee the title.  Celtic led for most of the match, and with two minutes of normal time remaining looked set for another SPL title.  However, two late [[Scott McDonald]] goals for Motherwell saw Celtic beaten 2\u20131 and hand the title to rivals Rangers. The season did end in silverware for Celtic as they retained the Scottish Cup, defeating Dundee United 1\u20130 in the final.  At the end of the season, Martin O'Neill parted ways with the club, to care for his ill wife.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4576981.stm |title=End of an era as O'Neill resigns |work=BBC Sport |date=25 May 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nUnder O'Neill's five year leadership, Celtic won the league three times, three Scottish Cup finals and the League Cup once.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefootballsupernova.com/2012/11/martin-oneill-is-his-time-up.html |title=Martin O'Neill - Is his time up? |work=The Football Supernova |date=5 November 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> In European competition, teams such as Juventus,<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/> Porto,<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> [[Valencia CF|Valencia]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> and Barcelona<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/3497300.stm |title=Celtic 1-0 Barcelona |work=BBC Sport |date=11 March 2004 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> all visited Glasgow to face Celtic and returned home defeated. He led Celtic to their first European final in 33 years, albeit losing narrowly after extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espnfc.com/blog/_/name/celtic/id/394?cc=5739 |title=Memories of Seville 2003: Ten years on |publisher=ESPN FC  |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic also commenced an unbeaten run of 77 home matches, which spanned from 2001 to 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=aberdeen-ends-celtics-77-game-unbeaten-home-run-2004-04-23 |title=SPORTS - Aberdeen ends Celtic's 77-game unbeaten home run |work=Hurriyet Daily News |date=23 April 2004 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and notched up an SPL record for the most consecutive wins in a single season.<ref name=\"lg0304\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=esp/news/newsid=1588768.html |title=Europe's longest domestic winning streaks |publisher=UEFA.com |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>  In conclusion, O'Neill's tenure as manager at Celtic was the club's most successful period since the time of Jock Stein.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Gordon Strachan and Tony Mowbray (2005\u20132010)==\n[[File:Gordon David Strachan.jpg|thumb|177px|left|Gordon Strachan]]\n[[Gordon Strachan]] was announced in June 2005 as Martin O'Neill's replacement,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4572091.stm |title=Strachan in for O'Neill at Celtic |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 May 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> after apparently being recommended by O'Neill himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/strachan-follows-oneills-example-1577944 |title=Strachan follows O'Neill's example |work=Chronicle Live |date=1 June 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Strachan faced a number of challenges, not least in inheriting an aged squad who were highly expensive and one that had still failed to replace the talismanic Henrik Larsson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4729853.stm |title=Strachan not veering from course |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Strachan made an unpromising start, in particular his first game in which Celtic lost 0\u20135 to Slovakian side [[Artmedia Bratislava]] and recorded their worst ever European result,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-357323/Humiliated-Celtic-got-deserved--Bratislava-captain.html |title=Humiliated Celtic got what they deserved - Bratislava captain |work=Mail Online |date=28 July 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic, however, quickly regained form and confidence and went on to become the fastest team to win the SPL championship ever,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Armstrong|first1=Gary|title=Celtic on course to break their own record as earliest ever title winners|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-course-break-record-earliest-9541164|accessdate=2 January 2017|work=Daily Record|date=1 January 2017}}</ref> along with the League Cup in the [[2005\u201306 Celtic F.C. season|2005\u201306 season]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunfermline 0-3 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/4807338.stm|accessdate=2 January 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=19 March 2006}}</ref> The title was clinched before the league was split with a 1\u20130 home victory over second-placed Hearts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/4873944.stm |title=Celtic 1-0 Hearts |work=BBC Sport |date=5 April 2006 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> [[Shaun Maloney]] had an outstanding season for Celtic and became the first player to win both [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year|Young Player of the Year]] awards from [[PFA Scotland]] in the same season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4951722.stm |title=Maloney in historic awards double |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=28 March 2008 |date=1 May 2006}}</ref> Celtic's home games that season attracted an average attendance of 58,149,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotprem.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Attendance/0,,10002~20053,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410122328/http://www.scotprem.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Attendance/0%2C%2C10002~20053%2C00.html |archivedate=10 April 2008 |title=Attendance Scottish Premier League Stats 2005/06 |publisher=SPL |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> placing Celtic at the time behind only [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in terms of highest average attendance for any football club in the UK.<ref name=\"s0506\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nufc.com/html/2005-06html/homeatt.html |title=Premiership Attendances 2005-2006 |accessdate=26 March 2015 |publisher=NUFC.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:JohnReidHeadshot.jpg|170px|thumb|right|Celtic Chairman 2007-2011, John Reid]]During the [[2006\u201307 Celtic F.C. season|2006\u201307 season]] Celtic continued their domination of the Scottish Premier League, despite a huge effort by Strachan and the club to reduce the wage bill. Expensive mainstays of the O'Neill years such as Hartson and Sutton, who on average delivered 40 goals per season between them, were moved on and replaced by far younger, and less expensive, players. The team proved unerringly consistent, as had O'Neill's, despite their youth and comparative lack of experience. By the close of the January transfer window, Celtic were 19 points ahead of second-placed Rangers,<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan |title=Red card mars win which puts Celtic in sight of March title|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/jan/29/match.invernesscaledonianthistle |work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 November 2013|date=29 January 2007}}</ref> something which may have been a large contribution to a complete loss of form and partial loss of points in the second half of the season.<ref name=\"l07win\">{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Months of Celtic frustration forgotten as Nakamura wonder-strike secures title|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/apr/23/match.kilmarnock|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 November 2013|date=23 April 2007}}</ref> They completed their quest for back-to-back titles on 22 April 2007 with a 2\u20131 win against Kilmarnock. [[Shunsuke Nakamura]] ensured the victory with a goal from a free kick from 25 yards in the final minute,<ref name=\"l07win\" /> leaving Celtic 13 points clear of Rangers with four matches remaining.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Premier League 2006-2007 - Table on Monday 23rd April 2007|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2006-2007/table/2007-04-23|website=Statto|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThat season also saw Strachan guide Celtic into last 16 of the Champions League for the first time. Celtic secured their progress from the group stages courtesy of Shunsuke Nakamura's 30-yard free-kick against Manchester United in a 1\u20130 win at Parkhead. The win on the night, and qualification to the last 16, was clinched when [[Artur Boruc]] saved [[Louis Saha]]'s 88th-minute penalty kick.<ref>{{cite web |title=United crash as Nakamura puts Celtic through |first=Kevin |last=McCarra |work=The Guardian |date=22 November 2006 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/nov/22/match.sport |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Celtic lost 0\u20131 in the last 16 round to the eventual winners of the cup, [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], after a goal from [[Kak\u00e1]] in extra time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Aikman|first=Richard|title=Celtic foiled by Kak\u00e1 magic |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2006/matches/round=2358/match=85505/postmatch/report/index.html|publisher=UEFA.com|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref> On 26 May 2007, Celtic again won the Scottish Cup, for a 34th time, beating Dunfermline 1\u20130, completing another league and cup double. The Cup final was also captain [[Neil Lennon]]'s final appearance as a Celtic player.<ref>{{cite web|last=Glenn|first=Patrick|title=Kenny's gallant men floored by the Doumbe Double |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/27/match.celtic|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 November 2013|date=27 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 September 2007 it was announced [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]] would become chairman of Celtic and he took over from [[Brian Quinn (economist)|Brian Quinn]] on 7 November. Reid is a lifelong supporter of the club and described the appointment as \"the greatest honour of my life\".<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/scotland/article2901473.ece |title=John Reid appointed as Celtic chairman |work=Times Online |accessdate=17 February 2008 |date=19 November 2007}}{{subscription}}</ref> His appointment was approved by a large majority of shareholders, though many fans opposed the motion at Celtic's [[annual general meeting]] over Reid's role in the [[British Government]] during the [[Iraq War]].<ref name=\"The Times\"/>\n\nThe start of Strachan's third season saw further changes to the team. [[Neil Lennon]] had left in the summer and centre-half [[Stephen McManus]] was now made captain of the side.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/6923901.stm McManus named new Celtic captain], BBC Sport, 31 July 2007</ref> In May, Celtic completed the signing of midfielder [[Scott Brown (footballer, born June 1985)|Scott Brown]] from Hibernian for a fee of around \u00a34.4&nbsp;million, the largest transfer fee exchanged between two Scottish clubs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Atkinson|first=Mark|title=Celtic bag Brown from under Rangers' nose|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/16/newsstory.sport6|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 March 2014|date=16 May 2007}}</ref> Motherwell striker [[Scott McDonald]] also arrived at Celtic Park, signed for a fee of \u00a3700,000,<ref name=\"smsig\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/motherwell/6511631.stm |title=Celtic complete McDonald capture |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 March 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523045817/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/motherwell/6511631.stm |archivedate=23 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and having been the player who famously scored two late goals against Celtic on the last day of the season in 2005 to effectively hand Rangers the title.<ref name=\"smsig\" /> [[File:KDoddvCelts.jpg|thumb|177px|left|Shunsuke Nakamura against Falkirk in December 2006]]\n\nAs the 2007\u201308 season progressed, Celtic found themselves embroiled in a tight contest with Rangers for the SPL title. Celtic led for the early part of the season, but a series of poor results in the winter and early spring saw Rangers overtake them. A [[Kevin Thomson]] goal on 31 March 2008 gave Rangers a 1\u20130 win at Ibrox over Celtic, leaving Celtic trailing their rivals in the league by six points.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sharp|first=David|title=Rangers 1 Celtic 0|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/7317659.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=29 March 2008}}</ref> A few days later, Neil Lennon returned to Celtic as a coach, effectively replacing first-team coach Tommy Burns, who was being treated for cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grahame|first1=Ewing|title=Neil Lennon joins Celtic's coaching staff|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2296272/Neil-Lennon-joins-Celtics-coaching-staff.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=4 April 2008}}</ref> A dramatic, and seemingly unlikely, turnaround in Celtic's fortunes then began on 16 April, when the Old Firm met again at Celtic Park. A re-invigorated Celtic dominated the opening proceedings and took the lead when Shunsuke Nakamura scored with a spectacular swerving shot from 30 yards. [[Nacho Novo]] equalised for Rangers early in the second half, but Celtic got a chance to retake the lead when Nakamura's curling shot was handled off the line by Rangers defender [[Carlos Cu\u00e9llar]], who was sent off. Rangers goalkeeper [[Allan McGregor]], however, despite having an injured ankle, saved [[Scott McDonald]]'s penalty kick.  Rangers looked like holding on for a vital point until in the third minute of injury time [[Jan Vennegoor of Hesselink]] bundled the ball into the goal to clinch a 2\u20131 win for Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Celtic's last-gasp winner keeps title race alive|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/apr/17/sport.celtic|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=16 April 2008}}</ref> Celtic began to claw back on Rangers lead in the league, and by the time of the final league fixture of the season were league leaders. A Vennegoor of Hesselink headed goal gave Celtic a 1\u20130 win on the night away at Dundee United, clinching the title for Celtic. This ensured Strachan's place in the history books of Celtic, becoming only the third manager to win three successive league titles, behind [[Willie Maley]] and Jock Stein.<ref>{{cite news|last=Conaghan|first=Martin|title=Strachan's magic number is three |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/7414250.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=12 November 2013|date=23 May 2008}}</ref> The victory was also dedicated to the memory of Tommy Burns, former player, manager and coach, who had died earlier that week.<ref>{{cite web|last=McEachran|first=John|title=Fans remember legend Tommy Burns as Celtic clinch SPL title|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/fans-remember-legend-tommy-burns-978135|work=Daily Record|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=23 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maciej \u017burawski Celtic.jpg|thumb|177px|left|Maiej Zurawski in action for Celtic in a pre-season game against FC Basel in July 2007]]\nThe 2007\u201308 season saw Celtic again taking part in the Champions League. Celtic qualified for the group stages by knocking out [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]] in the prelims, the tie eventually going to penalty kicks with Artur Boruc saving twice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=Celtic 1-1 Spartak Moscow (2-2) Celtic win 4-3 on penalties|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6966717.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=29 August 2007}}</ref> Celtic won all three home games in the group stages; a last minute Scott McDonald goal giving Celtic a 2\u20131 win over Milan,<ref>{{cite news|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=Celtic 2 AC Milan 1|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7019611.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=3 October 2007}}</ref> [[Aiden McGeady]] scoring the only goal in a 1\u20130 win over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Sharp|first=David|title=Celtic 1 Benfica 0|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7078731.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=6 November 2007}}</ref> and [[Massimo Donati]] scoring an injury time winner against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Celtic 2-1 Shakhtar Donetsk|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7115381.stm|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=28 November 2007|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Despite losing all three of their corresponding away fixtures, Celtic qualified for the round of 16 for the second successive season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=AC Milan 1-0 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7123562.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=4 December 2007}}</ref> In the first leg of the round of 16 tie against Barcelona, Celtic twice took the lead at Parkhead, but finished losing 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Julian|title=Celtic 2-3 Barcelona|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7250340.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=20 February 2008}}</ref> They were unable to recover the deficit in the return match and were knocked out.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Julian|title=Barcelona 1-0 Celtic (agg: 4-2)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7272569.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=4 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, Celtic won the [[2008\u201309 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] beating Rangers 2\u20130 in the final after extra time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Celtic 2-0 Rangers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7941624.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 November 2013|date=15 March 2009}}</ref> Celtic failed to win the [[2008\u201309 Scottish Premier League|SPL title]], finishing second to Rangers and Strachan resigned from the manager's position at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ewan|last=Murray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/25/gordon-strachan-resigns-manager-celtic |title=Gordon Strachan resigns as manager of Celtic in wake of failure to win SPL |work=The Guardian|date=25 May 2009 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tony Mowbray Celtic unhappy edit.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Tony Mowbray, showing the strain]]\n[[Tony Mowbray]] was announced as the replacement for Strachan on 16 June 2009.<ref name=\"gdmow\">{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Tony Mowbray confirmed as new manager of Celtic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jun/16/tony-mowbray-celtic-west-bromwich|work=The Guardian|date=16 June 2009|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> He moved from his managerial post at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]. It was a return to Celtic for the Englishman after playing there for four years between 1991 and 1995 and is considered to be the player who started the famous Celtic prematch \"Huddle\".<ref name=\"gdmow\" /> He promised a \"Barcelona-esque\" style of football, and more attacking play,<ref>{{cite news|last=Traynor|first=James|title=Tony Mowbray: I want to get Celtic playing football like Spain or Barcelona|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/tony-mowbray-i-want-to-get-celtic-playing-1027904|accessdate=14 October 2013|newspaper=Daily Record|date=18 June 2009}}</ref> never afraid to hide his admiration for the likes of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]].<ref>{{cite web|title=West Brom boss Mowbray: Arsenal's Wenger transformed English football|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/west-brom-boss-mowbray-arsenals-wenger-transformed-english-football-197784#.UlxEqdKRD10|date=15 August 2008|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fisher|first=Stewart|title=Sustenance of style for Tony Mowbray|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/celtic/sustenance-of-style-for-tony-mowbray-1.822988|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>  Things started well, he won his first trophy shortly after signing for Celtic, with victory in the [[Wembley Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic win Wembley Cup|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/104863/report|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> He brought [[Marc-Antoine Fortun\u00e9]], [[Landry N'Gu\u00e9mo]] and [[Danny Fox]] to the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=SPL ins and outs|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8105863.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=14 October 2013|date=14 August 2009}}</ref> Things looked very promising when Celtic comprehensively beat Aberdeen in the opening SPL game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen 1 Celtic 3: McGeady grabs superb brace as Bhoys open campaign with victory |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1206748/Aberdeen-1-Celtic-3-McGeady-grabs-superb-brace-Bhoys-open-campaign-victory.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBecause of the previous season league position, two qualifying rounds were required to enter the Champions league group stages. After a 1\u20130 loss to [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]] at home,<ref>{{cite news|last=Grahame|first=Ewing|title=Celtic 0 Dinamo Moscow 1: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/5934557/Celtic-0-Dinamo-Moscow-1-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=30 October 2013|date=29 July 2009}}</ref> Mowbray lead Celtic to a 2\u20130 win in Moscow, ending a long run of not winning any away games in the Champions league.<ref>{{cite news|last=McGowan|first=Stephen|title=Dynamo Moscow 0 Celtic 2: Georgios Samaras late show sends Bhoys through in Europe |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1204560/Dynamo-Moscow-0-Celtic-2-Georgios-Samaras-late-sends-Bhoys-Europe.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=5 August 2009}}</ref> This was also the first time ever that Celtic had won a European tie after losing the first keg at home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dinamo Moscow 0 Celtic 2: My brave Bhoys got what they deserved, insists Mowbray |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1204565/Dinamo-Moscow-0-Celtic-2-My-brave-Bhoys-got-deserved-insists-Mowbray.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=30 January 2015|date=6 August 2009}}</ref> Celtic were then drawn with English side Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Champions League draw: Arsenal to face Celtic in play-off|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/5988106/Champions-League-draw-Arsenal-to-face-Celtic-in-play-off.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=7 August 2009}}</ref> Celtic lost the home leg, 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawton|first=Matt|title=Celtic 0 Arsenal 2: Gallas lucky dip rocks Scots but flukes don't hide Arsenal's real class|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1207502/Celtic-0-Arsenal-2-William-Gallas-lucky-dip-rocks-Scots-flukes-dont-hide-Arsenals-real-class.html |work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=19 August 2009}}</ref>  In the return leg in the [[Emirates Stadium]], Celtic were holding Arsenal 0\u20130 until a dive by Arsenal striker [[Eduardo da Silva|Eduardo]] won them a penalty, which Eduardo stepped up to put the ball past Artur Boruc from the spot, sending Arsenal en route to a 3\u20131 win. A rejuvenated Massimo Donati scored Celtic's only goal in the last minute.<ref>{{cite news|last=Winter|first=Henry|title=Arsenal 3 Celtic 1; agg 5-1: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/6095206/Arsenal-3-Celtic-1-agg-5-1-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=26 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nThings began to slide after that though, Celtic began hemorrhaging points to the so-called \"smaller teams\" in the league.<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Patience runs thin at Parkhead as Tony Mowbray's Celtic project stalls|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2009/nov/27/tony-mowbray-celtic-paul-le-guen|work=The Guardian|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=27 November 2009}}</ref> Celtic then exited the UEFA Europa League before Christmas despite a promising draw of group opponents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 2 Hapoel Tel-Aviv 0: Bhoys win at last in Europa League but it's too little too late|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1232747/Celtic-2-Hapoel-Tel-Aviv-0-Bhoys-win-Europa-League-little-late.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=3 December 2009}}</ref>  Despite a big squad shake-up in the January transfer window, including the departure of club captain Stephen McManus,<ref name=\"mgone\">{{cite news|last=Greechan|first=John|title=Celtic beat Hull City and West Brom to sign Fulham's Diomansy Kamara on loan as Scott McDonald edges closer to exit|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1247219/Celtic-beat-Hull-City-West-Brom-sign-Fulhams-Diomansy-Kamara-loan-Scott-McDonald-edges-closer-exit.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=30 January 2010}}</ref> leading goalscorer Scott McDonald,<ref name=\"mgone1\">{{cite web|title=Scott McDonald leaves Celtic for Middlesbrough|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/celtic/154604-scott-mcdonald-leaves-celtic-for-middlesbrough/|publisher=STV Sport|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=1 February 2010}}</ref>  [[Barry Robson]],<ref name=\"mgone1\" /> the newly acquired Danny Fox<ref name=\"mgone\" /> and a number of other fringe players; and the bringing in of Republic of Ireland striker [[Robbie Keane]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Tottenham's Robbie Keane moves to Celtic on loan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/feb/01/robbie-keane-celtic-loan-tottenham|work=The Guardian|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=1 February 2010}}</ref> [[Diomansy Kamara]]<ref name=\"mgone\" /> and others, Tony Mowbray was sacked by the club the day after their 4\u20130 defeat by [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 24 March 2010 and Neil Lennon took charge for the remainder of the [[2009\u201310 Celtic F.C. season|2009\u201310 season]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Galluzzo|first=Mauro|title=Tony Mowbray sacked by Celtic as Neil Lennon takes over|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/165174/Tony-Mowbray-sacked-by-Celtic-as-Neil-Lennon-takes-over|work=Daily Express|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=25 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Neil Lennon (2010\u20132014)==\n\n===\"Bring back the thunder\"===\n[[File:Neil lennon and excalibur.jpg|thumb|left|Former Celtic captain, Neil Lennon]]\n\nNeil Lennon became the caretaker manager after Tony Mowbray was fired, bringing in former teammate [[Johan Mj\u00e4llby]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic caretaker boss Neil Lennon wants job permanently|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8588663.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=26 March 2010}}</ref> Celtic were ten points behind Rangers, who had played two less games, when Lennon took over.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic end manager Tony Mowbray's troubled reign|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8586352.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=25 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jackson|first=Keith|title=Neil Lennon goes from Celtic outcast to Parkhead boss in just a few hours following Tony Mowbray's departure|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2010/03/26/neil-lennon-goes-from-celtic-outcast-to-parkhead-boss-in-space-of-just-hours-following-tony-mowbray-s-departure-86908-22139827/|work=Daily Record|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=26 March 2010}}</ref> Despite having no management experience Lennon lead Celtic to eight wins from the eight remaining league matches, finishing six points behind their Old Firm rivals<ref name=end0910>{{cite news|title=Hearts 1 - 2 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8666273.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=9 May 2010}}</ref> who they also beat 2\u20131 in the final Old Firm match of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 2 - 1 Rangers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8658392.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|first=Andy|last=Campbell|date=4 May 2010}}</ref> This provided a much needed morale boost to the club. Celtic's one chance for silverware was the [[2009\u201310 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]], they faced [[Scottish First Division|First Division]] [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] in the semi-final but lost 2\u20130. In the aftermath of the Ross County match, Lennon spoke frankly about his opinion of the players and their performances over the course of the season; he said that the players had lacked \"hunger and desire\" and that whether he was installed as manager or not, he would be recommending a serious clear-out of players to the board.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,13869_6085625,00.html|title= Lennon questions Hoops attitude|work=Sky Sports|date=10 April 2010|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8613251.stm|title=Neil Lennon slams the lack of Celtic hunger and desire|work=BBC Sport|date=10 April 2010|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2010, despite concern over his lack of experience, Lennon was officially announced as the new Celtic manager<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=New Celtic manager Neil Lennon prepares to reach for the stars and reclaim SPL title|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/7815427/New-Celtic-manager-Neil-Lennon-prepares-to-reach-for-the-stars-and-reclaim-SPL-title.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=9 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New manager Neil Lennon wants Celtic 'to go to war'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8728818.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=9 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lennon takes Celtic centre stage|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8716347.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=8 June 2010}}</ref> He retained Mj\u00e4llby as his assistant, as well as former Celtic teammate Alan Thompson and former Leicester City teammate [[Garry Parker]] as first-team coaches<ref name=Teamup>{{cite news|title=Celtic appoint Johan Mj\u00e4llby and Garry Parker|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8780796.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=1 July 2010}}</ref>  Lennon stated his desire to \"bring back the thunder\" to Celtic Park.<ref>{{cite web|first=Keith|last=Jackson |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/neil-lennon-i-want-to-put-thunder-1061348 |title=Neil Lennon: I want to put thunder back into Celtic Park |work=Daily Record |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311====\nLennon made considerable changes to the Celtic team for the [[2010\u201311 Celtic F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]]. A number of players left the club over the summer, including Aiden McGeady, who was sold for a then Scottish record \u00a39.5&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2010/08/13/aiden-mcgeady-puts-pen-to-paper-on-9-5m-switch-to-spartak-moscow-86908-22485224/ |title=Aiden McGeady puts pen to paper on \u00a39.5m switch to Spartak Moscow|work=Daily Record|date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=21 July 2011}}</ref> In turn, a large number of talented, young, cheap, relatively unknown players from England and smaller leagues around the world were signed. Several more experienced players also arrived at this time to strengthen the squad. [[Gary Hooper]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Scunthorpe striker Gary Hooper signs for Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8852050.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=27 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Scunthorpe's Gary Hooper completes \u00a32.5m move to Celtic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/27/gary-hooper-celtic|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=27 July 2010}}</ref> [[Beram Kayal]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic sign Israel midfielder Beram Kayal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8849942.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=29 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic complete signing of Israeli midfielder Biram Kayal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/29/celtic-transfer-israeli-midfielder-biram-kayal|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=29 July 2010}}</ref> and [[Emilio Izaguirre]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic sign Honduran international defender Emilio Izaguirre|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2010/08/18/celtic-sign-honduran-international-defender-emilio-izaguirre-86908-22496304/|work=Daily Record|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=18 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Neil Lennon boosts Celtic ranks with Honduras defender Emilio Izaguirre|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1304132/Emilio-Izaguirre-signs-Celtic.html|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=18 August 2010|work=Mail Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic complete deal for left-back Emilio Izaguirre|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8925044.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=18 August 2010}}</ref> all had excellent seasons and earned many plaudits,<ref name=signingpolicy>{{cite news|url= http://sport.stv.tv/football/scottish-premier/celtic/261423-neil-lennon-explains-celtics-recruitment-policy/|title=Neil Lennon explains Celtic's recruitment policy |work=STV Sport|date=6 July 2011 |accessdate = 18 July 2011}}</ref> with Izaguirre winning both the [[SPFA Players' Player of the Year|SPFA]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13256109.stm|title=Emilio Izaguirre wins Scotland's players' player prize|publisher=BBC |work=BBC Sport|date=1 May 2011|accessdate=2 May 2011}}</ref> and [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers']]<ref>{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13406778.stm |title=More awards for Izaguirre, Goodwillie and Paatelainan |work=BBC Sport |date=15 May 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2011 }}</ref> Player of the Year awards. Goalkeeper [[Fraser Forster]], signed on loan from Newcastle United,<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic boss Neil Lennon signs Newcastle keeper Fraser Forster on loan for the season|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1305686/Celtic-sign-Newcastle-keeper-Fraser-Forster-loan-season.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=24 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic sign goalkeeper Fraser Forster on loan from Newcastle|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/aug/24/fraser-forster-joins-celtic-loan|work=The Guardian|author=Press Association|date=24 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Newcastle goalkeeper Fraser Forster on Celtic loan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8935182.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=24 August 2010}}</ref> on became first choice goalkeeper and helped set a new SPL record for most clean sheets in a season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/editor-s-picks/fraser-forster-proud-of-role-in-shut-out-success-1.1102140 |title=Fraser Forster proud of role in shut-out success |work=Evening Times\n|date=18 May 2011|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>[[File:Izaguirre Nov2010.jpg|thumb|right|Emilio Izaguirre was voted SPFA Player of the Year in 2011]]\n\nCeltic were knocked out of the Champions League and Europa League at the first hurdles, losing to [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] and [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]] respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/soccer/2010/0826/1224277683720.html|title=Dutch disaster for Celtic|work=Irish Times|date=26 August 2010 |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> Celtic and Rangers both won their first eight SPL games,<ref name=CRAIH>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/9122150.stm Celtic v Rangers as it happened] BBC Sport, 24 October 2010</ref> but when the sides first clashed Celtic lost 3\u20131.<ref name=CRAIH/> Celtic played fairly well up until the next Old Firm match, but still went into the New Year fixture at Ibrox as underdogs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/8234551/Rangers-manager-Walter-Smith-dismisses-favourites-tag-ahead-of-Sundays-emotional-Old-Firm-derby-at-Ibrox.html|title=Rangers manager Walter Smith dismisses favourites' tag ahead of Sunday's emotional Old Firm derby at Ibrox|work=The Telegraph|date=31 December 2010|accessdate=19 July 2011|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth}}</ref> However, Celtic won 2\u20130 thanks to a [[Georgios Samaras]] brace<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/9330644.stm</ref> and went onto win 15 out of their 19 matches in the second half of the season.<ref name=\"10/11SPL\" /> Draws at [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]] and Ibrox, however, as well as losses at Inverness and Motherwell, saw them lose the league by a point.<ref name=\"10/11SPL\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=home_Statistics |title=SPL Table 2010-11 |publisher=Scottish Premier League |accessdate=20 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612200756/http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=home_Statistics |archivedate=12 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, Celtic did have the best defensive record only conceding 22 goals.<ref name=\"10/11SPL\" />\n\nCeltic got to the final of both domestic cups in 2010\u201311. They lost the [[2011 Scottish League Cup Final|League Cup final]] 2\u20131 to Rangers but won the [[2011 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup final]] 3\u20130 against Motherwell.<ref>{{cite news|title=Motherwell 0 - 3 Celtic |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/9491542.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=21 May 2011 |first=Martin|last=Conaghan}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lennon will never walk alone.jpg|thumb|right|Celtic fans show their support for Neil Lennon in 2011]]\nIn 2011, Neil Lennon was subject to a terror campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1363205/Lennon-quit-Celtic-Parkhead-boss-assess-future-terror-threat.html |title=Lennon may quit Celtic: Parkhead boss will assess his future after terror threat |work=Mail Online |date=5 March 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011 |first=John |last=Greechan}}</ref><ref name=Heraldbomb>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/police-in-hunt-for-celtic-bomb-fiend-1.1097224 |title=Police in hunt for Celtic bomb fiend |work=Herald Scotland |date=20 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> In January he, along with two other [[Northern Irish]], [[Catholic]], Celtic players [[Niall McGinn]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Ewan |title=Neil Lennon brushes aside bullets threat as Celtic ease past Berwick |work=The Guardian |date=10 January 2011 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jan/09/berwick-rangers-celtic-scottish-cup}}</ref> and [[Paddy McCourt]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-12168533 |title=Bullets in post target Celtic footballer Paddy McCourt |work=BBC News |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> were sent packages containing bullets in the post. In March and April two [[parcel bomb]]s were sent to high-profile fans of Celtic and two bombs were sent to Lennon. [[Trish Godman]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] and [[Paul McBride]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], who had represented Celtic in their court cases with the SFA, were both sent bombs through the [[Royal Mail]]. All of the devices were addressed to their places of work.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-13141592 |title=Neil Lennon parcel bomb 'cowardly act' |work=BBC News |date=20 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> The bombs, described by [[Strathclyde Police]] as being designed to \"kill or maim\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/celtic-football-boss-targeted-by-parcel-bomb-20110421-1dp5g.html |title=Celtic football boss targeted by parcel bomb |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> were widely condemned by footballing and political authorities. [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] leader, [[Iain Gray]], described the act as \"terrorism\" and [[First Minister of Scotland]] [[Alex Salmond]] said that, \"It is time to remember what we value in society, and unite to condemn those who use football as a pretext for their pathetic and dangerous prejudices.\"<ref name=quotes:bombs>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-13141898 |title=In quotes: Reaction to Celtic bomb threats |work=BBC News |date=20 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=quotes:bombs /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-13156498 |title=Lennon parcel bomb 'appalling act' says David Cameron |work=BBC News |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> Lennon and his family had to receive 24-hour police protection because of the bombs and threats.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/2011/03/05/latest-death-threat-against-neil-lennon-could-make-him-think-about-future-at-celtic-says-coach-alan-thompson-86908-22967583/ |title=Latest death threat against Neil Lennon could make him think about his Celtic future, says Alan Thompson |work=Daily Record |date=5 March 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> He also had to receive police protection at matches due to the threats against him.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-13159462 |title=Celtic fans offer Neil Lennon support after parcel bomb |work=BBC News |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> However, this did not stop a man at a match against Hearts at [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle]] running onto the pitch and attacking him. Lennon was uninjured, and the man was charged with assault and breach of the peace, both aggravated by religious prejudice.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-13368945 |title=Celtic manager Neil Lennon attack suspect in court |work=BBC News |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate = 20 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312====\nThe 2011\u201312 season saw Celtic make a poor start to their league campaign. Despite rising concerns about their financial situation, Rangers under new manager [[Ally McCoist]] topped the league table for the first few months. Celtic were run ragged by Rangers in the first Old Firm game of the season, a 4\u20132 win for the Ibrox club on 18 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|date=18 September 2011|title=Rangers 4 Celtic 2: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/8771949/Rangers-4-Celtic-2-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> By October 2011, Celtic were 15 points behind Rangers in the league, albeit Rangers had played two more games than Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Title success can enhance Celtic hunger - Alan Thompson|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17639324|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>  On 15 October 2011 at Rugby Park, Celtic trailed 0\u20133 at half-time to Kilmarnock. Lennon later admitted that had Celtic conceded a further goal he would have resigned.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Neil Lennon admits he would have resigned if Celtic had conceded another goal against Kilmarnock|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/8931544/Neil-Lennon-admits-he-would-have-resigned-if-Celtic-had-conceded-another-goal-against-Kilmarnock.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 October 2013|date=2 December 2011}}</ref> Instead, Celtic rallied in the second half and two goals from [[Anthony Stokes]] and a header from Charlie Mulgrew secured an unlikely 3\u20133 draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kilmarnock 3 Celtic 3: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/8829105/Kilmarnock-3-Celtic-3-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 October 2013|date=15 October 2011}}</ref>  Celtic began to find form, and by Christmas had closed the gap between themselves and Rangers to one point.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 2 Kilmarnock 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16229733|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> This run included a 1\u20130 win over Hearts on 10 December 2011 where [[Victor Wanyama]], signed from Belgium club [[Beerschot AC|Beerschot]] for \u00a3900,000 in July,<ref>{{cite web|last=McGuigan|first=Thomas|title=Kenya's Victor Wanyama shines for Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22253408|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=22 April 2013}}</ref> scored his first goal for Celtic with a powerful 25-yard shot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wonderful Wanyama delights Celts with his first goal|url=http://www.extratime.es/news/52/wonderful-wanyama-delights-celts-with-his-first-goal|work=Extra Time|accessdate=18 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019093908/http://www.extratime.es/news/52/wonderful-wanyama-delights-celts-with-his-first-goal|archivedate=19 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In the same match, Hearts were awarded a controversial penalty in the last minute but Fraser Forster saved [[Eggert Jonsson]]'s penalty kick.<ref>{{cite web|last=Conaghan|first=Martin|title=Celtic 1 Hearts 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16015615|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=10 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[Joe Ledley]] goal on 28 December 2011 gave Celtic a 1\u20130 win over Rangers at Parkhead, and saw them go top of the table two points clear of Rangers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=Celtic 1 Rangers 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16281414|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>  By February 2012, Celtic had increased their lead to four points.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 1 Inverness CT 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16884902|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> The title was then all but secured when Rangers entered into [[Administration (British football)|administration]] on 14 February 2012, with the Ibrox club incurring a ten-point deduction from the Scottish Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers' 10-point deduction confirmed by SPL|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17032099|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> Celtic's unbeaten league run continued up to the next Old Firm game on 25 March 2012 when a poor performance exacerbated by several contentious refereeing decisions saw Rangers win 3\u20132 and prevent their rivals clinching the league title that day.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Rangers 3 Celtic 2|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17419735|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=25 March 2012}}</ref> The title was eventually secured in style a couple of weeks later with an emphatic 6\u20130 win over Kilmarnock at Rugby Park, Gary Hooper and Charlie Mulgrew both scoring twice.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Kimarnock 0 Celtic 6|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17570842|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=7 April 2012}}</ref>  Celtic's next league fixture saw them comfortably beat Rangers 3\u20130 in a party atmosphere at Parkhead in a match more notable for the Celtic fans colourful banners mocking Rangers on-going financial problems rather than events on the pitch.<ref>{{cite web|last=McHugh|first=Joe|title=Green Brigade show Rangers no mercy|url=http://videocelts.com/2012/04/blogs/green-brigade-show-no-mercy|work=Video Celts|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Celtic stroll past Rangers in season's final Old Firm match|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/apr/29/celtic-rangers-scottish-premier-league|accessdate=18 October 2013|work=The Guardian|date=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=English|first=Tom|title=Badly beaten, cruelly goaded Ibrox men endure longest day|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/tom-english-badly-beaten-cruelly-goaded-ibrox-men-endure-longest-day-1-2264705|website=The Scotsman|accessdate=10 August 2015|date=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe domestic cup tournaments proved a source of disappointment in the 2011\u201312 season. Celtic reached the League Cup final and were strong favourites to win against unfancied Kilmarnock.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theawayend.net/articles/football/the-away-end-archive/1055-full-preview-celtic-v-kilmarnock |title=Full Preview: Celtic v Kilmarnock |publisher=Theawayend.net |date=18 March 2001 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112044639/http://www.theawayend.net/articles/football/the-away-end-archive/1055-full-preview-celtic-v-kilmarnock |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  However, Celtic were uninspiring on the day and a headed goal six minutes from the end by [[Dieter van Tornhout]] won the League Cup for the Ayrshire side. In the Scottish Cup, Celtic reached the semi-final and were drawn to play Hearts. Again, Celtic were not at their best and [[Craig Beattie]]'s stoppage time penalty secured a 2\u20131 win for ''The Jambos''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay |first=Clive |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17649430 |title=Celtic 1-2 Hearts |work=BBC Sport |date=15 April 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nCeltic qualified for the Europa League group stages in 2011\u201312 in bizarre circumstances. Swiss side [[FC Sion|Sion]] defeated Celtic 3\u20131 on aggregate in the qualifying tie,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14569496 |title=Sion 3-1 Celtic (agg 3-1) |work=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2011 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  however Sion were thrown out of the tournament by UEFA due to them fielding ineligible players in the two games against Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ewan Murray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/sep/02/celtic-europa-league-fc-sion |title=Celtic back in Europa League after successful protest against FC Sion |work=The Guardian |date=2 September 2011 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> Celtic were reinstated, eventually finishing third in Group I, behind [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] and [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] and ahead of [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Campbell |first=Andy |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/9662325.stm |title=Udinese v Celtic as it happened |work=BBC News |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Despite failing to progress from the group stages of the Europa League, Celtic had a respectable campaign and their performances on the European stage are considered to have acted as a catalyst for the improvement in their domestic form as the season progressed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16081808 |accessdate=3 September 2014 |work=BBC Sport |title=Udinese 1 Celtic 1 |last=Conaghan |first=Martin |date=15 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/neil-lennon-celtic-have-fallen-in-love-with-the-europa-league.15995841 |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=3 September 2014 |last=Grant |first=Michael |date=30 November 2011 |title=Neil Lennon: Celtic have fallen in love with the Europa League}}</ref>\n\n===A new era===\n\n====2012\u201313====\n[[File:Victor Wanyama 2012.jpg|180px|thumb|left|Victor Wanyama - voted the SPL Young Player of the Year in 2013]]\nThe summer of 2012 saw extraordinary developments in Scottish football. Rangers, who were being  pursued by [[HM Revenue and Customs]] (HMRC) for alleged unpaid tax, effectively went into [[liquidation]] on 12 June 2012 when HMRC rejected the club's proposed [[Company Voluntary Arrangement]] (CVA).<ref>{{cite news|author=John Mcgarry |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2158089/Rangers-liquidation-danger-CVA-deal-rejected.html |title=Rangers liquidation danger after CVA deal is rejected |work=Mail Online |date=13 June 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> A new company was quickly formed and the club re-constituted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football.co.uk/rangers/reformed_rangers_meet_brechin_in_challenge_cup_rss3069463.shtml |title=Reformed Rangers meet Brechin in Challenge Cup - Rangers News from |publisher=football.co.uk |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> However, despite an at-times hysterical [[Media of Scotland|media]] campaign making references to financial \"Armageddon\" for the other clubs in Scotland,<ref>{{cite news|author=Stephen Mcgowan |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2168730/Rangers-booted-SPL-Scottish-rivals-reject-newco-appeal.html |title=Rangers booted out of the SPL after Scottish rivals reject newco appeal |work=Mail Online |date=4 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ewan Murray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/aug/03/spl-clubs-rangers-fans-celtic |title=SPL clubs ready to bridge Rangers gap but fans must show their support |work=the Guardian |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> the re-formed Rangers were not allowed re-entry to the Scottish Premier League and instead were placed in the lowest tier of the Scottish Football League, the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Third Division]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Brian Marjoribanks |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2173130/Rangers-voted-Third-Division.html |title=Rangers voted into Third Division |work=Mail Online |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIgnoring the ongoing furore surrounding Rangers' financial crisis, Celtic went about their 2012\u201313 league campaign in a steady if not always inspiring manner.<ref name=\"wsc1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/wsc-daily/1163-june-2013/9868-2012-13-season-in-review-celtic |title=2012-13 season in review: Celtic |work=When Saturday Comes |date=9 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112052057/http://www.wsc.co.uk/wsc-daily/1163-june-2013/9868-2012-13-season-in-review-celtic |archive-date=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Motherwell, Inverness Caley Thistle and briefly Hibernian all either had spells at the top of the table, or thereabouts, but by Christmas Celtic had found a steady run of form to pull themselves comfortably clear of the pack.<ref name=\"wsc1\" />  Celtic eventually clinched their 44th League title on 21 April 2013 with a 4\u20131 win over Inverness CT at Parkhead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/celtic-clinch-title-in-style-2013-04-21/ |title=Celtic clinch title in style |publisher=Spfl.co.uk |date=21 April 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> Celtic's run in the League Cup saw them comfortably dispose of [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] (4\u20131)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19632469 |title=Celtic 4-1 Raith Rovers |work=BBC Sport|date=25 September 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> and St Johnstone (5\u20130)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20053650 |title=Celtic 5-0 St Johnstone |work=BBC Sport |date=30 October 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> in the earlier rounds. St Mirren, however, pulled off an unexpected but deserved 3\u20132 win over Celtic in the semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell |first=Andy |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21106906 |title=St Mirren 3-2 Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=27 January 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the Scottish Cup, Celtic knocked out [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]], Raith Rovers,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21218450 |title=Raith Rovers 0\u20133 Celtic |first=Stevie |last=Miller |work=BBC Sport |date=3 February 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> and St Mirren<ref name = \"mirren\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556779 |first=Kenny |last=Crawford |title=St Mirren 1\u20132 Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> in the earlier rounds. In the semi-final at Hampden Park, Celtic won a thrilling match by 4\u20133 after extra time against Dundee United.<ref name = \"united\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22056531 |title=Dundee Utd 3\u20134 Celtic |first=Clive |last=Lindsay |work=BBC Sport |date=14 April 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> Celtic met Hibernian in the Scottish Cup final on 26 May 2013.  For the first time in its history, the Cup Final was played on a Sunday.<ref name = \"sunday\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16685196|title=Sunday switch for 2013 Scottish Cup final|work=BBC Sport |date=23 January 2012|accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref> This was done to comply with UEFA regulations which prohibit televised matches being played on the same day as the [[UEFA Champions League Final]].  Celtic won the cup and clinched a League and Cup double with a 3\u20130 win, Gary Hooper scoring twice in the first half before Joe Ledley added a third late on in the second half.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22585339 |title=Scottish Cup final: Hibernian 0-3 Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs Scottish Champions from the previous season, Celtic took part in the 2012\u201313 Champions League, negotiating two qualifying rounds to qualify for the tournament proper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19424943 |title=Champions League: Celtic to face Barcelona, Benfica & Spartak |work=BBC Sport |date=30 August 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> On 2 October 2012, Celtic achieved their first ever away win in the group stages of the Champions League with a 3\u20132 win in Russia over Spartak Moscow, Georgios Samaras scoring the winning goal in the 90th minute.<ref>{{cite news|author=Stephen Mcgowan |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2211872/Spartak-Moscow-2-Celtic-3.html |title=Spartak Moscow 2 Celtic 3 |work=Mail Online |date=2 October 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Celtic's home match with Barcelona in November 2012 coincided with the week of Celtic's 125th Anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dave Wood |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2229241/Lionel-Messi-Xavi-Hernandez-Andres-Iniesta-join-Celtics-125th-birthday-celebrations.html |title=Lionel Messi, Xavi Hernandez and Andres Iniesta join in Celtic's 125th birthday celebrations |work=Mail Online |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  As such, an ''[[Ultras]]'' styled section of the Celtic support called the [[Green Brigade]] organised a full stadium pre-match card display (a ''[[tifo]]'') to celebrate the club's 125th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Incredible pre-match display from supporters |url=http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3319 |work=celticfc.net |publisher=Celtic F.C. |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112134748/http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3319 |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The display featured a [[Celtic cross]], green and white hoops and ''125 Celtic'' in written form, with supporters earning the praise of club chairman [[Peter Lawwell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Peter Lawwell congratulates team and support on collective effort |url=http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3325 |work=celticfc.net |publisher=Celtic F.C. |date=8 November 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112134645/http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3325 |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  A memorable night was completed when goals from Victor Wanyama and 18-year-old striker [[Tony Watt]] gave Celtic a shock 2\u20131 win over Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20150451 |title=Celtic 2-1 Barcelona |work=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> Goalkeeper Fraser Forster produced an outstanding performance in the game, winning the praise of the Spanish media who nicknamed him \"''La Gran Muralla''\" (\"The Great Wall\").<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/11/08/fraser-forster-great-wall_n_2091816.html |title=Fraser Forster Great Wall |work=Huffington Post | date = 8 November 2012 | accessdate = 8 November 2012 }}</ref>  Celtic secured their progress to the knock-out stages of the Champions League on 5 December 2012 with a 2\u20131 home win over Spartak Moscow, [[Kris Commons]] scoring the winning goal in 82 minutes with a penalty.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20522174 |title=Celtic 2-1 Spartak Moscow |work=BBC Sport |date=5 December 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Celtic were drawn against Juventus but succumbed to 5\u20130 aggregate defeat in the Spring of 2013 to go out of the tournament. Despite the emphatic scoreline over the two legs, Celtic were not outclassed by their Italian opponents in terms of general play but while Juventus defended with a ruthless defiance, Celtic in contrast shipped their goals all far too easily.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Mcgowan |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2289315/Juventus-2-Celtic-0-agg-5-0--Neil-Lennons-Champions-League-dream-over.html |title=Juventus 2 Celtic 0 (agg 5-0): Neil Lennon's Champions League dream over |work=Mail Online |date=6 March 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Despite the result against Juventus, Celtic and Neil Lennon won praise for their Champions League campaign.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tony |last=Haggerty |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-boss-neil-lennon-just-2670834 |title=Celtic boss Neil Lennon is just like my old man Harry in the dugout, claims ex-England star Jamie Redknapp |work=Daily Record |date=3 November 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107032139/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-boss-neil-lennon-just-2670834 |archivedate=7 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Jeff Stelling |url=http://www.skysports.com/opinion/story/0,25212,12088_8235533,00.html |title=Celtic win over Barcelona compels Jeff Stelling to tackle a challenging problem |work=Sky Sports |date=8 November 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Jeff Stelling |url=http://www.skysports.com/opinion/story/0,25212,12088_8313877,00.html |title=Man City could learn a lot from Celtic's Champions League exploits |work=Sky Sports |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314====\nOver the summer, Gary Hooper and [[Kelvin Wilson]] were sold to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] respectively, while the highly rated Victor Wanyama was sold to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for a Scottish record fee of \u00a312.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic in record breaking transfer sale as Wanyama heads south|url=http://www.scotzine.com/2013/07/celtic-in-record-breaking-transfer-sale-as-wanyama-heads-south/|work=Scotzine|accessdate=7 May 2014|date=11 July 2013}}</ref>  Neil Lennon rebuilt his squad by signing [[Virgil van Dijk]] and [[Amido Bald\u00e9]] in the summer, and [[Teemu Pukki]] from [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] on transfer deadline day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic sign Teemu Pukki from Schalke on four-year deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23832031|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kris Commons 2012.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Kris Commons \u2013 Celtic's top scorer in 2014 and Scottish Player of the Year]]\nCeltic again started their season playing in the qualifying rounds of the Champions League, knocking out Northern Irish champions [[Cliftonville F.C.|Cliftonville]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 2 Cliftonville 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23324257|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=23 July 2013}}</ref> and Swedish side [[IF Elfsborg]] to reach the final play-off round.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=Elfsborg 0 Celtic 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23513157|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=7 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic were drawn with Kazakh champions [[Shakhter Karagandy]] and found themselves losing the first leg away in [[Karagandy]] 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grant|first=Michael|title=Shakhter Karagandy 2 Celtic 0: stirring cocktail leaves Lennon's side groggy|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/shakhter-karagandy-2-celtic-0-stirring-cocktail-leaves-lennon-s-side-groggy.1377061269|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=21 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic rallied in the return leg at Celtic Park in the home leg, overcoming the 2\u20130 deficit to level the aggregate score thanks to goals either side of half-time by Kris Commons and Georgios Samaras. [[James Forrest (footballer)|James Forrest]] completed the comeback for Celtic with a 90th-minute strike, seeing Celtic progress to the Group stages.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Celtic 3 Shakhter Karagandy 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23776602|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=28 August 2013}}</ref> The campaign from then on was dismal though; winning only once with a 2\u20131 home win over Ajax,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont|first=Alasdair|title=Celtic 2 Ajax 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24614436|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=22 October 2013}}</ref> and slumping to a 6\u20131 rout away against Barcelona in the final group match.<ref name=\"thrash\">{{cite web|last=Lamont|first=Alasdair|title=Barcelona 6 Celtic 1 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25303700|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=11 December 2013}}</ref>  That game saw Celtic concede the most goals they had ever done in a single European tie, and equalled their previous heaviest defeat in Europe (5-0 against [[FC Artmedia Bratislava|Artmedia Bratislava]]).<ref name=\"thrash\" />\n\nThe domestic campaign had ups and downs; towards the end of February, Celtic had not lost a single game in the league,<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Eric|title=The prospect of going a whole season unbeaten is driving the Celtic players on|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/football/366845/The-prospect-of-going-a-whole-season-unbeaten-is-driving-the-Celtic-players-on|work=Daily Star|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=24 February 2014}}</ref> and drew just twice against Dundee United and Hibernian. Their league success did not translate to cup competition however; going out of the League Cup (0\u20131 to [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]),<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 0 - 1 Morton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24122182|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=24 September 2014}}</ref> and the [[Scottish Cup]](1\u20132 to [[Aberdeen]]),<ref>{{cite web|last=MacDonald|first=Calum|title=Celtic 1 - 2 Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25995228|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=8 February 2014}}</ref> both at Celtic Park. Celtic also struggled to find a suitable strike partner for [[Anthony Stokes]], forcing Kris Commons into a striking role. Neil Lennon signed former Hibs striker [[Leigh Griffiths]] on [[Transfer window|transfer deadline day]] in January 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25977707|title=Wolves striker Griffiths joins Celtic|work=BBC Sport|date=31 January 2014}}</ref> as well as [[Stefan Johansen]] earlier in the month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/stefan-johansen-signs-for-celtic-1-3268643|last=Walker|first=Mark||title=Stefan Johansen signs for Celtic|work=The Scotsman |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> After being unable to reach an agreement on a new contract, Joe Ledley left Celtic for [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ledley Joins Palace |url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/2014/january/ledley-joins-palace/ |work=Crystal Palace FC |date=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2014, goalkeeper Fraser Forster set a new a club-record of 11 league clean sheets in a row,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26011023 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 February 2014 |title=Celtic: Neil Lennon applauds record-breaking Fraser Forster}}</ref> surpassing a record of 10 clean sheets set by [[Charlie Shaw (footballer, born 1885)|Charlie Shaw]] in the 1921\u201322 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11787/9147994/neil-lennon-proud-to-break-92-year-old-record-in-win-over-st-mirren |title=Neil Lennon proud to break 92-year-old record in win over St Mirren  |accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>  On 22 February, he broke [[Bobby Clark (footballer)|Bobby Clark]]'s Scottish League record of 1155 minutes without conceding a goal in a league match. Celtic won 2\u20130 away at Hearts, and Forster racked up his 13th consecutive clean sheet in the league.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Premiership LIVE: Hearts v Celtic |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/scottish-premiership-live-hearts-v-3172172 |work=Daily Record |accessdate=22 February 2014 |date=22 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425003512/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/scottish-premiership-live-hearts-v-3172172 |archivedate=25 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hearts 0 Celtic 2: Double thumbs up for Celtic at Tynecastle as Fraser Forster sets new record and Leigh Griffiths strikes |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/hearts-0-celtic-2-double-3172864 |work=Daily Record |accessdate=1 March 2014 |date=22 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309102535/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/hearts-0-celtic-2-double-3172864 |archivedate=9 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \nForster's clean sheet run finally ended on 1,256 minutes against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] on 25 February 2014, as Aberdeen defeated Celtic 2\u20131 to end their unbeaten run in the league.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25892139 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=26 February 2014 |title=Aberdeen 2-1 Celtic}}</ref>\n\nCeltic finished the season as league champions again, their third consecutive [[Scottish Professional Football League|Scottish League]] title,<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Alan|title=Celtic crush Partick Thistle to make it three SPL titles in a row|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/mar/26/celtic-partick-thistle-scottish-premier-league-match-report|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 April 2014|date=26 March 2014}}</ref> scoring 102 goals in the process.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 3 Dundee Utd 1: champion Hoops take home the trophy|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/celtic-3-dundee-utd-1-celtic-confirm-champion-status-with-united-win-and-take-home-th.1399815846|work=Herald Online|accessdate=12 May 2014|date=11 May 2014}}</ref>  Kris Commons was the top scorer in Scotland, netting 32 goals, and won both the [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|PFA Scotland]] and [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers']] Player of the Year awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic's Kris Commons named Premiership player of year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27183434|work=BBC Sport|date=28 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic's Kris Commons is football writers' player of year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27362516|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 May 2014|date=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 2014, Neil Lennon announced that he was leaving Celtic after four years as manager. \"I have parted company with Celtic,\" the 42-year-old Northern Irishman said in a brief statement, adding, \"The club are in a very strong position and I wish the fans and the club all the very best for the future.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=McLaughlin|first=Chris|title=Neil Lennon ends his four-year spell as manager|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27519596|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=22 May 2014|date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Ronny Deila (2014\u20132016)==\nNorwegian [[Ronny Deila]] was appointed manager of Celtic on 6 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27718845 |title=Celtic confirm Ronny Deila as new manager |work=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/6007 |title=Ronny Deila appointed as new Celtic manager |publisher=Celtic FC |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>  He signed a 12-month rolling contract with the club,<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2650572/Celtic-appoint-Norwegian-Ronny-Deila-new-manager.html|title= Celtic appoint Norwegian Ronny Deila as new manager on 12-month rolling contract|date=6 June 2014|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref> with former Celtic midfielder and Scotland international [[John Collins (footballer, born 1968)|John Collins]] appointed as his assistant.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27890417 |title=Celtic: John Collins appointed as Ronny Deila's assistant boss |work=BBC Sport |date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u201315===\nAfter going unbeaten on a pre-season tour in Austria,<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson|first=Mark|title=Ronny Deila: We'll be positive in Iceland|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/6223|publisher=Celtic FC |accessdate=15 July 2014|date=13 July 2014}}</ref> Deila's first competitive match as manager of Celtic, a Champions League qualifying tie away against [[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Reykjav\u00edkur|KR Reykjavik]] on 15 July 2014, ended in a 1\u20130 win with midfielder [[Callum McGregor]] scoring the decisive goal on 84 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|last=McVake|first=Roddie|title=KR Reykjav\u00edk 0 - 1 Celtic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28278531|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 January 2015|date=15 July 2014}}</ref>  Celtic eased to a 4\u20130 win in the return match in Scotland,<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 4-0 KR Reykjavik (agg 5-0)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28331345|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 August 2014|date=22 July 2014}}</ref> but were comprehensively beaten and outplayed in the next qualifying round, losing 6\u20131 on aggregate to [[Legia Warsaw]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28656118 |accessdate=1 August 2014 |title=Celtic 0 - 2 Legia Warsaw |date=6 August 2014 |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont}}</ref>  Despite this, Celtic were given a reprieve when it was discovered that Legia had fielded an ineligible player in the second leg, [[Bartosz Bereszy\u0144ski]] coming on as a substitute in the last four minutes. UEFA punished the Polish club by awarding the game 3\u20130 to Celtic, levelling the aggregate score at 4\u20134 and seeing the Scottish champions progress on away goals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic reinstated to Champions League after Uefa punishes Legia Warsaw|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/08/celtic-reinstated-champions-league-uefa-legia-warsaw|work=The Guardian|accessdate=8 August 2014|date=8 August 2014}}</ref> Despite this astonishing piece of luck, Celtic failed abjectly to take advantage in the final qualifier against [[NK Maribor|Maribor]], losing 2\u20131 on aggregate to drop down to the Europa League.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 0 - 1 NK Maribor|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28927666|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 August 2014|date=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:FC Salzburg gegen Celtic Glasgow 33.JPG|thumb|left|350px|Celtic in action away to [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] during the group stage of their [[UEFA Europa League]] campaign in 2014.]]\nCeltic were unconvincing in the early stages of the league as well,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronny Deila looking for revenge as Celtic travel to Motherwell|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11787/9593890/scottish-premiership-ronny-deila-looking-for-revenge-as-celtic-travel-to-motherwell|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=6 December 2014}}</ref> but improved as the season progressed and also qualified from their Europa League group.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic 1 - 3 FC Red Bull Salzburg|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30204414|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=27 November 2014}}</ref> Deila won the Manager of the Month award for November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronny Deila is manager of the month for November|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30334346|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=7 December 2014}}</ref>  By February 2015, Celtic had won 15 of their last 17 domestic games<ref>{{cite web|last=McGarry|first=John|title=Ronny Deila admits first few months as Celtic manager were 'tough to handle'|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2943417/Ronny-Deila-admits-months-Celtic-manager-tough-handle.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=7 February 2015}}</ref> and comfortably defeated Rangers 2\u20130 in the semi-final of the League Cup.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=Ewan|title=Celtic push past feeble Rangers in first Old Firm game for three years|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/feb/01/celtic-rangers-scottish-league-cup-semi-final|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=1 February 2015}}</ref> Celtic played [[Inter Milan]] in the round of 16 stage of the Europa League, rallying to draw 3\u20133 at Parkhead from an early 0\u20132 deficit in a pulsating encounter,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fosyth|first=Roddy|title=Celtic 3 Inter Milan 3, match report: John Guidetti scores last-gasp equaliser to keep hosts alive in tie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/11423375/Celtic-3-Inter-Milan-3-match-report-John-Guidetti-scores-last-gasp-equaliser-to-keep-hosts-alive-in-tie.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=19 February 2015}}</ref> then losing 1\u20130 in [[Milan]] to go out on aggregate despite a highly credible performance.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mullen|first1=Scott|title=Inter 1 Celtic 0 (agg: 4-3): Hoops exit Europe after Guarin's wonder strike|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/celtic/inter-1-celtic-0-agg-4-3-hoops-exit-europe-after-guarins-wonder-strike-198656n.119510154|work=Evening Times|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=26 February 2015}}</ref> In the league, Celtic thrashed second-placed Aberdeen 4\u20130 on 1 March to go six points clear with a game in hand and a vastly superior goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic win is important mental lift - Ronny Deila|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31685655|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=1 March 2015}}</ref> It was Celtic's eighth consecutive win in the league, and the turn around in form saw previous critics of Deila review their opinion of him.  Former Celtic striker [[John Hartson]] had branded Deila as \"clueless\" in October, but now stated that Deila has \"..turned it round to his credit and they\u2019re playing some brilliant football at the moment\".<ref>{{cite web|last=MacArthur|first=Scott|title=Celtic legend John Hartson: \"I was wrong about Ronny Deila & Celts can lift The Treble\"|url=http://www.talkingbaws.com/2015/03/02/celtic-legend-john-hartson-i-was-wrong-about-ronny-deila-celts-can-lift-the-treble/|work=Talking Baws|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=2 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:One final Ronny Roar (26998950046).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Deila celebrating winning the 2015\u201316 Scottish Premiership league title in May 2016]]\nIn March 2015, Celtic agreed a new kit deal with [[Boston]]-based sportswear manufacturer [[New Balance]] to replace [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] from the start of the 2015\u201316 season.  It is believed to be the biggest kit contract in the club's history, outdoing the decade-long deal with Nike who paid Celtic \u00a35&nbsp;million a year to make their shirts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic confirm kit deal with New Balance|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/celtic-confirm-kit-deal-with-new-balance-1-3710125|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=5 March 2015|date=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeila won his first trophy at Celtic on 15 March; Celtic's defeating Dundee United 2\u20130 in the [[2015 Scottish League Cup Final|League Cup final]]. Kris Commons opened the scoring in the first half and James Forrest steered the ball into the net from 20 yards out to double Celtic's lead in the second half.<ref>{{cite web|last=McGowan|first=Stephen|title=Dundee United 0-2 Celtic: Kris Commons and James Forrest land The Bhoys QTS Scottish League Cup to keep treble dreams alive|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2996008/Dundee-United-0-2-Celtic-Kris-Commons-James-Forrest-land-Bhoys-QTS-Scottish-League-Cup-treble-dreams-alive.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=16 March 2015|date=15 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Dundee Utd 0 - 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31785677|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 March 2015|date=15 March 2015}}</ref>  Celtic's bid for a domestic treble ended when they were beaten by Inverness Caledonian Thistle in the [[2014\u201315 Scottish Cup|semi-final of the Scottish Cup]] on 19 April 2015.  The match however was controversial, with Inverness defender [[Josh Meekings]]' deliberate handball of Leigh Griffiths' goal-bound header just before half-time going unpunished by the match officials.  Insult was added to injury in the second half when Craig Gordon was sent off (correctly) for fouling [[Marley Watkins]] in the penalty box.  [[Greg Tansey]] converted the resultant penalty to level the tie at 1\u20131. Down to ten men, Celtic struggled for the rest of the match and eventually lost 3\u20132 after extra-time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Inverness CT 3 - 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32089585|date=19 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic boss says referee mistake is hard to take in Cup semi-final|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32373912|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 April 2015|date=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nCeltic clinched their fourth successive league title in May,<ref name=\"ltit15\">{{cite web|title=Celtic win Scottish Premiership title after Aberdeen lose|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32566809|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 May 2015|date=2 May 2015}}</ref> with manager Deila commenting \"We've had a terrific few months - we deserved to win the league.\"<ref name=\"ltit15\" />\n\n===2015\u201316===\nCeltic began the season again attempting to qualify for the Champions League.  They knocked out [[Stjarnan]] from Iceland<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Stjarnan 1 - 4 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33609346|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=22 July 2015 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> and [[Qaraba\u011f FK|Qaraba\u011f]] from Azerbaijan in the early qualifying rounds,<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=FK Qarabag 0 - 0 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33755230|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=5 August 2015}}</ref> but lost 4\u20133 on aggregate to Swedish side [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] in the final play-off round. This meant for the second successive season, Celtic dropped in to the Europa League.<ref name=\"el1516\">{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=Malmo 2 - 0 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34047527|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=25 August 2015}}</ref> Celtic's Europa League campaign was poor and littered with individual errors which contributed to dropped points in every match.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lamont|first1=Alasdair|title=Fenerbah\u00e7e 1 - 1 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35020011|accessdate=12 February 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=10 December 2015}}</ref> Celtic failed to qualify, finishing bottom of their group, and was the first time Celtic went through a group stage of a European competition without recording a single victory.<ref name=\"el1516\" />\n\nDeila was criticised for Celtic's poor European campaign,<ref>{{cite news|last=Lindsay|first=Matthew|title=Pat Bonner: Ronny Deila must make wins his priority in Europe - not playing \"the Celtic way\" |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/14098141.Pat_Bonner__Ronny_Deila_must_make_wins_his_priority_in_Europe___not_playing__quot_the_Celtic_way_quot_/|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=Herald Scotland|date=23 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Berry|first=Gavin|title=Former Celtic stopper Marc Rieper: Sorry Tom, Ronny Deila has been a disaster in Europe and that is the ONLY stage that counts|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-celtic-stopper-marc-rieper-7347464#eb0C2akBl6oibkHP.97|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=Daily Record|date=11 February 2016}}</ref> and a series of indifferent performances in the league saw him placed under further scrutiny.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cameron|first=Neil|title=Ronny Deila pleads for calm but will he become the first Celtic manager going for a Double to be sacked?|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14251493.Ronny_Deila_pleads_for_calm_but_will_he_become_the_first_Celtic_manager_going_for_a_Double_to_be_sacked_/|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=Herald Scotland|date=4 February 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, Celtic suffered a 5\u20134 loss on penalties to Old Firm rivals Rangers in the semi-final of the Scottish Cup, after a 2\u20132 extra-time draw in which Celtic fought back against the newly promoted [[Scottish Championship|Championship]] side twice to level the score.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Rangers 2 Celtic 2: Rangers triumph 5-4 in epic penalty shootout to reach Scottish Cup final|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/17/rangers-2-celtic-2-rangers-triumph-5-4-in-epic-penalty-shootout/|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Telegraph|date=17 April 2016}}</ref> Three days later, Deila announced his resignation from his post once Celtic had finished the season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fowler|first=Craig|title=Ronny Deila to leave Celtic at the end of the season|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/ronny-deila-to-leave-celtic-at-the-end-of-the-season-1-4105304|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=20 April 2016}}</ref> Nevertheless, Deila led Celtic to their fifth consecutive League championship, clinching the title on 8 May with a 3&ndash;2 win over nearest challengers Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Celtic clinch Scottish Premiership title with victory over Aberdeen|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/05/08/celtic-clinch-scottish-premiership-title-with-victory-over-aberd/|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Telegraph|date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Celtic finished the season a week later with an emphatic 7\u20130 win over Motherwell, seeing Deila depart the club on a high note after two years in charge. The seventh goal in that game was scored by debutant [[Jack Aitchison]], who at 16 years and 71 days old became both the youngest player ever to represent the club in a competitive match and the youngest goalscorer.<ref name=\"aitch\">{{cite news|last=Hamouda|first=Omar|title=Jack Aitchison becomes Celtic\u2019s youngest ever goalscorer|url=http://www.squawka.com/news/jack-aitchison-becomes-celtics-youngest-ever-goalscorer/670677|accessdate=15 May 2016|work=Squawka|date=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jack Aitchison|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2015/teams/player=250081673/index.html|website=UEFA.com|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Celtic had been generally mediocre, striker [[Leigh Griffiths]] had an outstanding season, scoring 40 goals and winning both the [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|PFA Scotland]] and [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers' Association]] Player of the Year awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic striker Leigh Griffiths wins Scottish Premiership Player of the Season|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11787/10301127/celtic-striker-leigh-griffiths-wins-scottish-premiership-player-of-the-season|accessdate=19 November 2016|work=Sky Sports|date=1 June 2016}}</ref> The season also saw 18 year old [[Kieran Tierney]] emerge as one of the most promising prospects in Scottish football, establishing himself as first-choice left-back at Celtic and making his full international debut for Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Andrew|title=No place like home for Celtic\u2019s Kieran Tierney|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/competitions/premiership/no-place-like-home-for-celtic-s-kieran-tierney-1-4128153|accessdate=19 November 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Brendan Rodgers (2016\u2013present) ==\n[[File:Celtic FC rail seating section.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Rail seating at Celtic Park]]\nOn 20 May 2016, it was confirmed that 43-year-old [[Brendan Rodgers]] would take over at the club with immediate effect, the Irishman having previously managed [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] and Liverpool in the English Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36338244 |title=Celtic: Brendan Rodgers is appointed manager |work=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2016 |accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> In the days that followed, Chris Davies was named as assistant manager<ref name=\"brasst\">{{cite news|title=Celtic name Chris Davies as Brendan Rodgers' assistant|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36380828|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=25 May 2016}}</ref> and Glen Driscoll appointed as head of performance.<ref name=\"brhop\">{{cite news|title=Celtic appoint Glen Driscoll, who worked with Brendan Rodgers at Liverpool and Swansea, as new head of performance|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3613084/Celtic-appoint-Glen-Driscoll-worked-Brendan-Rodgers-Liverpool-Swansea-new-head-performance.html|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Mail Online|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> Both men had previously worked with Rodgers at Swansea and Liverpool.<ref name=\"brasst\" /><ref name=\"brhop\" />\n\n[[File:Cel-Zen (12) (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|300px|alt=Photograph of Brendan Rodgers|[[Brendan Rodgers]] led Celtic to two consecutive [[domestic treble]]s]]On 14 July 2016, Celtic formally unveiled their new 2,600 capacity \"[[Safe standing#Rail seats|rail seating]]\" area within Celtic Park, becoming the first British club to do so. The club had obtained a \"[[safe standing]]\" certificate 13 months earlier after years of negotiations with supporters, football authorities and Glasgow City Council. Rail seating is particularly common in Germany's Bundesliga, most notably at Borussia Dortmund's [[Westfalenstadion]], a ground with a reputation on par with Celtic Park for its intensity and atmosphere.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/scottish-premier/celtic/271667-celtic-studying-feasibility-of-standing-area-at-celtic-park/ |title=Celtic studying feasibility of standing area at Celtic Park |work=STV Sport |date=23 September 2011 |accessdate=13 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Spencer|title=Celtic become first British club to introduce safe-standing after completing construction ahead of Brendan Rodgers' first home game|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3690004/Celtic-British-club-introduce-safe-standing-completing-construction-ahead-Brendan-Rodgers-home-game.html?ITO=1490|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Mail Online|date=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic secure green light for rail seating|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/8420|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Celtic FC|date=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stevens|first1=Samuel|title=Celtic reveal new 2,600 capacity safe-standing area with Brendan Rodgers set for first home match as manager|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/celtic-reveal-new-2600-capacity-safe-standing-area-with-brendan-rodgers-set-for-first-home-match-as-a7136581.html|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Independent|date=14 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016&ndash;17===\nCeltic's first competitive match under Rodgers, saw the team [[Lincoln Red Imps 1\u20130 Celtic|lose 1&ndash;0]] against [[Gibraltar|Gibraltan]] minnows [[Lincoln Red Imps F.C.|Lincoln Red Imps]] in the first leg of the Second Round Champions League qualifiers, a result described by ''The Scotsman'' as a \"humiliation\" and mooted by other media as being one of the worst results in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lincoln Red Imps 1 - 0 Celtic: Stunning upset in Rodgers\u2019 first match|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/lincoln-red-imps-1-0-celtic-stunning-upset-in-rodgers-first-match-1-4175957|accessdate=30 July 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=12 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cameron|first=Neil|title=Lincoln Red Imps 1, Celtic 0: The Brendan Rodgers era begins with what could easily be seen as the club's worst ever result|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/14614532.Lincoln_Red_Imps_1__Celtic_0__The_Brendan_Rodgers_era_begins_with_what_could_easily_be_seen_as_the_club__39_s_worst_ever_result/|accessdate=30 July 2016|work=Herald Scotland|date=12 July 2016}}</ref> Celtic quickly found their feet though, winning the second leg 3&ndash;0 and going on to eliminate [[FC Astana|Astana]] and [[Hapoel Be'er Sheva F.C|Hapoel Be'er Sheva]] in the subsequent qualifying rounds to progress into the Champions League group stages for the first time since 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=English|first=Tom|title=Celtic 2 - 1 FC Astana 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36955619|accessdate=13 September 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=3 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Esplin|first=Ronnie|title=Celtic vs Hapoel Be'er Sheva: Brendan Rodgers praises major shareholder after surviving Champions League scare|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/celtic-vs-hapoel-beer-sheva-brendan-rodgers-praises-major-shareholder-after-surviving-champions-a7206711.html|accessdate=13 September 2016|work=The Independent|date=24 August 2016}}</ref> Celtic's new signings [[Scott Sinclair]] and [[Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 (French footballer)|Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9]] also helped the club make a strong start to their league campaign, with Sinclair scoring in each of the first six league matches<ref>{{cite news|title=Scott Sinclair scores again as Celtic thrash Kilmarnock|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/24/celtic-kilmarnock-scottish-premiership-match-report|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=The Guardian|date=24 September 2017}}</ref> and Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 scoring a hat-trick in Celtic's 5&ndash;1 win over newly promoted Rangers, becoming the first Celtic player to score three goals against Rangers since [[Harry Hood (footballer)|Harry Hood]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/14738379.Harry_Hood__I_spent_five_hours_in_hospital__missed_the_game_and_came_out_to_discover_my_Old_Firm_hat_trick_record_had_gone/ |work=Herald Scotland |title=Harry Hood: I spent five hours in hospital, missed the game and came out to discover my Old Firm hat-trick record had gone |first=Lindsay |last=Herron |date=13 September 2016 |accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20170701 SK Rapid Wien vs Celtic FC 1548.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Scott Sinclair]], one of Brendan Rodger's new signings, scored in each of Celtic's first six league matches of the season, and finished as top goalscorer in the Scottish Premiership]]The team's opening match in the Champions League on 13 September 2016 proved to be a humbling experience though as Barcelona delivered a footballing lesson in a 7&ndash;0 rout, the club's heaviest ever European defeat and the second-heaviest in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news|last=English|first=Tom|title=Barcelona 7 - 0 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37331224|accessdate=14 September 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=13 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alltime club records|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/club_records_overall.php|website=FitbaStats|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> A level of pride was restored in the next Champions League tie, Celtic holding [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] to a 3&ndash;3 draw at Celtic Park and ending the high-spending English club's run of ten consecutive wins, with Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 scoring twice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Daniel|title=Celtic end Manchester City\u2019s winning run with thrilling Champions League draw|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/28/celtic-manchester-city-champions-league-match-report|accessdate=19 November 2016|work=The Guardian|date=28 September 2016}}</ref> Further draws away at [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] and in the return match at Manchester City saw Celtic finish the group on three points, albeit coming fourth and going out of Europe.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic: Brendan Rodgers says Champions League campaign 'sets standard'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38228840|accessdate=13 February 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nCeltic continued their unbeaten run in domestic competitions into the New Year,<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Celtic 4 Hearts 0: Brendan Rodgers' side break unbeaten record set by Lisbon Lions in ruthless fashion|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/01/29/celtic-4-hearts-0-brendan-rodgers-side-break-unbeaten-record/|accessdate=13 February 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=29 January 2017}}</ref> during which time the club won their 100th major trophy, defeating Aberdeen 3\u20130 in the League Cup Final on 27 November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=League Cup final: Aberdeen 0-3 Celtic as it happened|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/scotland/38121946|accessdate=1 December 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=27 November 2016}}</ref> Celtic's 5&ndash;2 win away at St Johnstone on 5 February 2017 saw them extend their lead in the league to 27 points over second-placed Aberdeen, and was their 19th consecutive league win,<ref>{{cite news|title=Dembele hits hat-trick as Celtic fight back to maintain run|url=https://stv.tv/sport/football/1379967-dembele-hits-hat-trick-as-celtic-fight-back-to-maintain-run/|accessdate=14 February 2017|work=STV Sport|date=5 February 2017}}</ref> with the only points dropped in the season so far being in a 2&ndash;2 draw away at Inverness in September.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic: Brendan Rodgers still 'rankled' by draw with Inverness|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37864056|accessdate=14 February 2017|date=3 November 2016}}</ref> They continued undefeated through March, going to extend their winning run to 22 consecutive league games, although dropped points in a 1&ndash;1 draw at Parkhead against Rangers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic 1 - 1 Rangers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39170663|accessdate=25 April 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=12 March 2017}}</ref> Celtic clinched their sixth successive league title on 2 April 2017, with a record eight league games to spare.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic's title triumph by numbers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39330673|accessdate=4 April 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=2 April 2017}}</ref> As Celtic's unbeaten domestic run continued, they subjected Rangers to their heaviest defeat at Ibrox since 1915, thrashing their rivals 5&ndash;1 on 29 April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|last2=Stafford|first2=James|title=Rangers 1 Celtic 5: Home side humbled in record defeat|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/04/29/rangers-vs-celtic-old-firm-derby-live-score-updates/|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=29 April 2017|date=29 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alltime records|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/club_records_overall.php|website=FitbaStats|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716204124/http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/club_records_overall.php|archivedate=16 July 2015}}</ref> Celtic's 2&ndash;0 win over Hearts on 21 May saw them finish 30 points ahead of second-placed Aberdeen in the league, win a record 106 points, and the team become the first Scottish side to complete a top-flight season undefeated since 1899.<ref>{{cite news|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=Celtic 2 - 0 Hearts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39911911|accessdate=22 May 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=21 May 2017}}</ref> On 27 May 2017, Celtic clinched their fourth treble by defeating Aberdeen 2\u20131 in the Scottish Cup final, with [[Tom Rogic]] scoring the winning goal in injury time. The cup final win saw Celtic go through the entire domestic season unbeaten.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39984102 |work=BBC Sport |date=27 May 2016 |accessdate=28 May 2016 |first=Tom |last=English |title=Celtic 2 - 1 Aberdeen}}</ref>\n\n===2017&ndash;18===\n\nCeltic entered the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League]] at the 2nd qualifying round, they defeated [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]] 6\u20130, [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] 1\u20130 and [[FC Astana|Astana]] 8\u20134 on aggregate to enter the group stages.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 4 Linfield 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39330673|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=19 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rosenborg 0 Celtic 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40732241|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=2 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Astana 4 Celtic 3|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40997756|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=22 August 2017}}</ref> Celtic achieved only 3 points over the six games, but did win 3\u20130 away at [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]], their first group stages (Champions League and [[Europa League]]) win in 16 games. Celtic finished the group in third place despite losing 5\u20130 (at home) and 7\u20131 (away) to [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint Germain]].<ref>{{cite news|title=RSC Anderlecht 0 Celtic 3|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41372730|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=22 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Paris St-Germain 7 Celtic 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42056051|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2017, Celtic won their fourth consecutive domestic trophy, for the first time since Jock Stein's side in 1970, with a 2\u20130 win against Motherwell in the Scottish League Cup final.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42056522|title=Motherwell 0 Celtic 2|date=26 November 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> Celtic set the British record for consecutive unbeaten domestic games at 69, beating their own record of 62 set by Willie Maley's side in 1917, before finally losing 4\u20130 to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]. Over 585 days, Celtic won 60 of those 69 games, drawing the other 9, with 197 goals scored and 38 clean sheets in the process. Brendan Rodgers said of his Celtic team after the loss to Hearts, that \"They've set a record that may well never be beaten\".<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42297312|title=Heart of Midlothian 4 Celtic 0|date=17 December 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy finishing third in the Champions League group stages, Celtic qualified for the knockout round of 32 in the [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] where they were drawn against [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]]. Celtic won the first leg 1\u20130 after a late winner by [[Callum McGregor]], but succumbed to a disappointing 3\u20130 defeat in Saint Petersburg and were subsequently knocked out of the competition.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43136856|title=Zenit St Petersburg 3 Celtic 0|date=22 February 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 April 2018, Celtic secured their seventh consecutive league title with a 5\u20130 win over Rangers at Celtic Park. This win also extended Celtic's unbeaten run over Rangers to 12 games.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43854076|title=Celtic 5 Rangers 0|date=29 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> Celtic's season ended on 19 May 2018 when they secured the first ever 'Double-Treble' (a treble in two consecutive seasons) in Scottish football history with a 2\u20130 Scottish Cup Final win over Motherwell.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44091573|title=Celtic 2\u20130 Motherwell|date=19 May 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Celtic F.C. (1887\u20131994)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.celticfc.net Official club website]\n*[http://www.thecelticwiki.com/ TheCelticWiki]\n*[http://www.celtic-stream.net/ Celtic Fan Network]\n\n{{Celtic F.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Celtic F.C.}}\n[[Category:Celtic F.C.|History 1994-present]]\n[[Category:History of association football clubs in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n\n[[File:Celtic park 5.jpg|thumb|right|170px]]\n[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic Football Club]] has always competed in the highest level of [[football in Scotland]], currently the [[Scottish Premiership]]. The club was constituted in 1887, and played its first game in 1888. Celtic play their home games at [[Celtic Park]] having moved there in 1892 from their original ground nearby.\n\nBy 1994, Celtic had endured several years of decline and were encountering difficulties on and off the park.  Expatriate businessman [[Fergus McCann]] wrested control of the club from the family dynasties that had run Celtic since its founding.  The club was reconstituted as a PLC and floated on the stock market, raising \u00a314&nbsp;million.  The finance provided funding for the rebuilding of Celtic Park into a 60,000 all-seated stadium, the largest football stadium in Scotland.\n\nThe team improved over the years that followed and in 1998 won the league title, their first championship success in ten years. The arrival of [[Martin O'Neill]] as manager in 2000 saw the club become one of two dominant forces in Scotland, winning three league titles in five years and reaching the [[2003 UEFA Cup Final|UEFA Cup Final in 2003]]. In [[2005\u201306 in Scottish football|2005\u201306]], Celtic's home games attracted an average attendance of 58,149, placing Celtic at the time behind only [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in terms of highest average attendance for any football club in the United Kingdom.\n\nCeltic are currently managed by [[Neil Lennon]], who was appointed on a permanent basis after his Scottish Cup victory over Hearts in May 2019, having earlier in the season taken over on a caretaker basis following [[Brendan Rodgers]]' departure from the club.\n\n==The Fergus McCann era (1994\u20131999)==\nThe [[Bank of Scotland]] informed Celtic on 3 March 1994 that it was calling in [[Receivership|receivers]] as a result of the club exceeding a \u00a35&nbsp;million [[overdraft]].<ref name=\"ssc1\">{{cite web|last=MacDonald|first=Hugh|title=The Saving of Celtic, Part One: David Low|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/the-saving-of-celtic-part-one-david-low.23570438|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=1 March 2014|date=1 March 2014}}</ref> Expatriate businessman [[Fergus McCann]], however, wrested control of the club from the family dynasties which had controlled Celtic since its founding,<ref name=\"ssc1\" /> purchasing the club for a reported \u00a39&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=s9_2|title=Celtic FC Team Profile|publisher=Scottish Premier League|accessdate=23 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314003846/http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=s9_2|archive-date=14 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>  According to media reports, McCann took over the club minutes before it was to be declared [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]].<ref name=\"ssc1\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/6469284/Celtic-chairman-John-Reid-pledges-to-keep-the-clubs-finances-under-control.html |title=Celtic chairman John Reid pledges to keep the club's finances under control |work=The Telegraph |date=30 October 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2011 |first=Roddy |last=Forsyth}}</ref><ref name=\"Celticseer\">{{cite news |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/spl/Fergus-the-Celtic-seer.2507591.jp |title=Fergus the Celtic seer |work=The Scotsman |date=29 February 2004 |accessdate =23 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/new-celtic-team-takes-over-three-directors-ousted-as-17-8m-rescue-package-pledged-the-new-team-takes-over-with-a-promise-1.717089 |title= New Celtic team takes over. Three directors ousted as #17.8m rescue package pledged. The new team takes over with a promise |work=Herald Scotland |date=5 March 1994 |accessdate =23 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt this time, the club was an estimated \u00a37&nbsp;million in debt and attendances at Parkhead frequently dipped below 20,000.<ref name=\"dm0103\">{{cite news|last=McGarry|first=John|title=McCann:20 Years On; Covert operations in a great rebellion|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=1 March 2014|pages=106\u2013107}}</ref> The old board had insisted on a limit of only 7,000 season tickets, on the basis that \"season tickets are more trouble than they're worth\".<ref name=\"scot1\">{{cite web|last=Gibbons|first=Glenn|title=No point in McCann/Rangers parallel|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/glenn-gibbons-no-point-in-mccann-rangers-parallel-1-3307232|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=15 February 2014|date=15 February 2014}}</ref> Shortly prior to the takeover, the club was only valued at around \u00a320,000 due the [[Common stock#Ordinary shares|ordinary shares]] being artificially valued at \u00a31 each and the regulations of the [[Private company limited by shares|private limited]] company which decreed that shares could only be traded with the permission of the directors, who had first refusal on any that became available.<ref name=\"scot1\" />  Most significantly, the shares were not allowed to \"float\" to their true value, as a result of which directors were able to purchase them for around \u00a33 each. Bulk holders such as [[Michael Kelly (Lord Provost)|Michael Kelly]], Chris White and David Smith insisted on being paid around \u00a3300 per share, leaving McCann resentful over the disappearance of funds that could have been used in the resuscitation of the business.<ref name=\"ssc1\" /><ref name=\"scot1\" />\n\nIn order to alleviate the club's debt, McCann reconstituted the then [[Limited company|privately owned]] Celtic Football & Athletic Company Limited into a [[public limited company]] \u2013 Celtic PLC. To finance this restructuring, McCann set up a share issue which generated \u00a314&nbsp;million, one of the most successful [[Initial public offering|stock market flotations]] in British financial history.<ref name=\"ssc1\" /><ref name=\"Celticseer\" /><ref name=\"McCannAttack\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/4772870/McCann-on-the-attack-over-Celtic-criticism.html |title=McCann on the attack over Celtic criticism |work=The Telegraph |date=3 October 2000 |accessdate=23 September 2011 |first=Andrew |last=Lomax}}</ref>\n\n===Tommy Burns spell===\n[[File:Airdriecelticcupfinal.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Celtic playing against Airdrie in the 1995 Scottish Cup Final; this was their first trophy since 1989]]\nOn the playing side, manager [[Lou Macari]] was sacked by McCann and replaced in the summer of 1994 by former Celtic player [[Tommy Burns (footballer)|Tommy Burns]], with [[Billy Stark]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reynolds|first=Jim|title=As Celtic doors reopen, another looks set to close. Burns' continuing reshuffle now leaves Grimes in limbo|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/as-celtic-doors-reopen-another-looks-set-to-close-burns-continuing-reshuffle-now-leaves-grimes-in-limbo-1.492898|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=23 July 1994}}</ref> Former player and manager [[Davie Hay]] also returned to the club, as chief scout.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paul|first=Ian|title=Hay will be chief scout at Celtic|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/hay-will-be-chief-scout-at-celtic-1.493228|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=21 July 1994}}</ref> Celtic played their home games at [[Hampden Park]] in the first season under the new regime due to the redevelopment of Celtic Park.<ref>{{cite web|title=NOW YOU KNOW: No Hampden home comforts for Hoops|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/other-football/now-you-know-no-hampden-home-comforts-for-hoops-125825n.21212636|work=Evening Times|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=30 May 2013}}</ref> Celtic were poor in the league that season, but managed to win their first trophy in six years when they defeated [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrie]] 1\u20130 in the [[1995 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup Final]] on 27 May 1995.<ref name=\"cup95\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/celtics-compensation-1621393.html?CMP=ILC-refresh |work=The Independent |first=Simon |last=O'Hagan |title=Celtic's compensation |date=28 May 1995}}</ref> The winning goal was scored by Dutch striker [[Pierre van Hooijdonk]], who had been signed several months earlier from [[NAC Breda]] for \u00a31.2&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"cup95\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Celebration again as Dutch recall striker Hooydonk|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celebration-again-as-dutch-recall-striker-hooydonk-1.699671|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=13 January 1995}}</ref>\n\nThe following season saw Celtic return to their home ground at Celtic Park. Former East German international striker [[Andreas Thom]] was signed over the summer for a then club record fee of \u00a32.2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/celtic-break-club-record-to-sign-thom-1593811.html |title=Celtic break club record to sign Thom |work=The Independent |date=29 July 1995 |accessdate=5 August 2013 |first=Guy |last=Hodgson}}</ref> During the pre-season, defender [[Tony Mowbray]] persuaded his teammates to engage in a pre-match [[huddle]] prior to a friendly against German side [[Kickers Emden]] in an effort to boost the players' camaraderie and togetherness.<ref name=\"mhuddle\">{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=David|title=Tony Mowbray: The big bruising Celtic defender with an eye for the beautiful game|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/tony-mowbray-the-big-bruising-celtic-1027725|work=Daily Record|accessdate=10 July 2014|date=17 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tony Mowbray - Welcome To Celtic Football Club|url=http://www.ballymenashamrockcsc.com/?q=node/48|publisher=Ballymena Shamrock Celtic Supporters Club|accessdate=10 July 2014|date=18 June 2009}}</ref>  Although Mowbray would leave the club several weeks later, the pre-match huddle remains a constant ritual that is performed by Celtic players to this day prior to every game.<ref name=\"mhuddle\" />  Tommy Burns' second season saw him successfully restore a more attacking style of play to the side.  The new strike pairing of Van Hooijdonk and Thom forged an accomplished partnership up front.  The midfield duo of [[Paul McStay]] and [[John Collins (footballer, born 1968)|John Collins]] were integral to Celtic's attractive football and [[Jackie McNamara]] and [[Simon Donnelly]] won praise for their link-up play on the right. Celtic only lost one league match during the 1995\u201396 season, but for all the plaudits they received, they remained unable to prevent [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] from winning an eighth-straight league title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic's Nearly Men|url=http://www.scotzine.com/oor-football-years/celtics-nearly-men/|work=Scotzine|accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, the club was under pressure to invest heavily in playing talent \u2013 particularly from the fans \u2013 to thwart Rangers' attempts to equal and surpass the nine-in-a-row record Celtic held.<ref name=\"ssc1\" /> McCann was often criticised by the fans and media for his perceived frugality,<ref name=\"ssc1\" /> but further signings were made in 1996, with Portuguese striker [[Jorge Cadete]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Traynor|first=James|title=Message is clear that there's a new kid on the block|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/message-is-clear-that-there-s-a-new-kid-on-the-block-1.459085|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=2 April 1996}}</ref> and Italian winger [[Paolo Di Canio]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Di Canio joins Celtic in #3m deal|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/di-canio-joins-celtic-in-3m-deal-1.452648|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=1 June 1996}}</ref> arriving at Celtic Park.\n\nThe 1996\u201397 season saw Tommy Burns under intense media scrutiny and pressure from the supporters as Rangers closed in on their ninth successive league title. Despite Van Hooijdonk, Cadete and Di Canio having outstanding seasons as individual players, Celtic struggled to match the form of the previous season. John Collins had left for [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in the summer<ref name = \"bosman\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/FRANCS%3B+FOR%3B+NOTHING%3B+Celtic+in+French+farce+over+Collins+fee+CHEEKY!-a061314116|title=Francs For Nothing|first=Jim|last=Rodger|work=Daily Mirror|date=25 July 1996|accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref> and Paul McStay was toiling with injury. As a result, individual performances were unable to make up for the lack of overall team coherence and Celtic finished the season trophy-less, with Rangers winning their [[History of Rangers F.C.#Nine in a row|ninth successive league title]] and equalling Celtic's record set under Jock Stein.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers wins 9th successive Scottish title|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=rangers-wins-9th-successive-scottish-title-1997-05-09|work=Daily News|accessdate=2 March 2014|date=9 May 1997}}</ref>\n\nMcCann found himself embroiled in contractual disputes with the trio of Van Hooijdonk, Cadete and Di Canio, labelling them the \"Three Amigos\".<ref>{{cite news|title=McCann: I had to run 'Three Amigos' out of town|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/McCANN%3A+I+HAD+TO+RUN+THREE+AMIGOS+OUT+OF+TOWN.-a060751699|accessdate=16 December 2013|newspaper=Sunday Mail|date=1 November 1998}}</ref> McCann refused to cave in to what he considered the excessive demands of these foreign mercurial talents and, to the frustration of fans, the three each left the club under a cloud, albeit for large transfer fees.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fletcher|first=Rob|title=Whatever happened to Pierre van Hooijdonk|url=http://www.footballfancast.com/football-blogs/whatever-happened-to-pierre-van-hooijdonk|work=FootballFanCast|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=14 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jorge Cadete: the former Celtic striker who lost everything|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jan/29/jorge-cadete-portugal-celtic-state-benefits|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=29 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Di Canio\u2019s Celtic years: good, bad and ugly|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/di-canio-s-celtic-years-good-bad-and-ugly-1-3106641|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nWith just three weeks left of the 1996\u201397 season, Burns was sacked, with the club's remaining coaching staff also leaving at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Paul|first1=Ian|last2=Sinclair|first2=Paul|title=Burns is finally out The 'amicable' parting is not appreciated by more than 2000 angry fans outside Parkhead as even the manager has a police escort to leave|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/burns-is-finally-out-the-amicable-parting-is-not-appreciated-by-more-than-2000-angry-fans-outside-parkhead-as-even-the-manager-has-a-police-escort-to-leave-1.400268|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=2 March 2014|date=3 May 1997}}</ref> Various names were touted in the media as being likely to take over, however McCann made a surprising choice in Dutch coach [[Wim Jansen]]. Furthermore, it was announced that the traditional [[Manager (association football)|manager]]'s position at Celtic had been abolished, with the responsibilities to be split between the new roles of a [[Coach (sport)#Football|head coach]] (Jansen) who would deal with coaching, tactics and team selection, and a [[Director of football|general manager]] to deal with contracts and general administration duties.<ref name=\"misc9700\">{{cite book|last1=White|first1=John|title=The Celtic Football Miscellany|date=2006|publisher=Carlton Books|isbn=978-1844421626|page=122|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Celtic-Football-Miscellany-John-White/dp/1844421627/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1493155491&sr=1-1&keywords=9781844421626|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> The office of the general manager was somewhat controversially taken up by solicitor and former TV football commentator [[Jock Brown]].<ref name=\"JockB\">{{cite web|last=Oliver|first=Gary|title=Celtic cross|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/30-Clubs/6033-celtic-cross|work=When Saturday Comes|accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref>  [[Davie Hay]] was promoted from his scouting role to Assistant General Manager, whilst former Celtic player [[Murdo MacLeod]] was appointed as assistant coach to Jansen.\n\n===League title under Jansen===\nThe summer of 1997 saw substantial changes to Celtic's playing personnel.  Scottish internationalists [[Darren Jackson]] and [[Craig Burley]] were Jansen's first signings, closely followed by Dutch winger [[Regi Blinker]], Danish centre-half [[Marc Rieper]] and, more significantly, Swedish attacker [[Henrik Larsson]] from [[Feyenoord]] in a \u00a3650,000 deal.  [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]] reserve goalkeeper [[Jonathan Gould]] also arrived at Celtic Park in a low-key transfer deal. Club captain [[Paul McStay]], however, retired from playing that summer due to injury, after a playing career of 15 years and 678 appearances for the club.<ref>{{cite web|first=Graham |last=Spiers |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/still-the-modest-maestro-paul-mcstay-a-member-of-the-last-celtic-side-to-taste-victory-over-rangers-at-ibrox-in-1994-talks-to-graham-spiers-1.189683 |title=Still the modest maestro Paul McStay, a member of the last Celtic side to taste victory over Rangers at Ibrox, in 1994, talks to Graham Spiers |work=Herald Scotland |date=28 April 2001 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nRangers started the 1997\u201398 season as strong favourites for the league title and had themselves invested heavily over the summer in new players.  Celtic made a poor start to the season, losing their first two league matches, but soon began to find their feet.  Marc Rieper and [[Alan Stubbs]] quickly formed an impressive understanding in central defence,<ref>{{cite web|title=Player Profile - Alan Stubbs|url=http://www.toffeeweb.com/players/profiles/Stubbs.asp|publisher=Toffee Web|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> while Craig Burley proved to be a revelation in midfield with his energetic play and important goals. Jonathan Gould became the team's first choice goalkeeper and had an excellent season. Henrik Larsson had made an uninspiring start at Celtic, gifting [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]'s [[Chic Charnley]] the winning goal through a careless pass on his debut and then scoring an own-goal in a [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] tie (Celtic still triumphed 6\u20133 on the night and won on aggregate). The Swede, however, soon established himself as a pivotal player in the side,<ref>{{cite web|title=Larsson favourite to be player of year|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/larsson-favourite-to-be-player-of-year-1.352388|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=27 February 1998}}</ref> at this time playing just off the main strikers.\n\nAn injury time equaliser from Alan Stubbs in November 1997 against Rangers saw Celtic remain behind the Ibrox club in the league, but stay within reaching distance. The next Old Firm encounter at New Year saw Celtic win 2\u20130 with goals from Craig Burley and recent signing from [[Borussia Dortmund]], [[Paul Lambert]].  Over the following months, Celtic and Rangers each had spells at the top of the table,<ref>{{cite web|last=Gallacher|first=Ken|title=Now the title race tension swings back on to Celtic|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/now-the-title-race-tension-swings-back-on-to-celtic-1.347269|work=Hearld Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=13 April 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Broadley|first=Ian|title=Aberdeen ease relegation fears to leave Celtic three points clear of Rangers Defiant Smith not ready to surrender league title|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/aberdeen-ease-relegation-fears-to-leave-celtic-three-points-clear-of-rangers-defiant-smith-not-ready-to-surrender-league-title-1.346641|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=20 April 1998}}</ref> and as the season reached its climax, both sides dropped unexpected points as nerves took hold.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spiers|first=Graham|title=Celtic stunned by nerve gas Hibs deliver assured display to preserve a sliver of hope|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1998-04-25%3A+Celtic+0-0+Hibernian,+Premier+Division|accessdate=16 December 2013|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|date=26 April 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Killie Halt Rangers 10 In A Row Bid!|url=http://www.killiefc.com/Classic%20Matches/020598-Rangers%20(SPL).htm|publisher=KillieFC.com|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>  Celtic eventually clinched the league title win a 2\u20130 win over [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] on the last day of the season, their first championship title in ten years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/90174.stm |title=Celtic get by with a little help from their Scandinavians |work=BBC Sport |date=9 May 1998 |accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nDespite the triumph, the title-winning celebrations soon soured when Wim Jansen made good his long held threat to resign,<ref>{{cite web|last=Paul|first=Ian|title=Jansen controversy is played down by Celtic|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/jansen-controversy-is-played-down-by-celtic-1.349198|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=25 March 1998}}</ref> after difficulties working with Jock Brown and Fergus McCann.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Phil|title=Jansen had 'no future' at Celtic|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-jansen-had-no-future-at-celtic-1159706.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=12 May 1998}}</ref> Jansen resigned just two days after the club sealed the title, with Brown widely portrayed as the villain of the piece.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jansen 'wanted to quit Celtic after two weeks'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/91468.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=12 May 1998}}</ref> Davie Hay had been controversially sacked by Brown earlier in the season<ref>{{cite news|title=Jock forced me out; Davie Hay exclusive|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/JOCK+FORCED+ME+OUT%3B+Davie+Hay+exclusive.-a060757458|accessdate=17 December 2013|newspaper=Sunday Mail|date=11 January 1998}}</ref> and Jansen's assistant, Murdo MacLeod, was sacked a week after Jansen's resignation.<ref name=\"JockB\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Robertson|first=Rob|title=It's MacLeod's turn to be a Parkhead casualty|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/it-s-macleod-s-turn-to-be-a-parkhead-casualty-1.340940|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=16 December 2013|date=5 June 1998}}</ref>\n\n===Venglo\u0161 spell===\nA number of high-profile names were proferred as the replacement for Jansen, but the man eventually appointed by Celtic was Slovakian [[Jozef Venglo\u0161]]. Many fans, swayed doubtless by the local media, were disappointed and angry at the decision, citing  Venglo\u0161' poor record whilst in charge of English club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] some years before.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Madeley|first1=Gavin|title=Celtic pick new coach out of the blue |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celtic-pick-new-coach-out-of-the-blue-1.335554|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=18 July 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Broadfoot|first1=Darryl|title=Celtic deny that Slovakian's appointment is a panic move after Houllier snub Venglos takes hot seat |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celtic-deny-that-slovakian-s-appointment-is-a-panic-move-after-houllier-snub-venglos-takes-hot-seat-1.335641|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=18 July 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Shields|first1=Tom|title=Fans ask: Doctor Who?|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/fans-ask-doctor-who-1.335651|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=10 January 2015|date=18 July 1998}}</ref> Following early exits in the [[UEFA Champions League]], UEFA Cup and [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]], and a poor start to their league campaign,<ref name=\"JBq\">{{cite news|title=Brown quits Parkhead|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/scottish_premier/209621.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 January 2014|date=7 November 1998}}</ref> Celtic and Venglo\u0161 were subject to intense media scrutiny. The lack of players signed during the close season was one area in which the club were strongly criticised for.<ref name=\"JockB\" />  Amidst the almost constant negative publicity surrounding the club, Jock Brown resigned in November 1998.<ref name=\"JBq\" />\n\nPlayers did, however, begin to arrive in the late autumn: Norwegian defender [[Vidar Riseth]], Swedish defensive midfielder [[Johan Mj\u00e4llby]], Slovakian play-maker [[\u013dubom\u00edr Morav\u010d\u00edk]] and Australian striker [[Mark Viduka]] all joined. Following this, Celtic's fortunes began to turn when they won 5\u20131 against Rangers, Larsson and Morav\u010d\u00edk both scoring twice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tonic for Doctor Jo|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1998-11-21%3A+Celtic+5-1+Rangers,+PremierLeague|accessdate=29 January 2014|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|date=22 November 1998}}</ref>\n\nVenglo\u0161 now had Celtic playing good football and his deployment of Larsson as an out-and-out striker was proving to be a huge success, with the Swede eventually going  on to score 38 goals that season. The signing of Lubomir Morav\u010d\u00edk had initially been ridiculed by the Scottish media, but the Slovakian's skills soon won the doubters over.<ref>{{cite book|last=Purden|first=Richard|title=Faithful Through and Through|year=2013|publisher=Hachette Scotland}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Charles|first=Sean|title=Stars of the Past: Lubomir Moracvik|url=http://www.footandball.net/stars-of-the-past-lubomir-moracvik/|work=Foot and Ball|accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref>  Celtic rallied in the league but were still unable to prevent Rangers from winning the championship. Defeat in the [[1999 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup final]], also against Rangers, only confirmed the club's lack of progress on the field.<ref>{{cite news |last=Spiers|first=Graham|title=It's treble Advocaat|url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/page/1999-05-29%3A+Celtic+0-1+Rangers%2C+Scottish+Cup+Final|newspaper=Scotland on Sunday|accessdate=30 January 2015|date=30 May 1999}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Celtic Park New.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The redeveloped Celtic Park - a 60,832 capacity stadium]]\nShortly after the end of the season, Venglo\u0161 resigned on health grounds but remained as an advisor and European scout for the club for a brief period.<ref>{{cite web|title=Venglos to leave Celtic?|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/venglos-to-leave-celtic-26152292.html|work=The Independent (Ireland)|accessdate=30 January 2015|date=5 April 1999}}</ref><ref name=\"drjoz\">{{cite book|publisher=lulu.com|last=Ross|first=David|title=Gaffers|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3FBuAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA602&lpg=PA602&dq=venglos+leave+celtic&source=bl&ots=EbARPDf4tb&sig=xk7AdfHIm0VAzFwjy_3rlPKuKr0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mtbLVKWXLcT6UOOtgfAD&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=venglos%20leave%20celtic&f=false|accessdate=30 January 2015|page=602|isbn=978-1470927103}}</ref>  Although his tenure as head coach was strained, Venglo\u0161 is generally fondly regarded by fans, in particular for the signing of Morav\u010d\u00edk.<ref name=\"drjoz\" />\n\nIn March 1999, [[Scottish Football Association]] (SFA) Chief Executive [[Jim Farry]] was fired as a result of him deliberately delaying the registration of Jorge Cadete in 1996. The delay resulted in Cadete missing several matches for Celtic he could have played in, in particular a Scottish Cup semi-final tie against Rangers which Celtic lost 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|title=SFA boss suspended|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/288283.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 December 2013|date=1 March 1999}}</ref>  Fergus McCann had complained about the matter initially to the SFA and then to an independent commission, who subsequently found Farry guilty of gross misconduct.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ian|last=Paul |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/fergus-finishes-farry-mccann-leaves-sfa-no-option-1.303362 |title=Fergus finishes Farry McCann leaves SFA no option |work=Herald Scotland |date=2 March 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Farry was sacked days after the commission's findings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/292088.stm |title=Farry sacked by SFA |work=BBC Sport |date=8 March 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn taking over Celtic in 1994, Fergus McCann stated that he would be only be at the club for five years.  In September 1999, he officially announced that his majority stake in Celtic was for sale.<ref name=\"McCannSellshare\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/452152.stm |title=McCann sells Celtic shares |work=BBC Scotland |date=20 September 1999 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> By this time, the redevelopment of Celtic Park into a 60,000 all-seated capacity stadium was complete, at a cost of \u00a340&nbsp;million.,<ref name=\"Celticseer\" /><ref name=\"McCannSellshare\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/scottish_premier/341197.stm |title=Kerr's Ceaucescu jibe at McCann |work=BBC Sport |date=11 May 1999 |accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref> and the club had 53,000 season ticket holders.<ref name=\"scot1\" />  The club was now a successful business and the team vastly improved from when he took over in 1994.  McCann sold his shares for \u00a340&nbsp;million, making a profit of \u00a331&nbsp;million on his initial investment.<ref name=\"McCannSellshare\" />  After McCann's exit, Irish billionaire [[Dermot Desmond]] was left as the largest shareholder, with a 20% stake in the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/business/markets-lift-on-back-of-takeover-bids-397912.html |title=Markets lift on back of takeover bids |work=The Independent (Ireland)|date=25 September 1999 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> Allan MacDonald was appointed chief executive/managing director.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sinclair|first=Paul|title=Football: Fergus: my time at Celtic is over|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+Fergus%3A+my+time+at+Celtic+is+over.-a060419686|accessdate=1 February 2016|work=Daily Record|date=2 April 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Martin O'Neill (1999\u20132005)==\n\n===Barnes & Dalglish===\nThe [[1999\u20132000 Celtic F.C. season|1999\u20132000 season]] is widely considered one of the biggest disasters in the club's history. [[Kenny Dalglish]] returned to the club to fill the General Manager's post (which had been vacant since the departure of Jock Brown), while the head coach position was filled by former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[England national football team|England]] player [[John Barnes (footballer)|John Barnes]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Phil|last=Gordon |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-celtic-send-for-dalglish-and-barnes-1099459.html |title=Football: Celtic send for Dalglish and Barnes - Sport |work=The Independent |date=11 June 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarnes had never managed a professional club, and the fans' worst fears were realised when Celtic's title challenge drastically faltered shortly after the winter break. Following a series of poor results \u2013 including elimination from the UEFA Cup and a broken leg away against [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] for Henrik Larsson<ref>{{cite news|first=Simon|last=Buckland|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/fears-for-larssons-future-after-broken-leg-nightmare-26136099.html |title=Fears for Larsson's future after broken leg nightmare |work=The Independent (Ireland)|date=22 October 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/505289.stm |title=Celts fail to tame Lyon challenge |work=BBC Sport|date=4 November 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> \u2013 Rangers increased their lead at the top of the [[Scottish Premier League]] table and demands for Barnes to be sacked began.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moore |first=Glenn |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/dalglish-rallies-behind-celtic-coach-barnes-742841.html |title=Dalglish rallies behind Celtic coach Barnes - Scottish - Football |work=The Independent |date=4 December 1999 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20051013/celtic-v-hearts_2241541_725930 |title=Celtic v Hearts - Memorable Matches - Celtic 2 Hearts 3 |publisher=Heartsfc.co.uk |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112192702/http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/articles/20051013/celtic-v-hearts_2241541_725930 |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"fanp\">{{cite web|first1=Chris|last1=Starrs|first2=William|last2=Tinning |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/fans-in-protest-as-caley-humble-celtic-1.249919 |title=Fans in protest as Caley humble Celtic |work=Herald Scotland |date=9 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 2000, Celtic hosted a rearranged Scottish Cup tie at home to [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]]. Caley Thistle were an in-form side, fourth-placed in Division 1, although only in the Scottish Football League since 1994. Nevertheless, the match was still widely expected to be an easy victory for Celtic. However, Caley Thistle won the match 3\u20131 in one of the biggest Scottish Cup upsets ever,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/636000.stm |title=Caley's minnows slay Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=8 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> which sparked a protest involving over a hundred Celtic fans outside the stadium.<ref name=\"fanp\" /> The memorable headline in ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper the following day read: \"[[Supercalifragilisticexpialidocious#Other references|Super Caley Go Ballistic, Celtic Are Atrocious]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://supercaleygoballistic.com/2012/01/09/hello-world/ |title=Who Was the Super Caley Sub? |publisher=supercaleygoballistic |date=9 January 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529150051/http://supercaleygoballistic.com/2012/01/09/hello-world/ |archivedate=29 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Having refused to speak to the press after the match, Barnes held a press conference the next day, and implied that a dispute between him and Mark Viduka at half-time had badly unsettled the team and been responsible for the defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/636105.stm |title=Celtic chief plans 'full review' |work=BBC News |date=9 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Barnes was sacked the following morning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/637415.stm |title=Barnes forced out |work=BBC News |date=10 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nKenny Dalglish took over as head coach until the end of the season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/638554.stm |title=Dalglish aims to steady Celtic ship |work=BBC News |date=11 February 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and brought Tommy Burns back to assist him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/other-sports/tommy-burns-was-one-of-celtics-greatest-977594 |title=Tommy Burns was one of Celtic's greatest, says Scotland legend Kenny Dalglish |work=Daily Record |date=17 May 2008 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> While Dalglish generally retained the respect of the supporters, Celtic's league form deteriorated further and the club finished 21 points behind Rangers at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/1999-2000/table |title=Scottish Premier League 1999-2000 Table |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112190945/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/1999-2000/table |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A League Cup final victory over [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] was the only consolation in one of the most embarrassing periods of the club's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+DALGLISH+LIFTED+BY+CUP+WIN%3B+Celtic+2+Aberdeen+0.-a060293157 |title=Dalglish lifted by Cup win; Celtic 2 Aberdeen 0 |work=The Mirror |date=20 March 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===The arrival of O'Neill===\nFollowing the sacking of John Barnes, [[Guus Hiddink]] emerged as Celtic chief executive Alan MacDonald's initial choice to take over as manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/733476.stm |title=Celtic struggle to tempt Hiddink |work=BBC News |date=2 May 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  However, Hiddink's apparent lack of interest in the Celtic post<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+HIDDINK+DEAL+IN+DANGER%3B+Delays+cast+doubt+over+Guus+move.-a062047071 |title=HIDDINK DEAL IN DANGER; Delays cast doubt over Guus move |work=Daily Record |date=12 May 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> and the intervention of majority shareholder [[Dermot Desmond]] saw [[Leicester City]] manager [[Martin O'Neill]] come to the fore as the club's primary target.<ref>{{cite web|last=McHugh|first=Joe|title=Coyle, Moyes and Mowbray touted as Hoops power broker eyes up Strachan's successor|url=http://www.herald.ie/sport/soccer/coyle-moyes-and-mowbray-touted-as-hoops-power-broker-eyes-up-strachans-successor-27912944.html|work=The Herald (Ireland)|accessdate=22 October 2013|date=26 May 2009}}</ref>  \n \n[[File:O'Neill, Martin.jpg|180px|thumb|left|Martin O'Neill]]\n[[Martin O'Neill]] \u2013 from [[Kilrea]], [[Northern Ireland]], a former European Cup winner in his playing days with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] \u2013 arrived at the club in the wake of the Barnes/Dalglish fiasco in June 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/769394.stm |title=Celtic win O'Neill tussle |work=BBC Sport |date=1 June 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> O'Neill took full charge of all team matters, effectively re-establishing the traditional role of \"manager\" at Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kerr|first=Thomas|title=Dalglish set to leave post at Celtic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jun/07/newsstory.sport|work=The Guardian|accessdate=19 December 2013|date=7 June 2000}}</ref> With the \"general manager\" role now redundant, Dalglish was sacked by Celtic at the end of June.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Dalglish hits out over messy Celtic divorce|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/4754679/Dalglish-hits-out-over-messy-Celtic-divorce.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 December 2013|date=30 June 2000}}</ref>\n\nOver the summer, O'Neill bought [[Chris Sutton]] from [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for a club record \u00a36&nbsp;million, while Mark Viduka moved south to join [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/829023.stm |title=O'Neill secures Sutton |work=BBC Sport |date=11 July 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Belgian international centre-half [[Joos Valgaeren]] also arrived in the summer in a bid by O'Neill to shore up a porous Celtic defence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/848828.stm |title=Joos boost for Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=28 July 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nO'Neill's signings quickly settled in at Celtic; Sutton scored the winning goal on the first of the day of the season in a 2\u20131 win over [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/858625.stm |title=Celtic new boys off to winning start |work=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> while Valgaeren linked up well with Alan Stubbs and Tom Boyd in the centre of defence.  Further players arrived over the course of 2000-01; left-sided midfielder [[Alan Thompson (footballer, born 1973)|Alan Thompson]] was signed from Aston Villa,<ref>{{cite news|first=Jon |last=Brodkin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/sep/02/newsstory.sport6 |title=O'Neill gets his man as Thompson signs for Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=2 September 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> the pacy [[Didier Agathe]] arrived from Hibernian,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://celticjournal.org/2031/exclusive-didier-agathe-interview/ |title=Exclusive: Didier Agathe Interview |work=Celtic Journal |date=15 June 2013 |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726195358/http://celticjournal.org/2031/exclusive-didier-agathe-interview/ |archivedate=26 July 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> centre-half [[Ramon Vega]] headed north on loan from [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/1073543.stm |title=Celtic hit Dons for six |work=BBC Sport |date=17 December 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> goalkeeper [[Robert Douglas (footballer)|Rab Douglas]] was signed up from Dundee and midfielder [[Neil Lennon]] was signed from O'Neill's old club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ley |first=John |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/2994143/Lennon-realises-dream-to-join-his-idols-Celtic.html |title=Lennon realises dream to join his idols Celtic |work=The Telegraph |date=7 December 2000 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  That season saw Celtic go on to win their first domestic treble since 1969, winning the League, Scottish Cup and League Cup. O'Neill became only the second Celtic manager to achieve this, after Jock Stein.<ref name=\"treble32\">{{cite news|last=Hayward |first=Paul |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/3006199/Scottish-Cup-final-Business-as-usual-for-loyal-ONeill.html |title=Scottish Cup final: Business as usual for loyal O'Neill |work=The Telegraph |date=27 May 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The season was also additionally memorable because of some excellent results against rivals Rangers. A famous 6\u20132 victory in the opening [[Old Firm]] encounter of the season at Celtic Park proved to everyone that the balance of power in Scotland had shifted.<ref>{{cite web|first=James|last=Traynor |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/spl-celtic-6-rangers-2-1009206 |title=SPL: Celtic 6 Rangers 2, August 28, 2000 |work=Daily Record |date=10 February 2009 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Two further league victories against Rangers: 1\u20130 (at Celtic Park),<ref>{{cite web|first=Ian|last=Paul |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/celtic-close-in-on-league-title-ricksen-red-card-infuriates-advocaat-1.198993 |title=Celtic close in on league title:Ricksen red card infuriates Advocaat |work=Herald Scotland |date=12 February 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and 3\u20130 (at Ibrox)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/3004436/Larsson-brings-up-the-half-century-as-Celtic-win-Old-Firm-clash.html |title=Larsson brings up the half-century as Celtic win Old Firm clash |work=The Telegraph |date=29 April 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> ensured O'Neill's first league title was won by a considerable distance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2000-2001/table |title=Scottish Premier League 2000-2001 Table |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112194151/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2000-2001/table |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nO'Neill's debut season also saw outstanding performances produced by players already at Celtic. Henrik Larsson scored 53 goals in all competitions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/player.php?playerid=2842 |title=Celtic Player Henrik Larsson Details |work=FitbaStats |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and won the [[European Golden Shoe]] with his 35 league goals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Irvine |first=Neil |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/3007495/Larsson-goals-earn-Europes-golden-boot.html |title=Larsson goals earn Europe's golden boot |work=Telegraph |date=18 June 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Larsson was voted both SPFA and Scottish Football Writers Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season review 2000/01|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200001-2008-06-01/|publisher=SPFL|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> Young Bulgarian midfielder [[Stiliyan Petrov]] impressed as well, having been signed the previous season by John Barnes. In 2001, the 21-year-old Bulgarian became the first foreign winner of the [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year|SPFA Young Player of the Year]] award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstalk.ie/Petrov-announces-retirement-from-football |title=Newstalk - Petrov announces retirement from football |work=Newstalk.ie |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Impact in Europe===\nCeltic further strengthened their squad \u2013 in every sense \u2013 for the 2001\u201302 season with the signings of the powerfully-built Guinean defender [[Bobo Bald\u00e9]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=24753 |title=Bobo Balde |work=SoccerBase |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and Welsh striker [[John Hartson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1464876.stm |title=Celtic sign trio on deadline day |work=BBC Sport |date=2 August 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2001, Celtic played [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in [[Amsterdam]] in the first leg of the qualifier tie for the [[2001\u201302 UEFA Champions League|2001\u201302 Champions League]], turning in an outstanding performance.<ref name=\"Tictactic.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tictactic.co.uk/classic-tictactic-champions-league-3rd-qualifying-round-2001-ajax-1-3-celtic/ |title=Classic TicTacTic \u2013 Champions League 3rd Qualifying Round 2001: Ajax 1-3 Celtic |publisher=Tictactic.co.uk |date=11 July 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201215900/http://www.tictactic.co.uk/classic-tictactic-champions-league-3rd-qualifying-round-2001-ajax-1-3-celtic/ |archivedate=1 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"George Grant\">{{cite news|title=My Celtic could easily have had six, says O'Neill |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-65527/My-Celtic-easily-says-ONeill.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=6 August 2013|first=George|last=Grant|date=9 August 2001}}</ref> First-half goals from Dutch winger [[Bobby Petta]] and [[Didier Agathe]] gave Celtic a 2\u20131 lead at half-time. [[Chris Sutton]] added a third in the second half with a powerful header to give Celtic an impressive 3\u20131 win.<ref name=\"Forsyth\">{{cite news|last=Forsyth |first=Roddy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/3010365/Champions-League-Petta-sets-Celtic-on-the-path-to-glittering-prize.html |title=Champions League: Petta sets Celtic on the path to glittering prize |work=The Telegraph |date=8 August 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  A nervy second leg performance at Parkhead saw Celtic lose 0\u20131 on the night but progress to the group stages on aggregate, their first involvement in the Champions League group stages since the redevelopment of the tournament in the 1990s.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/3011251/Champions-League-Celtic-edge-through-but-nerves-show.html |title=Champions League: Celtic edge through but nerves show |work=The Telegraph |date=22 August 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> This was the first of three occasions that O'Neill's Celtic side qualified for the group stage of the Champions League, and on the only occasion they failed, they went on to reach the final of the UEFA Cup.\n\nCeltic made their debut in the group stages of the Champions League on 18 September 2001, losing 2\u20133 to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in [[Turin]].  Celtic had recovered from a 2\u20130 deficit to level the match at 2\u20132, but lost a third goal near the end from a controversial penalty.<ref>{{cite news|first=Barry|last=Glendenning |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/18/minutebyminute.sport1 |title=Juventus 3 - 2 Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=18 September 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/virals/130211/martin-oneills-memorable-rant-celtics-clash-juventus-2001-191434 |title=Magazine: Martin O'Neill's memorable rant from Celtic's clash with Juventus in 2001 |work=TalkSport |accessdate=6 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214020117/http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/virals/130211/martin-oneills-memorable-rant-celtics-clash-juventus-2001-191434 |archive-date=14 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Celtic recovered from that set-back to win their next two home matches against [[FC Porto|Porto]] and [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]],<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Walker |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/26/championsleague.porto |title=Celtic 1 - 0 Porto |work=The Guardian |date=26 September 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Graham|last=Clark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/11/championsleague.sport |title=Celtic 1 - 0 Rosenborg |work=The Guardian |date=11 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> but lost the away matches against the same opposition.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Taylor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/18/championsleague.porto |title=Porto 3 - 0 Celtic|work=The Guardian |date=18 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Walkerv|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/oct/24/championsleague.sport1 |title=Rosenborg 2 - 0 Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=24 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic's final group match was against Juventus at Parkhead on 31 October 2001. It was a memorable European night in [[Glasgow]] as a Chris Sutton brace and an outstanding performance from \u013dubom\u00edr Morav\u010d\u00edk helped Celtic to a famous 4\u20133 win. Despite finishing the group with nine points, however, Celtic failed to qualify for the next round<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/1627972.stm |title=Celtic bow out in style |work=BBC Sport |date=31 October 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and parachuted into the [[2001\u201302 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]. Celtic were drawn against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in the UEFA Cup, and in the first leg in Spain had goalkeeper Rab Douglas to thank for keeping the score to a manageable 0\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/1666912.stm |title=Valencia vanquish Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=22 November 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The second leg in Glasgow saw Henrik Larsson scoring to give Celtic a 1\u20130 win after 90 minutes to level the tie on aggregate.  As no goals were scored during extra-time, the tie went to penalty-kicks. Celtic lost the penalty shoot-out and were knocked out.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|first=Graham|last=Clark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/dec/07/uefa.sport |title=Uefa Cup: Celtic 1 - 0 Valencia (1-1 agg, Valencia win 5-4 on pens) |work=The Guardian |date=7 December 2001 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nCeltic cruised to their second successive league title in 2001\u201302, their first back-to-back titles in 20 years<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200102-2008-06-01/ |title=Season Review 2001/02 |publisher=SPFL |date=1 June 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> and finished 18 points clear of second-placed Rangers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2001-2002/table |title=Scottish Premier League 2001-2002 Table |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224418/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2001-2002/table |archivedate=1 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Rangers, under new manager [[Alex McLeish]], did however enjoy a modicum of revenge in the cup tournaments, beating Celtic 2\u20131 in the semi-final of the League Cup<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/cis_ins_cup/1800034.stm |title=Konterman kills Celtic's dream |work=BBC Sport |date=5 February 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and twice coming from behind in the Scottish Cup Final in May 2002 to win 3\u20132 through a last-minute goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scottish_cup/1966673.stm |title=Rangers win Old Firm final |work=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nO'Neill's third season at Celtic, 2002\u201303, was probably the most memorable, even although the club did not win any silverware.<ref name=\"killie4\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Walker |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/may/26/match.sport |title=Kilmarnock 0 - 4 Celtic |work=The Guardian |date=25 May 2003|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The domestic cup tournaments again eluded Celtic; in the space of a week in March 2003, Celtic lost 2\u20131 to Rangers in the League Cup final<ref>{{cite news|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2398103/CIS-Cup-Final-Hartson-makes-Rangers-day.html |title=CIS Cup Final: Hartson makes Rangers' day |work=The Telegraph |date=17 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and then were knocked out of the Scottish Cup a week later at the fourth round stage by Inverness Caledonian Thistle.<ref>{{cite news|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2398483/Super-Caley-shock-Celtic-in-cup-again.html |title=Super Caley shock Celtic in cup again |work=The Telegraph |date=27 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The league campaign was a tight contest, and going into the last fixture both Celtic and Rangers were level on points. Both sides recorded high-scoring wins in their respective fixtures \u2013 Celtic won 4\u20130 at [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], but Rangers' 6\u20131 win at Ibrox over [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dumfermline Athletic]] saw them win the league on goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200203-2008-06-01/ |title=Season Review 2002/03 |publisher=SPFL |date=1 June 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>  It was in Europe, however, that Celtic made their mark.\n\nCeltic's [[The Bhoys from Seville|European campaign in 2002\u201303]] began somewhat inauspiciously when they were beaten by [[FC Basel|Basel]] on away goals in a qualifier tie for the Champions League.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/2218965.stm |title=Celtic beaten in Basel |work=BBC Sport |date=28 August 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic dropped into the UEFA Cup, and in the first round eased to a 10\u20131 aggregate win over Lithuanian minnows [[FK S\u016bduva Marijampol\u0117|FK S\u016bduva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/FOOTBALL+%3A+CELTS+GO+ON+A+BALTIC+CRUISE%3B+So+easy+as+clever+Bhoys+make...-a092432444 |title=Celtic go on a Baltic cruise; So easy as clever Bhoys make it 10 out of 10 for the clever Bhoys|work=Daily Record |date=4 October 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  The next round, Celtic were paired with [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redandwhitekop.com/forum/index.php?topic=7379.0 |title=UEFA Cup draw. Celtic v Blackburn |publisher=Redandwhitekop.com |date= |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> managed by former Rangers player-manager [[Graeme Souness]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Davies |first=Christopher |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackburn-rovers/3035810/Souness-prepares-for-Scottish-reunion.html |title=Souness prepares for Scottish reunion |work=The Telegraph |date=9 October 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic were poor in the first leg at Parkhead, but a Henrik Larsson goal five minutes from full-time secured a crucial 1\u20130 win on the night and a narrow lead to take down to [[Ewood Park]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/3037111/Larsson-gives-Celtic-the-edge.html</ref>  In the build-up to the return match, Blackburn captain [[Gary Flitcroft]] made public that Souness had commented in the dressing room after the first game that Blackburn were the better side and should have won: \"That was men against boys.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth |first=Roddy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackburn-rovers/3037870/Irish-argue-Celtics-case.html |title=Irish argue Celtic's case |work=The Telegraph |date=14 November 2002 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  In the second leg, Celtic showed much more composure and scored after 14 minutes through Larsson.  Celtic controlled the game after that and Chris Sutton scored another goal for Celtic in the second half, with Celtic winning 2\u20130 on the night and 3\u20130 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Taylor|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/nov/15/uefa.sport |title=Blackburn Rovers 0 - 2 Celtic (Celtic won 3-0 on aggregate)|work=The Guardian |date=2 December 2003|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic's third round UEFA cup opponents were [[Celta de Vigo]]. In a first-leg overshadowed by eccentric refereeing,<ref>{{cite news|last=McCarthy|first=David|title=Clueless Columbo; Nightmare referee is a mystery as raging O'Neill blows his top |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+CLUELESS+COLUMBO%3B+Nightmare+referee+is+a+mystery+as+raging...-a094717506|accessdate=4 October 2013|newspaper=Daily Record|date=29 November 2002}}</ref> Larsson scored the only goal of the game in Glasgow.<ref>{{cite news|first=Graham|last=Clark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/nov/29/uefa.sport |title=Celtic 1 - 0 Celta Vigo |work=The Guardian |date=28 November 2002|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  The return match in Spain was won 2\u20131 by Celta, levelling the aggregate score at 2\u20132, but [[John Hartson]]'s away goal won the tie for Celtic. This was the first time ever that Celtic had knocked out a Spanish club in European competition, and also the first time in 23 years that Celtic had remained in European competition beyond Christmas.<ref>{{cite news|first=Chris|last=Roberts at the Balaidos Stadium |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/dec/13/uefa.sport1 |title=Celta Vigo 2 - 1 Celtic (Celtic win on away goals) |work=The Guardian |date=12 December 2002|accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seville celtic fans.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Celtic fans at the UEFA Cup Final in Seville]]\nGerman [[Bundesliga]] team [[VfB Stuttgart]] were Celtic's fourth round opponents in the Spring of 2003. Celtic came from behind to win the first leg 3\u20131 at Parkhead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/uefa_cup/2780267.stm |title=Petrov sinks Stuttgart |work=BBC Sport |date=21 February 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> In the second leg, Celtic went 2\u20130 up early on, but a comeback by Stuttgart saw the Bundesliga side win 3\u20132 on the night; Celtic however won 5\u20134 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2798753.stm |title=Celtic kill off Stuttgart |work=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  The quarter-finals saw another English [[Premier League]] opponent for Celtic: Liverpool. The first leg took place at Celtic Park on 13 March 2003.  The first leg ended 1\u20131 with Larsson scoring for Celtic in the first minute but the away goal gave Liverpool the advantage going in to their home tie at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2836319.stm |title=Liverpool hold Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> During the first leg, Liverpool player [[El Hadji Diouf]] spat at a Celtic supporter, and was later fined \u00a35,000 at Glasgow's [[Sheriff Court]] for the incident.<ref>{{cite news |title=Diouf will not face assault charges |work=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]| url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/english/2006/1116/211372-dioufe/ |accessdate=25 January 2015 |date=14 June 2007}}</ref>  The return match at Anfield took place the following week. Celtic won 2\u20130, with the goals coming from an Alan Thompson free-kick and a long-range strike from [[John Hartson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2864921.stm |title=Celtic brush aside Liverpool |work=BBC Sport |date=20 March 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nCeltic's first European semi-final since the early 1970s saw them paired against Portuguese side [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]]. Celtic drew 1\u20131 in the first game at Parkhead,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/2909819.stm |title=Celtic held by Boavista |work=BBC Sport |date=10 April 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> but a Henrik Larsson goal in the 80th minute of the return match in Portugal won the tie and ensured Celtic's progress to the UEFA Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jon|last=Brodkin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/apr/25/newsstory.sport4 |title=Boavista 0 - 1 Celtic (Agg: 1-2) |work=The Guardian |date=25 April 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2003, around 80,000 Celtic fans travelled to watch the club compete in the [[2003 UEFA Cup Final|final]], held in [[Seville]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/gallery/0,8561,972767,00.html |title=Celtic in Seville: A picture special |work=Observer Sport (The Guardian) |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stewart|first1=Stephen|last2=Henderson|first2=Damien|title=Hats off to very good bhoys and ghirls 80,000 Celtic fans in Spain and not a single arrest|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/hats-off-to-very-good-bhoys-and-ghirls-80-000-celtic-fans-in-spain-and-not-a-single-arrest-1.117903|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=23 May 2003}}</ref> Celtic lost the final on 21 May 2003 3\u20132 to Porto after extra time, despite two goals from Henrik Larsson during normal play. Celtic's cause was not helped by the late sending-off of defender Bobo Bald\u00e9 and the referee's over-indulgence of Porto's time-wasting and their players' persistent feigning of injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/european/2003/0522/172812-celtic01/ |title=UEFA may discipline O'Neill over comments |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |date=14 June 2007 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> However, the exemplary conduct of the thousands of travelling Celtic supporters received widespread praise from the people of Seville and the fans were awarded prestigious [[FIFA Fair Play Award|Fair Play Awards]] from both [[FIFA]] and [[UEFA]] \"for their extraordinarily loyal and sporting behaviour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/ballondor/archive/edition=1999902003/news/newsid=90249/index.html |title=Celebrating Celtic pride in the heart of Andalusia |publisher=FIFA.com |date=15 December 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3189853.stm |title=Celtic fans 'Europe's best' |work=BBC News |date=28 August 2003 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Continued success===\n[[File:Oldfirm.jpg|thumb|left|350px|Celtic and Rangers fans at Parkhead in 2004]]\nCeltic regained the SPL title in 2003\u201304 in emphatic manner, winning by a margin of 18 points and scoring over 100 goals.<ref name=\"lg0304\">{{cite web|title=Season review 2003/04|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/season-review-200304-2008-06-01/|publisher=SPFL|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> The league campaign also saw Celtic win 25 games in a row, setting a new British record.<ref name=\"lg0304\" />  Celtic recorded five wins (four in the league, one in the Scottish Cup) over rivals Rangers; a last minute Chris Sutton goal in May 2004 giving Celtic a 1\u20130 win in the final Old Firm fixture of the season and their first [[Whitewash (sport)|whitewash]] of wins over their rivals for over 30 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 1 Rangers 0|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/3691469.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=8 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nCeltic qualified for the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|Champions League in 2003\u201304]], but again could only finish third in the group stages and dropped into the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic suffer Lyon heartbreak; Lyon 3-2 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/3304353.stm|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=10 December 2003|work=BBC News}}</ref>  After a straightforward aggregate win over [[FK Teplice]],<ref>{{cite web|title=FK Teplice 1-0 Celtic: Safe passage|url=http://espnfc.com/en/report/142294/report.html?soccernet=true|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=4 March 2014|date=3 March 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304221913/http://espnfc.com/en/report/142294/report.html?soccernet=true|archivedate=4 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Celtic were drawn against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the round of 16. A dramatic first leg in Glasgow saw Celtic win 1\u20130 through an Alan Thompson goal, but goalkeeper Rab Douglas and Barcelona's [[Thiago Motta]] were sent off during half-time for fighting in the tunnel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic spoil Bar\u00e7a's winning streak|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2003/matches/round=1721/match=74496/postmatch/report/index.html|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=11 March 2004}}</ref>  The return match in Spain saw Celtic fielding 19-year-old reserve goalkeeper [[David Marshall (footballer)|David Marshall]] in place of Douglas and young defender [[John Kennedy (Scottish footballer)|John Kennedy]] standing in for Bobo Bald\u00e9, who was also suspended.<ref name=\"0416r\">{{cite news|title=Celtic stun Barcelona; Barcelona 0-0 Celtic (agg:0-1)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/3560199.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=25 March 2004}}</ref> Celtic found themselves under a sustained barrage of pressure, but the two youngsters turned in outstanding performances.  Marshall pulled off outstanding saves from [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]] and [[Luis Garc\u00eda (footballer, born 1978)|Luis Garc\u00eda]], while Kennedy made a number of great tackles to keep Barcelona at bay.<ref name=\"0416r\" /> Celtic held out for a scoreless draw on the night to win on aggregate and progress to the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"0416r\" />  Celtic's run in Europe was finally ended in the next round by another Spanish side, [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], losing 3\u20131 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Villareal 2-0 Celtic (Villareal win 3-1 on aggregate)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/3621937.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 March 2014|date=14 April 2004}}</ref>\n\nThe Scottish Cup final was reached with ease; Celtic conceding only one goal as they knocked out [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]], [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]], Rangers and [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] en route.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic Fixtures & Results - 2003/04 (Scottish Cup)|url=http://espnfc.com/team/fixtures/_/id/256/season/2003/league/sco.tennents/celtic?cc=5739|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>  The final against Dunfermline took place on 22 May 2004 and was the last match Henrik Larsson played for the club. The Swede ended his Celtic career on a high note, scoring twice as Celtic came from behind to win 3\u20131, completing a league and cup double for the season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barnes|first=John|title=Departing Larsson earns Celtic double|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2379408/Departing-Larsson-earns-Celtic-double.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 March 2014|date=23 May 2004}}</ref>\n\nThe following season ([[2004\u201305 Celtic F.C. season|2004\u201305]]), O'Neill's last at the club, saw Celtic struggle to maintain their dominance of recent years.  Nevertheless, they took an early lead in the league campaign and won their first encounter against Rangers in August 2004, their seventh consecutive win in Old Firm games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 1-0 Rangers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/3601320.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2014|date=29 August 2004}}</ref>  \nThe league contest went to the final day of the season with Celtic needing to win away at [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] to guarantee the title.  Celtic led for most of the match, and with two minutes of normal time remaining looked set for another SPL title.  However, two late [[Scott McDonald]] goals for Motherwell saw Celtic beaten 2\u20131 and hand the title to rivals Rangers. The season did end in silverware for Celtic as they retained the Scottish Cup, defeating Dundee United 1\u20130 in the final.  At the end of the season, Martin O'Neill parted ways with the club, to care for his ill wife.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4576981.stm |title=End of an era as O'Neill resigns |work=BBC Sport |date=25 May 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nUnder O'Neill's five year leadership, Celtic won the league three times, three Scottish Cup finals and the League Cup once.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefootballsupernova.com/2012/11/martin-oneill-is-his-time-up.html |title=Martin O'Neill - Is his time up? |work=The Football Supernova |date=5 November 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> In European competition, teams such as Juventus,<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/> Porto,<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> [[Valencia CF|Valencia]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> and Barcelona<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/3497300.stm |title=Celtic 1-0 Barcelona |work=BBC Sport |date=11 March 2004 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> all visited Glasgow to face Celtic and returned home defeated. He led Celtic to their first European final in 33 years, albeit losing narrowly after extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espnfc.com/blog/_/name/celtic/id/394?cc=5739 |title=Memories of Seville 2003: Ten years on |publisher=ESPN FC  |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic also commenced an unbeaten run of 77 home matches, which spanned from 2001 to 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=aberdeen-ends-celtics-77-game-unbeaten-home-run-2004-04-23 |title=SPORTS - Aberdeen ends Celtic's 77-game unbeaten home run |work=Hurriyet Daily News |date=23 April 2004 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> and notched up an SPL record for the most consecutive wins in a single season.<ref name=\"lg0304\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=esp/news/newsid=1588768.html |title=Europe's longest domestic winning streaks |publisher=UEFA.com |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>  In conclusion, O'Neill's tenure as manager at Celtic was the club's most successful period since the time of Jock Stein.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Gordon Strachan and Tony Mowbray (2005\u20132010)==\n[[File:Gordon David Strachan.jpg|thumb|177px|left|Gordon Strachan]]\n[[Gordon Strachan]] was announced in June 2005 as Martin O'Neill's replacement,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4572091.stm |title=Strachan in for O'Neill at Celtic |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 May 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> after apparently being recommended by O'Neill himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/strachan-follows-oneills-example-1577944 |title=Strachan follows O'Neill's example |work=Chronicle Live |date=1 June 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Strachan faced a number of challenges, not least in inheriting an aged squad who were highly expensive and one that had still failed to replace the talismanic Henrik Larsson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4729853.stm |title=Strachan not veering from course |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>  Strachan made an unpromising start, in particular his first game in which Celtic lost 0\u20135 to Slovakian side [[Artmedia Bratislava]] and recorded their worst ever European result,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-357323/Humiliated-Celtic-got-deserved--Bratislava-captain.html |title=Humiliated Celtic got what they deserved - Bratislava captain |work=Mail Online |date=28 July 2005 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic, however, quickly regained form and confidence and went on to become the fastest team to win the SPL championship ever,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Armstrong|first1=Gary|title=Celtic on course to break their own record as earliest ever title winners|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-course-break-record-earliest-9541164|accessdate=2 January 2017|work=Daily Record|date=1 January 2017}}</ref> along with the League Cup in the [[2005\u201306 Celtic F.C. season|2005\u201306 season]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunfermline 0-3 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/4807338.stm|accessdate=2 January 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=19 March 2006}}</ref> The title was clinched before the league was split with a 1\u20130 home victory over second-placed Hearts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/4873944.stm |title=Celtic 1-0 Hearts |work=BBC Sport |date=5 April 2006 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> [[Shaun Maloney]] had an outstanding season for Celtic and became the first player to win both [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year|Young Player of the Year]] awards from [[PFA Scotland]] in the same season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/4951722.stm |title=Maloney in historic awards double |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=28 March 2008 |date=1 May 2006}}</ref> Celtic's home games that season attracted an average attendance of 58,149,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotprem.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Attendance/0,,10002~20053,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410122328/http://www.scotprem.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Attendance/0%2C%2C10002~20053%2C00.html |archivedate=10 April 2008 |title=Attendance Scottish Premier League Stats 2005/06 |publisher=SPL |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> placing Celtic at the time behind only [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in terms of highest average attendance for any football club in the UK.<ref name=\"s0506\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nufc.com/html/2005-06html/homeatt.html |title=Premiership Attendances 2005-2006 |accessdate=26 March 2015 |publisher=NUFC.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:JohnReidHeadshot.jpg|170px|thumb|right|Celtic Chairman 2007-2011, John Reid]]During the [[2006\u201307 Celtic F.C. season|2006\u201307 season]] Celtic continued their domination of the Scottish Premier League, despite a huge effort by Strachan and the club to reduce the wage bill. Expensive mainstays of the O'Neill years such as Hartson and Sutton, who on average delivered 40 goals per season between them, were moved on and replaced by far younger, and less expensive, players. The team proved unerringly consistent, as had O'Neill's, despite their youth and comparative lack of experience. By the close of the January transfer window, Celtic were 19 points ahead of second-placed Rangers,<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan |title=Red card mars win which puts Celtic in sight of March title|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/jan/29/match.invernesscaledonianthistle |work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 November 2013|date=29 January 2007}}</ref> something which may have been a large contribution to a complete loss of form and partial loss of points in the second half of the season.<ref name=\"l07win\">{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Months of Celtic frustration forgotten as Nakamura wonder-strike secures title|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/apr/23/match.kilmarnock|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 November 2013|date=23 April 2007}}</ref> They completed their quest for back-to-back titles on 22 April 2007 with a 2\u20131 win against Kilmarnock. [[Shunsuke Nakamura]] ensured the victory with a goal from a free kick from 25 yards in the final minute,<ref name=\"l07win\" /> leaving Celtic 13 points clear of Rangers with four matches remaining.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Premier League 2006-2007 - Table on Monday 23rd April 2007|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/scotland/premier-league/2006-2007/table/2007-04-23|website=Statto|accessdate=19 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThat season also saw Strachan guide Celtic into last 16 of the Champions League for the first time. Celtic secured their progress from the group stages courtesy of Shunsuke Nakamura's 30-yard free-kick against Manchester United in a 1\u20130 win at Parkhead. The win on the night, and qualification to the last 16, was clinched when [[Artur Boruc]] saved [[Louis Saha]]'s 88th-minute penalty kick.<ref>{{cite web |title=United crash as Nakamura puts Celtic through |first=Kevin |last=McCarra |work=The Guardian |date=22 November 2006 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/nov/22/match.sport |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> Celtic lost 0\u20131 in the last 16 round to the eventual winners of the cup, [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], after a goal from [[Kak\u00e1]] in extra time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Aikman|first=Richard|title=Celtic foiled by Kak\u00e1 magic |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2006/matches/round=2358/match=85505/postmatch/report/index.html|publisher=UEFA.com|date=8 March 2007|accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref> On 26 May 2007, Celtic again won the Scottish Cup, for a 34th time, beating Dunfermline 1\u20130, completing another league and cup double. The Cup final was also captain [[Neil Lennon]]'s final appearance as a Celtic player.<ref>{{cite web|last=Glenn|first=Patrick|title=Kenny's gallant men floored by the Doumbe Double |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/27/match.celtic|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 November 2013|date=27 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 September 2007 it was announced [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]] would become chairman of Celtic and he took over from [[Brian Quinn (economist)|Brian Quinn]] on 7 November. Reid is a lifelong supporter of the club and described the appointment as \"the greatest honour of my life\".<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/scotland/article2901473.ece |title=John Reid appointed as Celtic chairman |work=Times Online |accessdate=17 February 2008 |date=19 November 2007}}{{subscription}}</ref> His appointment was approved by a large majority of shareholders, though many fans opposed the motion at Celtic's [[annual general meeting]] over Reid's role in the [[British Government]] during the [[Iraq War]].<ref name=\"The Times\"/>\n\nThe start of Strachan's third season saw further changes to the team. [[Neil Lennon]] had left in the summer and centre-half [[Stephen McManus]] was now made captain of the side.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/6923901.stm McManus named new Celtic captain], BBC Sport, 31 July 2007</ref> In May, Celtic completed the signing of midfielder [[Scott Brown (footballer, born June 1985)|Scott Brown]] from Hibernian for a fee of around \u00a34.4&nbsp;million, the largest transfer fee exchanged between two Scottish clubs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Atkinson|first=Mark|title=Celtic bag Brown from under Rangers' nose|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/16/newsstory.sport6|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 March 2014|date=16 May 2007}}</ref> Motherwell striker [[Scott McDonald]] also arrived at Celtic Park, signed for a fee of \u00a3700,000,<ref name=\"smsig\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/motherwell/6511631.stm |title=Celtic complete McDonald capture |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 March 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523045817/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/motherwell/6511631.stm |archivedate=23 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and having been the player who famously scored two late goals against Celtic on the last day of the season in 2005 to effectively hand Rangers the title.<ref name=\"smsig\" /> [[File:KDoddvCelts.jpg|thumb|177px|left|Shunsuke Nakamura against Falkirk in December 2006]]\n\nAs the 2007\u201308 season progressed, Celtic found themselves embroiled in a tight contest with Rangers for the SPL title. Celtic led for the early part of the season, but a series of poor results in the winter and early spring saw Rangers overtake them. A [[Kevin Thomson]] goal on 31 March 2008 gave Rangers a 1\u20130 win at Ibrox over Celtic, leaving Celtic trailing their rivals in the league by six points.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sharp|first=David|title=Rangers 1 Celtic 0|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/7317659.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=29 March 2008}}</ref> A few days later, Neil Lennon returned to Celtic as a coach, effectively replacing first-team coach Tommy Burns, who was being treated for cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grahame|first1=Ewing|title=Neil Lennon joins Celtic's coaching staff|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2296272/Neil-Lennon-joins-Celtics-coaching-staff.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=28 August 2014|date=4 April 2008}}</ref> A dramatic, and seemingly unlikely, turnaround in Celtic's fortunes then began on 16 April, when the Old Firm met again at Celtic Park. A re-invigorated Celtic dominated the opening proceedings and took the lead when Shunsuke Nakamura scored with a spectacular swerving shot from 30 yards. [[Nacho Novo]] equalised for Rangers early in the second half, but Celtic got a chance to retake the lead when Nakamura's curling shot was handled off the line by Rangers defender [[Carlos Cu\u00e9llar]], who was sent off. Rangers goalkeeper [[Allan McGregor]], however, despite having an injured ankle, saved [[Scott McDonald]]'s penalty kick.  Rangers looked like holding on for a vital point until in the third minute of injury time [[Jan Vennegoor of Hesselink]] bundled the ball into the goal to clinch a 2\u20131 win for Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Celtic's last-gasp winner keeps title race alive|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/apr/17/sport.celtic|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=16 April 2008}}</ref> Celtic began to claw back on Rangers lead in the league, and by the time of the final league fixture of the season were league leaders. A Vennegoor of Hesselink headed goal gave Celtic a 1\u20130 win on the night away at Dundee United, clinching the title for Celtic. This ensured Strachan's place in the history books of Celtic, becoming only the third manager to win three successive league titles, behind [[Willie Maley]] and Jock Stein.<ref>{{cite news|last=Conaghan|first=Martin|title=Strachan's magic number is three |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/7414250.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=12 November 2013|date=23 May 2008}}</ref> The victory was also dedicated to the memory of Tommy Burns, former player, manager and coach, who had died earlier that week.<ref>{{cite web|last=McEachran|first=John|title=Fans remember legend Tommy Burns as Celtic clinch SPL title|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/fans-remember-legend-tommy-burns-978135|work=Daily Record|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=23 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maciej \u017burawski Celtic.jpg|thumb|177px|left|Maiej Zurawski in action for Celtic in a pre-season game against FC Basel in July 2007]]\nThe 2007\u201308 season saw Celtic again taking part in the Champions League. Celtic qualified for the group stages by knocking out [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]] in the prelims, the tie eventually going to penalty kicks with Artur Boruc saving twice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=Celtic 1-1 Spartak Moscow (2-2) Celtic win 4-3 on penalties|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6966717.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=29 August 2007}}</ref> Celtic won all three home games in the group stages; a last minute Scott McDonald goal giving Celtic a 2\u20131 win over Milan,<ref>{{cite news|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=Celtic 2 AC Milan 1|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7019611.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=3 October 2007}}</ref> [[Aiden McGeady]] scoring the only goal in a 1\u20130 win over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Sharp|first=David|title=Celtic 1 Benfica 0|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7078731.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=6 November 2007}}</ref> and [[Massimo Donati]] scoring an injury time winner against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Celtic 2-1 Shakhtar Donetsk|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7115381.stm|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=28 November 2007|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Despite losing all three of their corresponding away fixtures, Celtic qualified for the round of 16 for the second successive season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=AC Milan 1-0 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7123562.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=4 December 2007}}</ref> In the first leg of the round of 16 tie against Barcelona, Celtic twice took the lead at Parkhead, but finished losing 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Julian|title=Celtic 2-3 Barcelona|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7250340.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=20 February 2008}}</ref> They were unable to recover the deficit in the return match and were knocked out.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Julian|title=Barcelona 1-0 Celtic (agg: 4-2)|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7272569.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 March 2014|date=4 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, Celtic won the [[2008\u201309 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] beating Rangers 2\u20130 in the final after extra time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Celtic 2-0 Rangers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7941624.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 November 2013|date=15 March 2009}}</ref> Celtic failed to win the [[2008\u201309 Scottish Premier League|SPL title]], finishing second to Rangers and Strachan resigned from the manager's position at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ewan|last=Murray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/25/gordon-strachan-resigns-manager-celtic |title=Gordon Strachan resigns as manager of Celtic in wake of failure to win SPL |work=The Guardian|date=25 May 2009 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tony Mowbray Celtic unhappy edit.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Tony Mowbray, showing the strain]]\n[[Tony Mowbray]] was announced as the replacement for Strachan on 16 June 2009.<ref name=\"gdmow\">{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Tony Mowbray confirmed as new manager of Celtic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jun/16/tony-mowbray-celtic-west-bromwich|work=The Guardian|date=16 June 2009|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> He moved from his managerial post at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]. It was a return to Celtic for the Englishman after playing there for four years between 1991 and 1995 and is considered to be the player who started the famous Celtic prematch \"Huddle\".<ref name=\"gdmow\" /> He promised a \"Barcelona-esque\" style of football, and more attacking play,<ref>{{cite news|last=Traynor|first=James|title=Tony Mowbray: I want to get Celtic playing football like Spain or Barcelona|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/tony-mowbray-i-want-to-get-celtic-playing-1027904|accessdate=14 October 2013|newspaper=Daily Record|date=18 June 2009}}</ref> never afraid to hide his admiration for the likes of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]].<ref>{{cite web|title=West Brom boss Mowbray: Arsenal's Wenger transformed English football|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/west-brom-boss-mowbray-arsenals-wenger-transformed-english-football-197784#.UlxEqdKRD10|date=15 August 2008|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fisher|first=Stewart|title=Sustenance of style for Tony Mowbray|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/celtic/sustenance-of-style-for-tony-mowbray-1.822988|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>  Things started well, he won his first trophy shortly after signing for Celtic, with victory in the [[Wembley Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic win Wembley Cup|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/104863/report|publisher=Sky Sports|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref> He brought [[Marc-Antoine Fortun\u00e9]], [[Landry N'Gu\u00e9mo]] and [[Danny Fox]] to the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=SPL ins and outs|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8105863.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=14 October 2013|date=14 August 2009}}</ref> Things looked very promising when Celtic comprehensively beat Aberdeen in the opening SPL game.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen 1 Celtic 3: McGeady grabs superb brace as Bhoys open campaign with victory |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1206748/Aberdeen-1-Celtic-3-McGeady-grabs-superb-brace-Bhoys-open-campaign-victory.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBecause of the previous season league position, two qualifying rounds were required to enter the Champions league group stages. After a 1\u20130 loss to [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]] at home,<ref>{{cite news|last=Grahame|first=Ewing|title=Celtic 0 Dinamo Moscow 1: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/5934557/Celtic-0-Dinamo-Moscow-1-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=30 October 2013|date=29 July 2009}}</ref> Mowbray lead Celtic to a 2\u20130 win in Moscow, ending a long run of not winning any away games in the Champions league.<ref>{{cite news|last=McGowan|first=Stephen|title=Dynamo Moscow 0 Celtic 2: Georgios Samaras late show sends Bhoys through in Europe |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1204560/Dynamo-Moscow-0-Celtic-2-Georgios-Samaras-late-sends-Bhoys-Europe.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=5 August 2009}}</ref> This was also the first time ever that Celtic had won a European tie after losing the first keg at home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dinamo Moscow 0 Celtic 2: My brave Bhoys got what they deserved, insists Mowbray |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1204565/Dinamo-Moscow-0-Celtic-2-My-brave-Bhoys-got-deserved-insists-Mowbray.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=30 January 2015|date=6 August 2009}}</ref> Celtic were then drawn with English side Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Champions League draw: Arsenal to face Celtic in play-off|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/5988106/Champions-League-draw-Arsenal-to-face-Celtic-in-play-off.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=7 August 2009}}</ref> Celtic lost the home leg, 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawton|first=Matt|title=Celtic 0 Arsenal 2: Gallas lucky dip rocks Scots but flukes don't hide Arsenal's real class|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1207502/Celtic-0-Arsenal-2-William-Gallas-lucky-dip-rocks-Scots-flukes-dont-hide-Arsenals-real-class.html |work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=19 August 2009}}</ref>  In the return leg in the [[Emirates Stadium]], Celtic were holding Arsenal 0\u20130 until a dive by Arsenal striker [[Eduardo da Silva|Eduardo]] won them a penalty, which Eduardo stepped up to put the ball past Artur Boruc from the spot, sending Arsenal en route to a 3\u20131 win. A rejuvenated Massimo Donati scored Celtic's only goal in the last minute.<ref>{{cite news|last=Winter|first=Henry|title=Arsenal 3 Celtic 1; agg 5-1: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/6095206/Arsenal-3-Celtic-1-agg-5-1-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=26 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nThings began to slide after that though, Celtic began hemorrhaging points to the so-called \"smaller teams\" in the league.<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Patience runs thin at Parkhead as Tony Mowbray's Celtic project stalls|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2009/nov/27/tony-mowbray-celtic-paul-le-guen|work=The Guardian|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=27 November 2009}}</ref> Celtic then exited the UEFA Europa League before Christmas despite a promising draw of group opponents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 2 Hapoel Tel-Aviv 0: Bhoys win at last in Europa League but it's too little too late|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1232747/Celtic-2-Hapoel-Tel-Aviv-0-Bhoys-win-Europa-League-little-late.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=3 December 2009}}</ref>  Despite a big squad shake-up in the January transfer window, including the departure of club captain Stephen McManus,<ref name=\"mgone\">{{cite news|last=Greechan|first=John|title=Celtic beat Hull City and West Brom to sign Fulham's Diomansy Kamara on loan as Scott McDonald edges closer to exit|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1247219/Celtic-beat-Hull-City-West-Brom-sign-Fulhams-Diomansy-Kamara-loan-Scott-McDonald-edges-closer-exit.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=30 January 2010}}</ref> leading goalscorer Scott McDonald,<ref name=\"mgone1\">{{cite web|title=Scott McDonald leaves Celtic for Middlesbrough|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/celtic/154604-scott-mcdonald-leaves-celtic-for-middlesbrough/|publisher=STV Sport|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=1 February 2010}}</ref>  [[Barry Robson]],<ref name=\"mgone1\" /> the newly acquired Danny Fox<ref name=\"mgone\" /> and a number of other fringe players; and the bringing in of Republic of Ireland striker [[Robbie Keane]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Tottenham's Robbie Keane moves to Celtic on loan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/feb/01/robbie-keane-celtic-loan-tottenham|work=The Guardian|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=1 February 2010}}</ref> [[Diomansy Kamara]]<ref name=\"mgone\" /> and others, Tony Mowbray was sacked by the club the day after their 4\u20130 defeat by [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 24 March 2010 and Neil Lennon took charge for the remainder of the [[2009\u201310 Celtic F.C. season|2009\u201310 season]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Galluzzo|first=Mauro|title=Tony Mowbray sacked by Celtic as Neil Lennon takes over|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/165174/Tony-Mowbray-sacked-by-Celtic-as-Neil-Lennon-takes-over|work=Daily Express|accessdate=31 October 2013|date=25 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Neil Lennon (2010\u20132014)==\n\n===\"Bring back the thunder\"===\n[[File:Neil lennon and excalibur.jpg|thumb|left|Former Celtic captain, Neil Lennon]]\n\nNeil Lennon became the caretaker manager after Tony Mowbray was fired, bringing in former teammate [[Johan Mj\u00e4llby]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic caretaker boss Neil Lennon wants job permanently|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8588663.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=26 March 2010}}</ref> Celtic were ten points behind Rangers, who had played two less games, when Lennon took over.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic end manager Tony Mowbray's troubled reign|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8586352.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=25 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jackson|first=Keith|title=Neil Lennon goes from Celtic outcast to Parkhead boss in just a few hours following Tony Mowbray's departure|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2010/03/26/neil-lennon-goes-from-celtic-outcast-to-parkhead-boss-in-space-of-just-hours-following-tony-mowbray-s-departure-86908-22139827/|work=Daily Record|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=26 March 2010}}</ref> Despite having no management experience Lennon lead Celtic to eight wins from the eight remaining league matches, finishing six points behind their Old Firm rivals<ref name=end0910>{{cite news|title=Hearts 1 - 2 Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8666273.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=9 May 2010}}</ref> who they also beat 2\u20131 in the final Old Firm match of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 2 - 1 Rangers|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8658392.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|first=Andy|last=Campbell|date=4 May 2010}}</ref> This provided a much needed morale boost to the club. Celtic's one chance for silverware was the [[2009\u201310 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]], they faced [[Scottish First Division|First Division]] [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] in the semi-final but lost 2\u20130. In the aftermath of the Ross County match, Lennon spoke frankly about his opinion of the players and their performances over the course of the season; he said that the players had lacked \"hunger and desire\" and that whether he was installed as manager or not, he would be recommending a serious clear-out of players to the board.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,13869_6085625,00.html|title= Lennon questions Hoops attitude|work=Sky Sports|date=10 April 2010|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8613251.stm|title=Neil Lennon slams the lack of Celtic hunger and desire|work=BBC Sport|date=10 April 2010|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2010, despite concern over his lack of experience, Lennon was officially announced as the new Celtic manager<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=New Celtic manager Neil Lennon prepares to reach for the stars and reclaim SPL title|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/7815427/New-Celtic-manager-Neil-Lennon-prepares-to-reach-for-the-stars-and-reclaim-SPL-title.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=9 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New manager Neil Lennon wants Celtic 'to go to war'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8728818.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=9 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lennon takes Celtic centre stage|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8716347.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=8 June 2010}}</ref> He retained Mj\u00e4llby as his assistant, as well as former Celtic teammate Alan Thompson and former Leicester City teammate [[Garry Parker]] as first-team coaches<ref name=Teamup>{{cite news|title=Celtic appoint Johan Mj\u00e4llby and Garry Parker|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8780796.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=1 July 2010}}</ref>  Lennon stated his desire to \"bring back the thunder\" to Celtic Park.<ref>{{cite web|first=Keith|last=Jackson |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/neil-lennon-i-want-to-put-thunder-1061348 |title=Neil Lennon: I want to put thunder back into Celtic Park |work=Daily Record |date=10 June 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311====\nLennon made considerable changes to the Celtic team for the [[2010\u201311 Celtic F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]]. A number of players left the club over the summer, including Aiden McGeady, who was sold for a then Scottish record \u00a39.5&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2010/08/13/aiden-mcgeady-puts-pen-to-paper-on-9-5m-switch-to-spartak-moscow-86908-22485224/ |title=Aiden McGeady puts pen to paper on \u00a39.5m switch to Spartak Moscow|work=Daily Record|date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=21 July 2011}}</ref> In turn, a large number of talented, young, cheap, relatively unknown players from England and smaller leagues around the world were signed. Several more experienced players also arrived at this time to strengthen the squad. [[Gary Hooper]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Scunthorpe striker Gary Hooper signs for Celtic|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8852050.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=27 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Scunthorpe's Gary Hooper completes \u00a32.5m move to Celtic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/27/gary-hooper-celtic|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=27 July 2010}}</ref> [[Beram Kayal]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic sign Israel midfielder Beram Kayal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8849942.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=29 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic complete signing of Israeli midfielder Biram Kayal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/29/celtic-transfer-israeli-midfielder-biram-kayal|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=29 July 2010}}</ref> and [[Emilio Izaguirre]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic sign Honduran international defender Emilio Izaguirre|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2010/08/18/celtic-sign-honduran-international-defender-emilio-izaguirre-86908-22496304/|work=Daily Record|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=18 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Neil Lennon boosts Celtic ranks with Honduras defender Emilio Izaguirre|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1304132/Emilio-Izaguirre-signs-Celtic.html|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=18 August 2010|work=Mail Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic complete deal for left-back Emilio Izaguirre|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8925044.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=18 August 2010}}</ref> all had excellent seasons and earned many plaudits,<ref name=signingpolicy>{{cite news|url= http://sport.stv.tv/football/scottish-premier/celtic/261423-neil-lennon-explains-celtics-recruitment-policy/|title=Neil Lennon explains Celtic's recruitment policy |work=STV Sport|date=6 July 2011 |accessdate = 18 July 2011}}</ref> with Izaguirre winning both the [[SPFA Players' Player of the Year|SPFA]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13256109.stm|title=Emilio Izaguirre wins Scotland's players' player prize|publisher=BBC |work=BBC Sport|date=1 May 2011|accessdate=2 May 2011}}</ref> and [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers']]<ref>{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13406778.stm |title=More awards for Izaguirre, Goodwillie and Paatelainan |work=BBC Sport |date=15 May 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2011 }}</ref> Player of the Year awards. Goalkeeper [[Fraser Forster]], signed on loan from Newcastle United,<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic boss Neil Lennon signs Newcastle keeper Fraser Forster on loan for the season|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1305686/Celtic-sign-Newcastle-keeper-Fraser-Forster-loan-season.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=24 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic sign goalkeeper Fraser Forster on loan from Newcastle|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/aug/24/fraser-forster-joins-celtic-loan|work=The Guardian|author=Press Association|date=24 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Newcastle goalkeeper Fraser Forster on Celtic loan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/8935182.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=24 August 2010}}</ref> on became first choice goalkeeper and helped set a new SPL record for most clean sheets in a season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/editor-s-picks/fraser-forster-proud-of-role-in-shut-out-success-1.1102140 |title=Fraser Forster proud of role in shut-out success |work=Evening Times\n|date=18 May 2011|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>[[File:Izaguirre Nov2010.jpg|thumb|right|Emilio Izaguirre was voted SPFA Player of the Year in 2011]]\n\nCeltic were knocked out of the Champions League and Europa League at the first hurdles, losing to [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] and [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]] respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/soccer/2010/0826/1224277683720.html|title=Dutch disaster for Celtic|work=Irish Times|date=26 August 2010 |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> Celtic and Rangers both won their first eight SPL games,<ref name=CRAIH>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/9122150.stm Celtic v Rangers as it happened] BBC Sport, 24 October 2010</ref> but when the sides first clashed Celtic lost 3\u20131.<ref name=CRAIH/> Celtic played fairly well up until the next Old Firm match, but still went into the New Year fixture at Ibrox as underdogs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/8234551/Rangers-manager-Walter-Smith-dismisses-favourites-tag-ahead-of-Sundays-emotional-Old-Firm-derby-at-Ibrox.html|title=Rangers manager Walter Smith dismisses favourites' tag ahead of Sunday's emotional Old Firm derby at Ibrox|work=The Telegraph|date=31 December 2010|accessdate=19 July 2011|first=Roddy|last=Forsyth}}</ref> However, Celtic won 2\u20130 thanks to a [[Georgios Samaras]] brace<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/9330644.stm</ref> and went onto win 15 out of their 19 matches in the second half of the season.<ref name=\"10/11SPL\" /> Draws at [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]] and Ibrox, however, as well as losses at Inverness and Motherwell, saw them lose the league by a point.<ref name=\"10/11SPL\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=home_Statistics |title=SPL Table 2010-11 |publisher=Scottish Premier League |accessdate=20 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612200756/http://www.scotprem.com/content/default.asp?page=home_Statistics |archivedate=12 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, Celtic did have the best defensive record only conceding 22 goals.<ref name=\"10/11SPL\" />\n\nCeltic got to the final of both domestic cups in 2010\u201311. They lost the [[2011 Scottish League Cup Final|League Cup final]] 2\u20131 to Rangers but won the [[2011 Scottish Cup Final|Scottish Cup final]] 3\u20130 against Motherwell.<ref>{{cite news|title=Motherwell 0 - 3 Celtic |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/9491542.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 July 2011|date=21 May 2011 |first=Martin|last=Conaghan}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lennon will never walk alone.jpg|thumb|right|Celtic fans show their support for Neil Lennon in 2011]]\nIn 2011, Neil Lennon was subject to a terror campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1363205/Lennon-quit-Celtic-Parkhead-boss-assess-future-terror-threat.html |title=Lennon may quit Celtic: Parkhead boss will assess his future after terror threat |work=Mail Online |date=5 March 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011 |first=John |last=Greechan}}</ref><ref name=Heraldbomb>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/police-in-hunt-for-celtic-bomb-fiend-1.1097224 |title=Police in hunt for Celtic bomb fiend |work=Herald Scotland |date=20 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> In January he, along with two other [[Northern Irish]], [[Catholic]], Celtic players [[Niall McGinn]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Ewan |title=Neil Lennon brushes aside bullets threat as Celtic ease past Berwick |work=The Guardian |date=10 January 2011 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jan/09/berwick-rangers-celtic-scottish-cup}}</ref> and [[Paddy McCourt]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-12168533 |title=Bullets in post target Celtic footballer Paddy McCourt |work=BBC News |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> were sent packages containing bullets in the post. In March and April two [[parcel bomb]]s were sent to high-profile fans of Celtic and two bombs were sent to Lennon. [[Trish Godman]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] and [[Paul McBride]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], who had represented Celtic in their court cases with the SFA, were both sent bombs through the [[Royal Mail]]. All of the devices were addressed to their places of work.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-13141592 |title=Neil Lennon parcel bomb 'cowardly act' |work=BBC News |date=20 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> The bombs, described by [[Strathclyde Police]] as being designed to \"kill or maim\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/celtic-football-boss-targeted-by-parcel-bomb-20110421-1dp5g.html |title=Celtic football boss targeted by parcel bomb |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> were widely condemned by footballing and political authorities. [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] leader, [[Iain Gray]], described the act as \"terrorism\" and [[First Minister of Scotland]] [[Alex Salmond]] said that, \"It is time to remember what we value in society, and unite to condemn those who use football as a pretext for their pathetic and dangerous prejudices.\"<ref name=quotes:bombs>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-13141898 |title=In quotes: Reaction to Celtic bomb threats |work=BBC News |date=20 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=quotes:bombs /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-13156498 |title=Lennon parcel bomb 'appalling act' says David Cameron |work=BBC News |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> Lennon and his family had to receive 24-hour police protection because of the bombs and threats.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/2011/03/05/latest-death-threat-against-neil-lennon-could-make-him-think-about-future-at-celtic-says-coach-alan-thompson-86908-22967583/ |title=Latest death threat against Neil Lennon could make him think about his Celtic future, says Alan Thompson |work=Daily Record |date=5 March 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> He also had to receive police protection at matches due to the threats against him.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-13159462 |title=Celtic fans offer Neil Lennon support after parcel bomb |work=BBC News |date=21 April 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> However, this did not stop a man at a match against Hearts at [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle]] running onto the pitch and attacking him. Lennon was uninjured, and the man was charged with assault and breach of the peace, both aggravated by religious prejudice.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-13368945 |title=Celtic manager Neil Lennon attack suspect in court |work=BBC News |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate = 20 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312====\nThe 2011\u201312 season saw Celtic make a poor start to their league campaign. Despite rising concerns about their financial situation, Rangers under new manager [[Ally McCoist]] topped the league table for the first few months. Celtic were run ragged by Rangers in the first Old Firm game of the season, a 4\u20132 win for the Ibrox club on 18 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|date=18 September 2011|title=Rangers 4 Celtic 2: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/8771949/Rangers-4-Celtic-2-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> By October 2011, Celtic were 15 points behind Rangers in the league, albeit Rangers had played two more games than Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Title success can enhance Celtic hunger - Alan Thompson|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17639324|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>  On 15 October 2011 at Rugby Park, Celtic trailed 0\u20133 at half-time to Kilmarnock. Lennon later admitted that had Celtic conceded a further goal he would have resigned.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Neil Lennon admits he would have resigned if Celtic had conceded another goal against Kilmarnock|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/8931544/Neil-Lennon-admits-he-would-have-resigned-if-Celtic-had-conceded-another-goal-against-Kilmarnock.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 October 2013|date=2 December 2011}}</ref> Instead, Celtic rallied in the second half and two goals from [[Anthony Stokes]] and a header from Charlie Mulgrew secured an unlikely 3\u20133 draw.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kilmarnock 3 Celtic 3: match report|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/scottish-premier/8829105/Kilmarnock-3-Celtic-3-match-report.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 October 2013|date=15 October 2011}}</ref>  Celtic began to find form, and by Christmas had closed the gap between themselves and Rangers to one point.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 2 Kilmarnock 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16229733|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> This run included a 1\u20130 win over Hearts on 10 December 2011 where [[Victor Wanyama]], signed from Belgium club [[Beerschot AC|Beerschot]] for \u00a3900,000 in July,<ref>{{cite web|last=McGuigan|first=Thomas|title=Kenya's Victor Wanyama shines for Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22253408|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=22 April 2013}}</ref> scored his first goal for Celtic with a powerful 25-yard shot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wonderful Wanyama delights Celts with his first goal|url=http://www.extratime.es/news/52/wonderful-wanyama-delights-celts-with-his-first-goal|work=Extra Time|accessdate=18 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019093908/http://www.extratime.es/news/52/wonderful-wanyama-delights-celts-with-his-first-goal|archivedate=19 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In the same match, Hearts were awarded a controversial penalty in the last minute but Fraser Forster saved [[Eggert Jonsson]]'s penalty kick.<ref>{{cite web|last=Conaghan|first=Martin|title=Celtic 1 Hearts 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16015615|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=10 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[Joe Ledley]] goal on 28 December 2011 gave Celtic a 1\u20130 win over Rangers at Parkhead, and saw them go top of the table two points clear of Rangers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moffat|first=Colin|title=Celtic 1 Rangers 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16281414|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>  By February 2012, Celtic had increased their lead to four points.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 1 Inverness CT 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16884902|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> The title was then all but secured when Rangers entered into [[Administration (British football)|administration]] on 14 February 2012, with the Ibrox club incurring a ten-point deduction from the Scottish Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers' 10-point deduction confirmed by SPL|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17032099|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> Celtic's unbeaten league run continued up to the next Old Firm game on 25 March 2012 when a poor performance exacerbated by several contentious refereeing decisions saw Rangers win 3\u20132 and prevent their rivals clinching the league title that day.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Rangers 3 Celtic 2|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17419735|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=25 March 2012}}</ref> The title was eventually secured in style a couple of weeks later with an emphatic 6\u20130 win over Kilmarnock at Rugby Park, Gary Hooper and Charlie Mulgrew both scoring twice.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Kimarnock 0 Celtic 6|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17570842|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=7 April 2012}}</ref>  Celtic's next league fixture saw them comfortably beat Rangers 3\u20130 in a party atmosphere at Parkhead in a match more notable for the Celtic fans colourful banners mocking Rangers on-going financial problems rather than events on the pitch.<ref>{{cite web|last=McHugh|first=Joe|title=Green Brigade show Rangers no mercy|url=http://videocelts.com/2012/04/blogs/green-brigade-show-no-mercy|work=Video Celts|accessdate=18 October 2013|date=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Murray|first=Ewan|title=Celtic stroll past Rangers in season's final Old Firm match|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/apr/29/celtic-rangers-scottish-premier-league|accessdate=18 October 2013|work=The Guardian|date=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=English|first=Tom|title=Badly beaten, cruelly goaded Ibrox men endure longest day|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/tom-english-badly-beaten-cruelly-goaded-ibrox-men-endure-longest-day-1-2264705|website=The Scotsman|accessdate=10 August 2015|date=30 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe domestic cup tournaments proved a source of disappointment in the 2011\u201312 season. Celtic reached the League Cup final and were strong favourites to win against unfancied Kilmarnock.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theawayend.net/articles/football/the-away-end-archive/1055-full-preview-celtic-v-kilmarnock |title=Full Preview: Celtic v Kilmarnock |publisher=Theawayend.net |date=18 March 2001 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112044639/http://www.theawayend.net/articles/football/the-away-end-archive/1055-full-preview-celtic-v-kilmarnock |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  However, Celtic were uninspiring on the day and a headed goal six minutes from the end by [[Dieter van Tornhout]] won the League Cup for the Ayrshire side. In the Scottish Cup, Celtic reached the semi-final and were drawn to play Hearts. Again, Celtic were not at their best and [[Craig Beattie]]'s stoppage time penalty secured a 2\u20131 win for ''The Jambos''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay |first=Clive |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17649430 |title=Celtic 1-2 Hearts |work=BBC Sport |date=15 April 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nCeltic qualified for the Europa League group stages in 2011\u201312 in bizarre circumstances. Swiss side [[FC Sion|Sion]] defeated Celtic 3\u20131 on aggregate in the qualifying tie,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14569496 |title=Sion 3-1 Celtic (agg 3-1) |work=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2011 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  however Sion were thrown out of the tournament by UEFA due to them fielding ineligible players in the two games against Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ewan Murray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/sep/02/celtic-europa-league-fc-sion |title=Celtic back in Europa League after successful protest against FC Sion |work=The Guardian |date=2 September 2011 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> Celtic were reinstated, eventually finishing third in Group I, behind [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] and [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] and ahead of [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Campbell |first=Andy |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/celtic/9662325.stm |title=Udinese v Celtic as it happened |work=BBC News |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Despite failing to progress from the group stages of the Europa League, Celtic had a respectable campaign and their performances on the European stage are considered to have acted as a catalyst for the improvement in their domestic form as the season progressed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16081808 |accessdate=3 September 2014 |work=BBC Sport |title=Udinese 1 Celtic 1 |last=Conaghan |first=Martin |date=15 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/neil-lennon-celtic-have-fallen-in-love-with-the-europa-league.15995841 |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=3 September 2014 |last=Grant |first=Michael |date=30 November 2011 |title=Neil Lennon: Celtic have fallen in love with the Europa League}}</ref>\n\n===A new era===\n\n====2012\u201313====\n[[File:Victor Wanyama 2012.jpg|180px|thumb|left|Victor Wanyama - voted the SPL Young Player of the Year in 2013]]\nThe summer of 2012 saw extraordinary developments in Scottish football. Rangers, who were being  pursued by [[HM Revenue and Customs]] (HMRC) for alleged unpaid tax, effectively went into [[liquidation]] on 12 June 2012 when HMRC rejected the club's proposed [[Company Voluntary Arrangement]] (CVA).<ref>{{cite news|author=John Mcgarry |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2158089/Rangers-liquidation-danger-CVA-deal-rejected.html |title=Rangers liquidation danger after CVA deal is rejected |work=Mail Online |date=13 June 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> A new company was quickly formed and the club re-constituted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football.co.uk/rangers/reformed_rangers_meet_brechin_in_challenge_cup_rss3069463.shtml |title=Reformed Rangers meet Brechin in Challenge Cup - Rangers News from |publisher=football.co.uk |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> However, despite an at-times hysterical [[Media of Scotland|media]] campaign making references to financial \"Armageddon\" for the other clubs in Scotland,<ref>{{cite news|author=Stephen Mcgowan |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2168730/Rangers-booted-SPL-Scottish-rivals-reject-newco-appeal.html |title=Rangers booted out of the SPL after Scottish rivals reject newco appeal |work=Mail Online |date=4 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ewan Murray |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/aug/03/spl-clubs-rangers-fans-celtic |title=SPL clubs ready to bridge Rangers gap but fans must show their support |work=the Guardian |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> the re-formed Rangers were not allowed re-entry to the Scottish Premier League and instead were placed in the lowest tier of the Scottish Football League, the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Third Division]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Brian Marjoribanks |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2173130/Rangers-voted-Third-Division.html |title=Rangers voted into Third Division |work=Mail Online |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIgnoring the ongoing furore surrounding Rangers' financial crisis, Celtic went about their 2012\u201313 league campaign in a steady if not always inspiring manner.<ref name=\"wsc1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/wsc-daily/1163-june-2013/9868-2012-13-season-in-review-celtic |title=2012-13 season in review: Celtic |work=When Saturday Comes |date=9 July 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112052057/http://www.wsc.co.uk/wsc-daily/1163-june-2013/9868-2012-13-season-in-review-celtic |archive-date=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Motherwell, Inverness Caley Thistle and briefly Hibernian all either had spells at the top of the table, or thereabouts, but by Christmas Celtic had found a steady run of form to pull themselves comfortably clear of the pack.<ref name=\"wsc1\" />  Celtic eventually clinched their 44th League title on 21 April 2013 with a 4\u20131 win over Inverness CT at Parkhead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/celtic-clinch-title-in-style-2013-04-21/ |title=Celtic clinch title in style |publisher=Spfl.co.uk |date=21 April 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> Celtic's run in the League Cup saw them comfortably dispose of [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] (4\u20131)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19632469 |title=Celtic 4-1 Raith Rovers |work=BBC Sport|date=25 September 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> and St Johnstone (5\u20130)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20053650 |title=Celtic 5-0 St Johnstone |work=BBC Sport |date=30 October 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> in the earlier rounds. St Mirren, however, pulled off an unexpected but deserved 3\u20132 win over Celtic in the semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell |first=Andy |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21106906 |title=St Mirren 3-2 Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=27 January 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the Scottish Cup, Celtic knocked out [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]], Raith Rovers,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21218450 |title=Raith Rovers 0\u20133 Celtic |first=Stevie |last=Miller |work=BBC Sport |date=3 February 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> and St Mirren<ref name = \"mirren\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21556779 |first=Kenny |last=Crawford |title=St Mirren 1\u20132 Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> in the earlier rounds. In the semi-final at Hampden Park, Celtic won a thrilling match by 4\u20133 after extra time against Dundee United.<ref name = \"united\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22056531 |title=Dundee Utd 3\u20134 Celtic |first=Clive |last=Lindsay |work=BBC Sport |date=14 April 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> Celtic met Hibernian in the Scottish Cup final on 26 May 2013.  For the first time in its history, the Cup Final was played on a Sunday.<ref name = \"sunday\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16685196|title=Sunday switch for 2013 Scottish Cup final|work=BBC Sport |date=23 January 2012|accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref> This was done to comply with UEFA regulations which prohibit televised matches being played on the same day as the [[UEFA Champions League Final]].  Celtic won the cup and clinched a League and Cup double with a 3\u20130 win, Gary Hooper scoring twice in the first half before Joe Ledley added a third late on in the second half.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22585339 |title=Scottish Cup final: Hibernian 0-3 Celtic |work=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs Scottish Champions from the previous season, Celtic took part in the 2012\u201313 Champions League, negotiating two qualifying rounds to qualify for the tournament proper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19424943 |title=Champions League: Celtic to face Barcelona, Benfica & Spartak |work=BBC Sport |date=30 August 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> On 2 October 2012, Celtic achieved their first ever away win in the group stages of the Champions League with a 3\u20132 win in Russia over Spartak Moscow, Georgios Samaras scoring the winning goal in the 90th minute.<ref>{{cite news|author=Stephen Mcgowan |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/article-2211872/Spartak-Moscow-2-Celtic-3.html |title=Spartak Moscow 2 Celtic 3 |work=Mail Online |date=2 October 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Celtic's home match with Barcelona in November 2012 coincided with the week of Celtic's 125th Anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dave Wood |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2229241/Lionel-Messi-Xavi-Hernandez-Andres-Iniesta-join-Celtics-125th-birthday-celebrations.html |title=Lionel Messi, Xavi Hernandez and Andres Iniesta join in Celtic's 125th birthday celebrations |work=Mail Online |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  As such, an ''[[Ultras]]'' styled section of the Celtic support called the [[Green Brigade]] organised a full stadium pre-match card display (a ''[[tifo]]'') to celebrate the club's 125th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|title=Incredible pre-match display from supporters |url=http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3319 |work=celticfc.net |publisher=Celtic F.C. |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112134748/http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3319 |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The display featured a [[Celtic cross]], green and white hoops and ''125 Celtic'' in written form, with supporters earning the praise of club chairman [[Peter Lawwell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Peter Lawwell congratulates team and support on collective effort |url=http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3325 |work=celticfc.net |publisher=Celtic F.C. |date=8 November 2012 |accessdate=8 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112134645/http://www.celticfc.net/newsstory?item=3325 |archivedate=12 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  A memorable night was completed when goals from Victor Wanyama and 18-year-old striker [[Tony Watt]] gave Celtic a shock 2\u20131 win over Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20150451 |title=Celtic 2-1 Barcelona |work=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> Goalkeeper Fraser Forster produced an outstanding performance in the game, winning the praise of the Spanish media who nicknamed him \"''La Gran Muralla''\" (\"The Great Wall\").<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/11/08/fraser-forster-great-wall_n_2091816.html |title=Fraser Forster Great Wall |work=Huffington Post | date = 8 November 2012 | accessdate = 8 November 2012 }}</ref>  Celtic secured their progress to the knock-out stages of the Champions League on 5 December 2012 with a 2\u20131 home win over Spartak Moscow, [[Kris Commons]] scoring the winning goal in 82 minutes with a penalty.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20522174 |title=Celtic 2-1 Spartak Moscow |work=BBC Sport |date=5 December 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Celtic were drawn against Juventus but succumbed to 5\u20130 aggregate defeat in the Spring of 2013 to go out of the tournament. Despite the emphatic scoreline over the two legs, Celtic were not outclassed by their Italian opponents in terms of general play but while Juventus defended with a ruthless defiance, Celtic in contrast shipped their goals all far too easily.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Mcgowan |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2289315/Juventus-2-Celtic-0-agg-5-0--Neil-Lennons-Champions-League-dream-over.html |title=Juventus 2 Celtic 0 (agg 5-0): Neil Lennon's Champions League dream over |work=Mail Online |date=6 March 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>  Despite the result against Juventus, Celtic and Neil Lennon won praise for their Champions League campaign.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tony |last=Haggerty |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-boss-neil-lennon-just-2670834 |title=Celtic boss Neil Lennon is just like my old man Harry in the dugout, claims ex-England star Jamie Redknapp |work=Daily Record |date=3 November 2013 |accessdate=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107032139/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-boss-neil-lennon-just-2670834 |archivedate=7 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Jeff Stelling |url=http://www.skysports.com/opinion/story/0,25212,12088_8235533,00.html |title=Celtic win over Barcelona compels Jeff Stelling to tackle a challenging problem |work=Sky Sports |date=8 November 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Jeff Stelling |url=http://www.skysports.com/opinion/story/0,25212,12088_8313877,00.html |title=Man City could learn a lot from Celtic's Champions League exploits |work=Sky Sports |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314====\nOver the summer, Gary Hooper and [[Kelvin Wilson]] were sold to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] respectively, while the highly rated Victor Wanyama was sold to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for a Scottish record fee of \u00a312.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic in record breaking transfer sale as Wanyama heads south|url=http://www.scotzine.com/2013/07/celtic-in-record-breaking-transfer-sale-as-wanyama-heads-south/|work=Scotzine|accessdate=7 May 2014|date=11 July 2013}}</ref>  Neil Lennon rebuilt his squad by signing [[Virgil van Dijk]] and [[Amido Bald\u00e9]] in the summer, and [[Teemu Pukki]] from [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] on transfer deadline day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic sign Teemu Pukki from Schalke on four-year deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23832031|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kris Commons 2012.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Kris Commons \u2013 Celtic's top scorer in 2014 and Scottish Player of the Year]]\nCeltic again started their season playing in the qualifying rounds of the Champions League, knocking out Northern Irish champions [[Cliftonville F.C.|Cliftonville]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 2 Cliftonville 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23324257|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=23 July 2013}}</ref> and Swedish side [[IF Elfsborg]] to reach the final play-off round.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=Elfsborg 0 Celtic 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23513157|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=7 August 2013}}</ref> Celtic were drawn with Kazakh champions [[Shakhter Karagandy]] and found themselves losing the first leg away in [[Karagandy]] 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grant|first=Michael|title=Shakhter Karagandy 2 Celtic 0: stirring cocktail leaves Lennon's side groggy|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/shakhter-karagandy-2-celtic-0-stirring-cocktail-leaves-lennon-s-side-groggy.1377061269|work=Herald Scotland|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=21 August 2013}}</ref>  Celtic rallied in the return leg at Celtic Park in the home leg, overcoming the 2\u20130 deficit to level the aggregate score thanks to goals either side of half-time by Kris Commons and Georgios Samaras. [[James Forrest (footballer)|James Forrest]] completed the comeback for Celtic with a 90th-minute strike, seeing Celtic progress to the Group stages.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Celtic 3 Shakhter Karagandy 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23776602|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=28 August 2013}}</ref> The campaign from then on was dismal though; winning only once with a 2\u20131 home win over Ajax,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamont|first=Alasdair|title=Celtic 2 Ajax 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24614436|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=22 October 2013}}</ref> and slumping to a 6\u20131 rout away against Barcelona in the final group match.<ref name=\"thrash\">{{cite web|last=Lamont|first=Alasdair|title=Barcelona 6 Celtic 1 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25303700|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 February 2014|date=11 December 2013}}</ref>  That game saw Celtic concede the most goals they had ever done in a single European tie, and equalled their previous heaviest defeat in Europe (5-0 against [[FC Artmedia Bratislava|Artmedia Bratislava]]).<ref name=\"thrash\" />\n\nThe domestic campaign had ups and downs; towards the end of February, Celtic had not lost a single game in the league,<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Eric|title=The prospect of going a whole season unbeaten is driving the Celtic players on|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/football/366845/The-prospect-of-going-a-whole-season-unbeaten-is-driving-the-Celtic-players-on|work=Daily Star|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=24 February 2014}}</ref> and drew just twice against Dundee United and Hibernian. Their league success did not translate to cup competition however; going out of the League Cup (0\u20131 to [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]]),<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 0 - 1 Morton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24122182|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=24 September 2014}}</ref> and the [[Scottish Cup]](1\u20132 to [[Aberdeen]]),<ref>{{cite web|last=MacDonald|first=Calum|title=Celtic 1 - 2 Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25995228|accessdate=17 March 2014|date=8 February 2014}}</ref> both at Celtic Park. Celtic also struggled to find a suitable strike partner for [[Anthony Stokes]], forcing Kris Commons into a striking role. Neil Lennon signed former Hibs striker [[Leigh Griffiths]] on [[Transfer window|transfer deadline day]] in January 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25977707|title=Wolves striker Griffiths joins Celtic|work=BBC Sport|date=31 January 2014}}</ref> as well as [[Stefan Johansen]] earlier in the month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spfl/stefan-johansen-signs-for-celtic-1-3268643|last=Walker|first=Mark||title=Stefan Johansen signs for Celtic|work=The Scotsman |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> After being unable to reach an agreement on a new contract, Joe Ledley left Celtic for [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ledley Joins Palace |url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/2014/january/ledley-joins-palace/ |work=Crystal Palace FC |date=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2014, goalkeeper Fraser Forster set a new a club-record of 11 league clean sheets in a row,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26011023 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 February 2014 |title=Celtic: Neil Lennon applauds record-breaking Fraser Forster}}</ref> surpassing a record of 10 clean sheets set by [[Charlie Shaw (footballer, born 1885)|Charlie Shaw]] in the 1921\u201322 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11787/9147994/neil-lennon-proud-to-break-92-year-old-record-in-win-over-st-mirren |title=Neil Lennon proud to break 92-year-old record in win over St Mirren  |accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>  On 22 February, he broke [[Bobby Clark (footballer)|Bobby Clark]]'s Scottish League record of 1155 minutes without conceding a goal in a league match. Celtic won 2\u20130 away at Hearts, and Forster racked up his 13th consecutive clean sheet in the league.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Premiership LIVE: Hearts v Celtic |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/scottish-premiership-live-hearts-v-3172172 |work=Daily Record |accessdate=22 February 2014 |date=22 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425003512/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/scottish-premiership-live-hearts-v-3172172 |archivedate=25 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hearts 0 Celtic 2: Double thumbs up for Celtic at Tynecastle as Fraser Forster sets new record and Leigh Griffiths strikes |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/hearts-0-celtic-2-double-3172864 |work=Daily Record |accessdate=1 March 2014 |date=22 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309102535/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/hearts-0-celtic-2-double-3172864 |archivedate=9 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> \nForster's clean sheet run finally ended on 1,256 minutes against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] on 25 February 2014, as Aberdeen defeated Celtic 2\u20131 to end their unbeaten run in the league.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25892139 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=26 February 2014 |title=Aberdeen 2-1 Celtic}}</ref>\n\nCeltic finished the season as league champions again, their third consecutive [[Scottish Professional Football League|Scottish League]] title,<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Alan|title=Celtic crush Partick Thistle to make it three SPL titles in a row|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/mar/26/celtic-partick-thistle-scottish-premier-league-match-report|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 April 2014|date=26 March 2014}}</ref> scoring 102 goals in the process.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 3 Dundee Utd 1: champion Hoops take home the trophy|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/celtic-3-dundee-utd-1-celtic-confirm-champion-status-with-united-win-and-take-home-th.1399815846|work=Herald Online|accessdate=12 May 2014|date=11 May 2014}}</ref>  Kris Commons was the top scorer in Scotland, netting 32 goals, and won both the [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|PFA Scotland]] and [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers']] Player of the Year awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic's Kris Commons named Premiership player of year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27183434|work=BBC Sport|date=28 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic's Kris Commons is football writers' player of year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27362516|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 May 2014|date=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 2014, Neil Lennon announced that he was leaving Celtic after four years as manager. \"I have parted company with Celtic,\" the 42-year-old Northern Irishman said in a brief statement, adding, \"The club are in a very strong position and I wish the fans and the club all the very best for the future.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=McLaughlin|first=Chris|title=Neil Lennon ends his four-year spell as manager|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27519596|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=22 May 2014|date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Ronny Deila (2014\u20132016)==\nNorwegian [[Ronny Deila]] was appointed manager of Celtic on 6 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27718845 |title=Celtic confirm Ronny Deila as new manager |work=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/6007 |title=Ronny Deila appointed as new Celtic manager |publisher=Celtic FC |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>  He signed a 12-month rolling contract with the club,<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2650572/Celtic-appoint-Norwegian-Ronny-Deila-new-manager.html|title= Celtic appoint Norwegian Ronny Deila as new manager on 12-month rolling contract|date=6 June 2014|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref> with former Celtic midfielder and Scotland international [[John Collins (footballer, born 1968)|John Collins]] appointed as his assistant.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27890417 |title=Celtic: John Collins appointed as Ronny Deila's assistant boss |work=BBC Sport |date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u201315===\nAfter going unbeaten on a pre-season tour in Austria,<ref>{{cite web|last=Henderson|first=Mark|title=Ronny Deila: We'll be positive in Iceland|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/6223|publisher=Celtic FC |accessdate=15 July 2014|date=13 July 2014}}</ref> Deila's first competitive match as manager of Celtic, a Champions League qualifying tie away against [[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Reykjav\u00edkur|KR Reykjavik]] on 15 July 2014, ended in a 1\u20130 win with midfielder [[Callum McGregor]] scoring the decisive goal on 84 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|last=McVake|first=Roddie|title=KR Reykjav\u00edk 0 - 1 Celtic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28278531|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 January 2015|date=15 July 2014}}</ref>  Celtic eased to a 4\u20130 win in the return match in Scotland,<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 4-0 KR Reykjavik (agg 5-0)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28331345|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 August 2014|date=22 July 2014}}</ref> but were comprehensively beaten and outplayed in the next qualifying round, losing 6\u20131 on aggregate to [[Legia Warsaw]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28656118 |accessdate=1 August 2014 |title=Celtic 0 - 2 Legia Warsaw |date=6 August 2014 |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont}}</ref>  Despite this, Celtic were given a reprieve when it was discovered that Legia had fielded an ineligible player in the second leg, [[Bartosz Bereszy\u0144ski]] coming on as a substitute in the last four minutes. UEFA punished the Polish club by awarding the game 3\u20130 to Celtic, levelling the aggregate score at 4\u20134 and seeing the Scottish champions progress on away goals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic reinstated to Champions League after Uefa punishes Legia Warsaw|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/aug/08/celtic-reinstated-champions-league-uefa-legia-warsaw|work=The Guardian|accessdate=8 August 2014|date=8 August 2014}}</ref> Despite this astonishing piece of luck, Celtic failed abjectly to take advantage in the final qualifier against [[NK Maribor|Maribor]], losing 2\u20131 on aggregate to drop down to the Europa League.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic 0 - 1 NK Maribor|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28927666|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 August 2014|date=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:FC Salzburg gegen Celtic Glasgow 33.JPG|thumb|left|350px|Celtic in action away to [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] during the group stage of their [[UEFA Europa League]] campaign in 2014.]]\nCeltic were unconvincing in the early stages of the league as well,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronny Deila looking for revenge as Celtic travel to Motherwell|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11787/9593890/scottish-premiership-ronny-deila-looking-for-revenge-as-celtic-travel-to-motherwell|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=6 December 2014}}</ref> but improved as the season progressed and also qualified from their Europa League group.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic 1 - 3 FC Red Bull Salzburg|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30204414|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=27 November 2014}}</ref> Deila won the Manager of the Month award for November 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronny Deila is manager of the month for November|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30334346|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=7 December 2014}}</ref>  By February 2015, Celtic had won 15 of their last 17 domestic games<ref>{{cite web|last=McGarry|first=John|title=Ronny Deila admits first few months as Celtic manager were 'tough to handle'|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2943417/Ronny-Deila-admits-months-Celtic-manager-tough-handle.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=7 February 2015}}</ref> and comfortably defeated Rangers 2\u20130 in the semi-final of the League Cup.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=Ewan|title=Celtic push past feeble Rangers in first Old Firm game for three years|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/feb/01/celtic-rangers-scottish-league-cup-semi-final|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 February 2015|date=1 February 2015}}</ref> Celtic played [[Inter Milan]] in the round of 16 stage of the Europa League, rallying to draw 3\u20133 at Parkhead from an early 0\u20132 deficit in a pulsating encounter,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fosyth|first=Roddy|title=Celtic 3 Inter Milan 3, match report: John Guidetti scores last-gasp equaliser to keep hosts alive in tie|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/celtic/11423375/Celtic-3-Inter-Milan-3-match-report-John-Guidetti-scores-last-gasp-equaliser-to-keep-hosts-alive-in-tie.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=19 February 2015}}</ref> then losing 1\u20130 in [[Milan]] to go out on aggregate despite a highly credible performance.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mullen|first1=Scott|title=Inter 1 Celtic 0 (agg: 4-3): Hoops exit Europe after Guarin's wonder strike|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/celtic/inter-1-celtic-0-agg-4-3-hoops-exit-europe-after-guarins-wonder-strike-198656n.119510154|work=Evening Times|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=26 February 2015}}</ref> In the league, Celtic thrashed second-placed Aberdeen 4\u20130 on 1 March to go six points clear with a game in hand and a vastly superior goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic win is important mental lift - Ronny Deila|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31685655|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=1 March 2015}}</ref> It was Celtic's eighth consecutive win in the league, and the turn around in form saw previous critics of Deila review their opinion of him.  Former Celtic striker [[John Hartson]] had branded Deila as \"clueless\" in October, but now stated that Deila has \"..turned it round to his credit and they\u2019re playing some brilliant football at the moment\".<ref>{{cite web|last=MacArthur|first=Scott|title=Celtic legend John Hartson: \"I was wrong about Ronny Deila & Celts can lift The Treble\"|url=http://www.talkingbaws.com/2015/03/02/celtic-legend-john-hartson-i-was-wrong-about-ronny-deila-celts-can-lift-the-treble/|work=Talking Baws|accessdate=3 March 2015|date=2 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:One final Ronny Roar (26998950046).jpg|thumb|right|200px|Deila celebrating winning the 2015\u201316 Scottish Premiership league title in May 2016]]\nIn March 2015, Celtic agreed a new kit deal with [[Boston]]-based sportswear manufacturer [[New Balance]] to replace [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] from the start of the 2015\u201316 season.  It is believed to be the biggest kit contract in the club's history, outdoing the decade-long deal with Nike who paid Celtic \u00a35&nbsp;million a year to make their shirts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic confirm kit deal with New Balance|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/celtic-confirm-kit-deal-with-new-balance-1-3710125|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=5 March 2015|date=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nDeila won his first trophy at Celtic on 15 March; Celtic's defeating Dundee United 2\u20130 in the [[2015 Scottish League Cup Final|League Cup final]]. Kris Commons opened the scoring in the first half and James Forrest steered the ball into the net from 20 yards out to double Celtic's lead in the second half.<ref>{{cite web|last=McGowan|first=Stephen|title=Dundee United 0-2 Celtic: Kris Commons and James Forrest land The Bhoys QTS Scottish League Cup to keep treble dreams alive|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2996008/Dundee-United-0-2-Celtic-Kris-Commons-James-Forrest-land-Bhoys-QTS-Scottish-League-Cup-treble-dreams-alive.html|work=Mail Online|accessdate=16 March 2015|date=15 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Dundee Utd 0 - 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31785677|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 March 2015|date=15 March 2015}}</ref>  Celtic's bid for a domestic treble ended when they were beaten by Inverness Caledonian Thistle in the [[2014\u201315 Scottish Cup|semi-final of the Scottish Cup]] on 19 April 2015.  The match however was controversial, with Inverness defender [[Josh Meekings]]' deliberate handball of Leigh Griffiths' goal-bound header just before half-time going unpunished by the match officials.  Insult was added to injury in the second half when Craig Gordon was sent off (correctly) for fouling [[Marley Watkins]] in the penalty box.  [[Greg Tansey]] converted the resultant penalty to level the tie at 1\u20131. Down to ten men, Celtic struggled for the rest of the match and eventually lost 3\u20132 after extra-time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Inverness CT 3 - 2 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32089585|date=19 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic boss says referee mistake is hard to take in Cup semi-final|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32373912|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 April 2015|date=19 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nCeltic clinched their fourth successive league title in May,<ref name=\"ltit15\">{{cite web|title=Celtic win Scottish Premiership title after Aberdeen lose|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32566809|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 May 2015|date=2 May 2015}}</ref> with manager Deila commenting \"We've had a terrific few months - we deserved to win the league.\"<ref name=\"ltit15\" />\n\n===2015\u201316===\nCeltic began the season again attempting to qualify for the Champions League.  They knocked out [[Stjarnan]] from Iceland<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindsay|first=Clive|title=Stjarnan 1 - 4 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33609346|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=22 July 2015 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> and [[Qaraba\u011f FK|Qaraba\u011f]] from Azerbaijan in the early qualifying rounds,<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=FK Qarabag 0 - 0 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33755230|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=5 August 2015}}</ref> but lost 4\u20133 on aggregate to Swedish side [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] in the final play-off round. This meant for the second successive season, Celtic dropped in to the Europa League.<ref name=\"el1516\">{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=Malmo 2 - 0 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34047527|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 August 2015|date=25 August 2015}}</ref> Celtic's Europa League campaign was poor and littered with individual errors which contributed to dropped points in every match.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lamont|first1=Alasdair|title=Fenerbah\u00e7e 1 - 1 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35020011|accessdate=12 February 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=10 December 2015}}</ref> Celtic failed to qualify, finishing bottom of their group, and was the first time Celtic went through a group stage of a European competition without recording a single victory.<ref name=\"el1516\" />\n\nDeila was criticised for Celtic's poor European campaign,<ref>{{cite news|last=Lindsay|first=Matthew|title=Pat Bonner: Ronny Deila must make wins his priority in Europe - not playing \"the Celtic way\" |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/14098141.Pat_Bonner__Ronny_Deila_must_make_wins_his_priority_in_Europe___not_playing__quot_the_Celtic_way_quot_/|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=Herald Scotland|date=23 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Berry|first=Gavin|title=Former Celtic stopper Marc Rieper: Sorry Tom, Ronny Deila has been a disaster in Europe and that is the ONLY stage that counts|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-celtic-stopper-marc-rieper-7347464#eb0C2akBl6oibkHP.97|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=Daily Record|date=11 February 2016}}</ref> and a series of indifferent performances in the league saw him placed under further scrutiny.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cameron|first=Neil|title=Ronny Deila pleads for calm but will he become the first Celtic manager going for a Double to be sacked?|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14251493.Ronny_Deila_pleads_for_calm_but_will_he_become_the_first_Celtic_manager_going_for_a_Double_to_be_sacked_/|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=Herald Scotland|date=4 February 2016}}</ref> In April 2016, Celtic suffered a 5\u20134 loss on penalties to Old Firm rivals Rangers in the semi-final of the Scottish Cup, after a 2\u20132 extra-time draw in which Celtic fought back against the newly promoted [[Scottish Championship|Championship]] side twice to level the score.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Rangers 2 Celtic 2: Rangers triumph 5-4 in epic penalty shootout to reach Scottish Cup final|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/17/rangers-2-celtic-2-rangers-triumph-5-4-in-epic-penalty-shootout/|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Telegraph|date=17 April 2016}}</ref> Three days later, Deila announced his resignation from his post once Celtic had finished the season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fowler|first=Craig|title=Ronny Deila to leave Celtic at the end of the season|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/ronny-deila-to-leave-celtic-at-the-end-of-the-season-1-4105304|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=20 April 2016}}</ref> Nevertheless, Deila led Celtic to their fifth consecutive League championship, clinching the title on 8 May with a 3&ndash;2 win over nearest challengers Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Celtic clinch Scottish Premiership title with victory over Aberdeen|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/05/08/celtic-clinch-scottish-premiership-title-with-victory-over-aberd/|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Telegraph|date=8 May 2016}}</ref> Celtic finished the season a week later with an emphatic 7\u20130 win over Motherwell, seeing Deila depart the club on a high note after two years in charge. The seventh goal in that game was scored by debutant [[Jack Aitchison]], who at 16 years and 71 days old became both the youngest player ever to represent the club in a competitive match and the youngest goalscorer.<ref name=\"aitch\">{{cite news|last=Hamouda|first=Omar|title=Jack Aitchison becomes Celtic\u2019s youngest ever goalscorer|url=http://www.squawka.com/news/jack-aitchison-becomes-celtics-youngest-ever-goalscorer/670677|accessdate=15 May 2016|work=Squawka|date=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jack Aitchison|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2015/teams/player=250081673/index.html|website=UEFA.com|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Celtic had been generally mediocre, striker [[Leigh Griffiths]] had an outstanding season, scoring 40 goals and winning both the [[PFA Scotland Players' Player of the Year|PFA Scotland]] and [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers' Association]] Player of the Year awards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic striker Leigh Griffiths wins Scottish Premiership Player of the Season|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11787/10301127/celtic-striker-leigh-griffiths-wins-scottish-premiership-player-of-the-season|accessdate=19 November 2016|work=Sky Sports|date=1 June 2016}}</ref> The season also saw 18 year old [[Kieran Tierney]] emerge as one of the most promising prospects in Scottish football, establishing himself as first-choice left-back at Celtic and making his full international debut for Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Andrew|title=No place like home for Celtic\u2019s Kieran Tierney|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/competitions/premiership/no-place-like-home-for-celtic-s-kieran-tierney-1-4128153|accessdate=19 November 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Brendan Rodgers (2016\u2013present) ==\n[[File:Celtic FC rail seating section.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Rail seating at Celtic Park]]\nOn 20 May 2016, it was confirmed that 43-year-old [[Brendan Rodgers]] would take over at the club with immediate effect, the Irishman having previously managed [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] and Liverpool in the English Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36338244 |title=Celtic: Brendan Rodgers is appointed manager |work=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2016 |accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> In the days that followed, Chris Davies was named as assistant manager<ref name=\"brasst\">{{cite news|title=Celtic name Chris Davies as Brendan Rodgers' assistant|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36380828|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=25 May 2016}}</ref> and Glen Driscoll appointed as head of performance.<ref name=\"brhop\">{{cite news|title=Celtic appoint Glen Driscoll, who worked with Brendan Rodgers at Liverpool and Swansea, as new head of performance|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3613084/Celtic-appoint-Glen-Driscoll-worked-Brendan-Rodgers-Liverpool-Swansea-new-head-performance.html|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Mail Online|date=27 May 2016}}</ref> Both men had previously worked with Rodgers at Swansea and Liverpool.<ref name=\"brasst\" /><ref name=\"brhop\" />\n\n[[File:Cel-Zen (12) (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|300px|alt=Photograph of Brendan Rodgers|[[Brendan Rodgers]] led Celtic to two consecutive [[domestic treble]]s]]On 14 July 2016, Celtic formally unveiled their new 2,600 capacity \"[[Safe standing#Rail seats|rail seating]]\" area within Celtic Park, becoming the first British club to do so. The club had obtained a \"[[safe standing]]\" certificate 13 months earlier after years of negotiations with supporters, football authorities and Glasgow City Council. Rail seating is particularly common in Germany's Bundesliga, most notably at Borussia Dortmund's [[Westfalenstadion]], a ground with a reputation on par with Celtic Park for its intensity and atmosphere.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/scottish-premier/celtic/271667-celtic-studying-feasibility-of-standing-area-at-celtic-park/ |title=Celtic studying feasibility of standing area at Celtic Park |work=STV Sport |date=23 September 2011 |accessdate=13 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Spencer|title=Celtic become first British club to introduce safe-standing after completing construction ahead of Brendan Rodgers' first home game|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3690004/Celtic-British-club-introduce-safe-standing-completing-construction-ahead-Brendan-Rodgers-home-game.html?ITO=1490|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Mail Online|date=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic secure green light for rail seating|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/8420|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=Celtic FC|date=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stevens|first1=Samuel|title=Celtic reveal new 2,600 capacity safe-standing area with Brendan Rodgers set for first home match as manager|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/celtic-reveal-new-2600-capacity-safe-standing-area-with-brendan-rodgers-set-for-first-home-match-as-a7136581.html|accessdate=26 July 2016|work=The Independent|date=14 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016&ndash;17===\nCeltic's first competitive match under Rodgers, saw the team [[Lincoln Red Imps 1\u20130 Celtic|lose 1&ndash;0]] against [[Gibraltar|Gibraltan]] minnows [[Lincoln Red Imps F.C.|Lincoln Red Imps]] in the first leg of the Second Round Champions League qualifiers, a result described by ''The Scotsman'' as a \"humiliation\" and mooted by other media as being one of the worst results in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lincoln Red Imps 1 - 0 Celtic: Stunning upset in Rodgers\u2019 first match|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/lincoln-red-imps-1-0-celtic-stunning-upset-in-rodgers-first-match-1-4175957|accessdate=30 July 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=12 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cameron|first=Neil|title=Lincoln Red Imps 1, Celtic 0: The Brendan Rodgers era begins with what could easily be seen as the club's worst ever result|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/14614532.Lincoln_Red_Imps_1__Celtic_0__The_Brendan_Rodgers_era_begins_with_what_could_easily_be_seen_as_the_club__39_s_worst_ever_result/|accessdate=30 July 2016|work=Herald Scotland|date=12 July 2016}}</ref> Celtic quickly found their feet though, winning the second leg 3&ndash;0 and going on to eliminate [[FC Astana|Astana]] and [[Hapoel Be'er Sheva F.C|Hapoel Be'er Sheva]] in the subsequent qualifying rounds to progress into the Champions League group stages for the first time since 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=English|first=Tom|title=Celtic 2 - 1 FC Astana 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36955619|accessdate=13 September 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=3 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Esplin|first=Ronnie|title=Celtic vs Hapoel Be'er Sheva: Brendan Rodgers praises major shareholder after surviving Champions League scare|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/celtic-vs-hapoel-beer-sheva-brendan-rodgers-praises-major-shareholder-after-surviving-champions-a7206711.html|accessdate=13 September 2016|work=The Independent|date=24 August 2016}}</ref> Celtic's new signings [[Scott Sinclair]] and [[Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 (French footballer)|Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9]] also helped the club make a strong start to their league campaign, with Sinclair scoring in each of the first six league matches<ref>{{cite news|title=Scott Sinclair scores again as Celtic thrash Kilmarnock|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/24/celtic-kilmarnock-scottish-premiership-match-report|accessdate=5 June 2017|work=The Guardian|date=24 September 2017}}</ref> and Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 scoring a hat-trick in Celtic's 5&ndash;1 win over newly promoted Rangers, becoming the first Celtic player to score three goals against Rangers since [[Harry Hood (footballer)|Harry Hood]] in 1973.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/14738379.Harry_Hood__I_spent_five_hours_in_hospital__missed_the_game_and_came_out_to_discover_my_Old_Firm_hat_trick_record_had_gone/ |work=Herald Scotland |title=Harry Hood: I spent five hours in hospital, missed the game and came out to discover my Old Firm hat-trick record had gone |first=Lindsay |last=Herron |date=13 September 2016 |accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20170701 SK Rapid Wien vs Celtic FC 1548.jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Scott Sinclair]], one of Brendan Rodger's new signings, scored in each of Celtic's first six league matches of the season, and finished as top goalscorer in the Scottish Premiership]]The team's opening match in the Champions League on 13 September 2016 proved to be a humbling experience though as Barcelona delivered a footballing lesson in a 7&ndash;0 rout, the club's heaviest ever European defeat and the second-heaviest in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news|last=English|first=Tom|title=Barcelona 7 - 0 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37331224|accessdate=14 September 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=13 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alltime club records|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/club_records_overall.php|website=FitbaStats|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> A level of pride was restored in the next Champions League tie, Celtic holding [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] to a 3&ndash;3 draw at Celtic Park and ending the high-spending English club's run of ten consecutive wins, with Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 scoring twice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Daniel|title=Celtic end Manchester City\u2019s winning run with thrilling Champions League draw|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/28/celtic-manchester-city-champions-league-match-report|accessdate=19 November 2016|work=The Guardian|date=28 September 2016}}</ref> Further draws away at [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] and in the return match at Manchester City saw Celtic finish the group on three points, albeit coming fourth and going out of Europe.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic: Brendan Rodgers says Champions League campaign 'sets standard'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38228840|accessdate=13 February 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nCeltic continued their unbeaten run in domestic competitions into the New Year,<ref>{{cite news|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|title=Celtic 4 Hearts 0: Brendan Rodgers' side break unbeaten record set by Lisbon Lions in ruthless fashion|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/01/29/celtic-4-hearts-0-brendan-rodgers-side-break-unbeaten-record/|accessdate=13 February 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=29 January 2017}}</ref> during which time the club won their 100th major trophy, defeating Aberdeen 3\u20130 in the League Cup Final on 27 November 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=League Cup final: Aberdeen 0-3 Celtic as it happened|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/scotland/38121946|accessdate=1 December 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=27 November 2016}}</ref> Celtic's 5&ndash;2 win away at St Johnstone on 5 February 2017 saw them extend their lead in the league to 27 points over second-placed Aberdeen, and was their 19th consecutive league win,<ref>{{cite news|title=Dembele hits hat-trick as Celtic fight back to maintain run|url=https://stv.tv/sport/football/1379967-dembele-hits-hat-trick-as-celtic-fight-back-to-maintain-run/|accessdate=14 February 2017|work=STV Sport|date=5 February 2017}}</ref> with the only points dropped in the season so far being in a 2&ndash;2 draw away at Inverness in September.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic: Brendan Rodgers still 'rankled' by draw with Inverness|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37864056|accessdate=14 February 2017|date=3 November 2016}}</ref> They continued undefeated through March, going to extend their winning run to 22 consecutive league games, although dropped points in a 1&ndash;1 draw at Parkhead against Rangers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic 1 - 1 Rangers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39170663|accessdate=25 April 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=12 March 2017}}</ref> Celtic clinched their sixth successive league title on 2 April 2017, with a record eight league games to spare.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic's title triumph by numbers|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39330673|accessdate=4 April 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=2 April 2017}}</ref> As Celtic's unbeaten domestic run continued, they subjected Rangers to their heaviest defeat at Ibrox since 1915, thrashing their rivals 5&ndash;1 on 29 April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Forsyth|first=Roddy|last2=Stafford|first2=James|title=Rangers 1 Celtic 5: Home side humbled in record defeat|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/04/29/rangers-vs-celtic-old-firm-derby-live-score-updates/|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=29 April 2017|date=29 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alltime records|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/club_records_overall.php|website=FitbaStats|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716204124/http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/club_records_overall.php|archivedate=16 July 2015}}</ref> Celtic's 2&ndash;0 win over Hearts on 21 May saw them finish 30 points ahead of second-placed Aberdeen in the league, win a record 106 points, and the team become the first Scottish side to complete a top-flight season undefeated since 1899.<ref>{{cite news|last=Campbell|first=Andy|title=Celtic 2 - 0 Hearts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39911911|accessdate=22 May 2017|work=BBC Sport|date=21 May 2017}}</ref> On 27 May 2017, Celtic clinched their fourth treble by defeating Aberdeen 2-1 in the Scottish Cup final, with [[Tom Rogic]] scoring the winning goal in injury time. The cup final win saw Celtic go through the entire domestic season unbeaten.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39984102 |work=BBC Sport |date=27 May 2016 |accessdate=28 May 2016 |first=Tom |last=English |title=Celtic 2 - 1 Aberdeen}}</ref>\n\n===2017&ndash;18===\n\nCeltic entered the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League]] at the 2nd qualifying round, they defeated [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]] 6\u20130, [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] 1\u20130 and [[FC Astana|Astana]] 8\u20134 on aggregate to enter the group stages.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic 4 Linfield 0|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39330673|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=19 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rosenborg 0 Celtic 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40732241|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=2 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Astana 4 Celtic 3|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40997756|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=22 August 2017}}</ref> Celtic achieved only 3 points over the six games, but did win 3\u20130 away at [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]], their first group stages (Champions League and [[Europa League]]) win in 16 games. Celtic finished the group in third place despite losing 5\u20130 (at home) and 7\u20131 (away) to [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint Germain]].<ref>{{cite news|title=RSC Anderlecht 0 Celtic 3|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41372730|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=22 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Paris St-Germain 7 Celtic 1|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42056051|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2017, Celtic won their fourth consecutive domestic trophy, for the first time since Jock Stein's side in 1970, with a 2\u20130 win against Motherwell in the Scottish League Cup final.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42056522|title=Motherwell 0 Celtic 2|date=26 November 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> Celtic set the British record for consecutive unbeaten domestic games at 69, beating their own record of 62 set by Willie Maley's side in 1917, before finally losing 4\u20130 to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]. Over 585 days, Celtic won 60 of those 69 games, drawing the other 9, with 197 goals scored and 38 clean sheets in the process. Brendan Rodgers said of his Celtic team after the loss to Hearts, that \"They've set a record that may well never be beaten\".<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42297312|title=Heart of Midlothian 4 Celtic 0|date=17 December 2017|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy finishing third in the Champions League group stages, Celtic qualified for the knockout round of 32 in the [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] where they were drawn against [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]]. Celtic won the first leg 1\u20130 after a late winner by [[Callum McGregor]], but succumbed to a disappointing 3\u20130 defeat in Saint Petersburg and were subsequently knocked out of the competition.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43136856|title=Zenit St Petersburg 3 Celtic 0|date=22 February 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 April 2018, Celtic secured their seventh consecutive league title with a 5\u20130 win over Rangers at Celtic Park. This win also extended Celtic's unbeaten run over Rangers to 12 games.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43854076|title=Celtic 5 Rangers 0|date=29 April 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> Celtic's season ended on 19 May 2018 when they secured the first ever 'Double-Treble' (a treble in two consecutive seasons) in Scottish football history with a 2\u20130 Scottish Cup Final win over Motherwell.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44091573|title=Celtic 2\u20130 Motherwell|date=19 May 2018|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Celtic F.C. (1887\u20131994)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.celticfc.net Official club website]\n*[http://www.thecelticwiki.com/ TheCelticWiki]\n*[http://www.celtic-stream.net/ Celtic Fan Network]\n\n{{Celtic F.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Celtic F.C.}}\n[[Category:Celtic F.C.|History 1994-present]]\n[[Category:History of association football clubs in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2-1 \u2192 2\u20131, 2000-01 \u2192 2000\u201301", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Celtic_F.C._(1994%E2%80%93present)"}
